<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Amnesty-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru a0816 09-08 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0816,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Asked To Act For Iraqi Kurds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Kurdish leader saying
fighting continues in Iraq. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said on Thursday that it has
appealed to the United Nations Security Council to ``act
immediately to stop the massacre of Kurdish civilians by Iraqi
forces.''
   Meanwhile, the leader of the Kurdish rebels said that Iraqi
government troops are still attacking guerrillas and civilians in
northern Iraq despite the government's amnesty offer.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human rights
organization, said in a statement that it made its first direct
appeal on Wednesday night to the 15-member U.N. body in New York
because the ``systematic and deliberate'' killings ``call out for
immediate action by the Security Council.''
   The statement charged Iraq wants to punish the Kurds for their
political sympathies and in retaliation for opposition Kurdish
activities. More than 100,000 Iraqi Kurds fled across the border to
Turkey and many of them gave consistent accounts of the use of
chemical weapons, the statement said.
   Amnesty last week accused Iraq of killing hundreds of Kurdish
villagers with chemical weapons in mountainous northern Iraq and of
employing helicopter gunships, tanks and artillery in Duhok, Mosul
and Arbil provinces.
   Iraq's ambassador to Britain, Mohammed Sadiq al-Mashat, denied
chemical weapons were used. He was summoned to the Foreign Office
in London on Tuesday and was told of British concern over the large
numbers of Kurdish refugees and the reports of chemical weapons use.
   The latest Amnesty statement gave a qualified welcome to the
Iraqi amnesty for Kurds, saying it received reports in the past of
Kurds being imprisoned and executed after responding to previous
amnesties.
   Massoud Barzani, president of the Kurdistan Democratic Party,
said in a telex sent to The Associated Press office in Cyprus on
Wednesday that the Kurds will not accept the general amnesty
offered by Iraq the day before.
   ``The Kurds have not struggled to be pardoned but to acheive
their national and democratic rights within autonomy,'' Barzani
said. ``Our struggle will continue until these goals are
fulfilled.''
   Iraq launched the offensive against the Kurdish rebels after a
cease-fire in its eight-year war with Iran went into effect Aug.
20. Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds have been struggling on and off for 50
years for an autonomous homeland.
   The Kurdistan Democratic Party has said that nearly 2,000
civilians have been killed and another 5,000 injured, many by
chemical weapons.
   In his statement Wednesday, Barzani said the amnesty offer was
an attempt by Iraq to deflect attention from its use of chemical
weapons.
</TEXT>
