<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NorthKorea-40Years Bjt   09-08 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Korea-40 Years, Bjt,0907</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Marks 40th Anniversary In Troubled Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four decades after its founding, North Korea
remains an isolated, secretive state with an enigmatic leader who
shows no signs of handing over power to his designated heir _ his
son.
   The Democratic People's Republic of Korea celebrates its 40th
anniversary Friday with praise for President Kim Il Sung, 76, the
communist strongman.
   The country plans a huge celebration, with senior foreign
emissaries including President Yang Shangkun of China and Soviet
KGB chief Viktor Chebrikov representing North Korea's two major
allies.
   No political figures or journalists from the West have been
invited, and requests from Western news agencies to cover the
anniversary have gone unanswered. North Korea rarely allows Western
journalists into the country.
   The ceremonies Friday will include a mass rally, a sports
competition and cultural performances in praise of Kim.
   ``Koreans respect Kim Il Sung as a prominent leader in
anti-Japanese warfare and hero of the Korean revolution,'' said
Choe Kwan Ick, an official of the pro-North Korean General
Association of Korean Residents of Japan (Chongryon). ``He goes to
every corner of the country, among farmers and workers, to solve
problems they face. The people respect this, and that is why he has
remained in power so long.''
   A 1986 U.S. State Department report called Kim ``the object of
an intensive and far-reaching personality cult, probably unequalled
in the rest of today's world.''
   Huge statues of the Great Leader, as Kim is known, stand
throughout the country and almost all North Koreans wear badges
with his picture.
   Similar public loyalty to Kim's son Kim Jong Il, 46, is
encouraged. The elder Kim plans to hand power over to his son in
what may be the world's first communist dynasty.
   It has been a troubling year for North Korea. World attention
has focused on rival South Korea and on the upcoming Olympic Games,
which begin in Seoul Sept. 17. South Korea has stressed security
preparations against a possible terrorist attack from the north.
   North Korea finally stated this week that it would not use
military or other means to interrupt the Olympics.
   ``As for `terrorism,' it is utterly alien to us and the United
States itself is the chieftain of state terrorism as already
exposed to the world,'' the North Korean Foreign Ministry said.
   Tension remains high along the Demilitarized Zone with North
Korea's deployment of Soviet-made missiles and jet fighters,
including MiG-23s and MiG-29s. The North has an estimated 850,000
troops _ the world's fifth largest army _ against 650,000 South
Korean and 42,000 American soldiers.
   North Korea failed in its attempt to share in the glory of the
Olympics, and is now watching allies China, Yugoslavia, Hungary and
probably Poland establish trade relations with Seoul.
   Eclipsed by South Korea in industry and foreign trade, the
country faces two formidable tasks: ensuring a smooth transfer of
power and modernizing its economy.
   The country has a foreign debt of about $4.2 billion against
foreign trade of only $3.5 billion annually, according to Western
estimates. Last year,North Korea was declared in default on its
foreign loans.
   Trade is modest, amounting to only $1.7 billion annually with
the Soviet Union, North Korea's largest trading partner and main
economic benefactor.
   ``They (North Korea) import machinery and vehicles, but lack
parts and skill and can't get them repaired,'' a Japanese
intelligence official said.
   To earn badly needed foreign currency, North Korea is on a
building spree of luxury hotels and sports and cultural facilities,
but ``they're building everything literally by hand, with shovels
and wheelbarrows,'' the official said.
   ``It reminds me of Japan in the 1950s,'' said Masaru Nishida, a
literature professor at Tokyo's Hosei University who has visited
the country three times.
   Strapped for cash, North Korea has been shifting some of the 20
percent of its GNP currently spent on the military to joint
ventures with the Soviet Union, according to the Japanese official.
The products include household goods, clothing, shoes and are sold
in Siberia.
   ``North Korea wants to cut down military expenditures because
they're a waste of money,'' said Choe. Authorities have demobilized
200,000 soldiers in the last two years and shifted them to economic
reconstruction, he said.
   How to solidify the political position of Kim's son is a more
delicate issue. Little is known about Kim Jong Il, but he clearly
lacks the charisma of his father, the Japanese official said.
   Kim Pyong Il, 34, Kim Jong Il's half-brother, has been posted as
ambassador to Hungary in an apparent move to avoid a challenge to
Kim Jong Il, the official said.
   A major question is when Kim Il Sung will abdicate in favor of
his son _ or be forced to for health reasons. During a visit to
Mongolia in July, he had difficulty climbing slopes and once
abandoned an attempt to enter a pavillion because he could not
negotiate the stairs, the Japanese official said.
   ``Kim Il Sung wants quickly to give reins to his son,'' the
official said. ``But the domestic situation doesn't allow that
right now.'' He said Moscow and Beijing had been pressuring Kim not
to put his son in power yet because they do not have complete
confidence in him.
</TEXT>
