<DOCNO> AP880908-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JonesClub     09-08 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jones Club,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Barnaby Jones' Club Thrives, To Delight Of Buddy Ebsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't try to tell Joe Camerada about Madonna,
Tom Selleck or Elvis. He's got his own idol: Barnaby Jones.
   ``I just like his easygoing style,'' Camerada says.
   Camerada is not alone. He is one of more than 800 members of the
Barnaby Jones Fan Club, dedicated to the memory of the venerable
detective who ambled across the nation's television screens from
1973 to 1980, and in countless reruns.
   Unlike most fan clubs, the members of this one actually get to
meet their idol regularly. Buddy Ebsen, who played Jones, is a
frequent guest at the club's weekly meetings at a restaurant off
Times Square.
   ``It's a cult now,'' says Ebsen, 80. ``I love them. They're
great guys.''
   The great guys are mostly retired executives, men of Ebsen's own
generation. They include former President Richard M. Nixon, a fan
of the show who joined the club at Ebsen's suggestion.
   This fan club collects no dues, sells nothing, follows no rules
and only loosely organizes an occasional golf outing. ``It is
instantaneous. You walk in and you're a member,'' said member Joe
Desimone, 57.
   ``It really was a sincere, grass-roots germination,'' Ebsen said.
   President Alfred Lamberti said the club started some years ago
when a retired Army colonel was hospitalized for an operation. Each
day, the patient watched Barnaby Jones reruns, and soon he and his
visitors were hooked.
   Thereafter, they met for lunch or drinks each week. They would
send Ebsen birthday cards each year. His curiosity was piqued, and
one day he dropped in to La Vert-Galant, official meeting place of
the BJFC.
   Now, whenever he's in town, Ebsen is a regular. And when he
shows up, the bartender whips up an alcoholic drink that looks like
the favored drink of the club's favorite detective _ a glass of
milk.
   The meetings are not like Trekkie conventions _ there are no
trivia contests, with questions of what color tie Barnaby wore in
episode 33; there is no swap meet of Barnaby memorabilia.
   Mostly, the guys talk about sex, fights, baseball and dirty
jokes.
   ``It's like a family,'' said Gordon McKay, 60.
   The club has attracted Ebsen lookalikes and a Scottish man who,
like Jones, drank only milk. There are members in Ireland,
California and Florida.
   Then there was the visit from Nixon. Ebsen, who is on the board
of directors of Nixon's library, said he recruited Nixon into the
club when Nixon asked him why the Barnaby Jones private detective
show was taken off the air in New York and how he could help get it
back on.
   Now, said Ebsen, ``He's a card-carrying member.''
   When Nixon stopped by, more than 40 members gathered at the
restaurant and listened to plenty of behind-the-scenes stuff, as
Lamberti recalls.
   ``He was going to stay a half hour but he stayed two hours,'' he
said. ``He told us things about Washington that I can't tell you.
He said of all the clubs he ever went to this was the greatest
because there was no ulterior motive.''
   Nixon also figured in another big moment in club history _ the
time members rented a yacht and followed Ebsen in a race around
Staten Island.
   ``I had a Richard Nixon mask on,'' Lamberti said, with a chuckle.
   Ebsen said he recalls racing in the Liberty Regatta. There,
tagging along behind him, was a yacht bearing a large banner.
   ``Go Barnaby,'' the sign said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
