<DOCNO> AP880908-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NobelCandidates     09-08 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nobel Candidates,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ninety-Seven Candidates For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Norwegian Nobel Committee says it will
choose this year's Nobel Peace Prize laureate from 97 candidates,
including 74 people and 23 organizations.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
reportedly are in the running for their agreement to dismantle
intermediate range nuclear missiles.
   Jakob Sverdrup, secretary of the five-member committee, said
Wednesday that the winner will be announced Sept. 29 by chairman
Egil Aarvik.
   The number of approved candidates is close to the all-time
record of 100. Last year, President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica was
chosen from among 93 candidates for his Central American peace plan.
   The committee refuses to confirm the names of candidates.
Nominations for the 1988 prize closed on Feb. 1
   Speculation has focused on United Nations' General Secretary
Javier Perez de Cuellar, who reportedly was nominated for the 1989
prize by Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany
for his efforts to end the Iran-Iraq and Afghanistan wars.
   A Norwegian member of parliament has said he has proposed
President Cory Aquino for her efforts for a peaceful tranisition in
the Philippines.
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland of Norway reportedly was
nominated for her U.N.-appointed work on drafting a program for
environment and development.
   Other unconfirmed nominations were jailed black anti-apartheid
leader Nelson Mandela of South Africa, and Indian Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi.
   Members of Finland's parliament reportedly have nominated the
World Health Organization (WHO) celebrating its 40th anniversary
this year, and Swedish parliamentarians proposed the Rev. Joseph
Ingle of the Nashville-based Southern Coalition on Jails and
Prisons, who campaigns against the death penalty.
   This prize is worth about $385,000, up 15 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
