<DOCNO> AP880908-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MurderousRelic     09-08 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murderous Relic,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Case Made of Murderer's Skin Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOWLE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A visiting-card case made from the skin
of executed 19th century mass murderer William Burke was bought at
auction for $1,785 by a man whose business takes tourists to the
scenes of notorious crimes.
   ``The price was much more than Burke and William Hare, his
accomplice, received for all the bodies of their victims, which
they sold to anatomists,'' said Robin Mitchell, who bought the
relic in a sale at Knowle in central England.
   Burke and Hare, who began as grave-robbers, went on to murder at
least 15 people in Edinburgh in 1827 and 1828, a time when medical
professors could not get enough bodies for demonstrations to their
students.
   Burke was hanged in 1829 on the evidence of Hare, who fled the
city and disappeared.
   Burke's body was flayed after dissection by Edinburgh's medical
authorities and part of his skin was used by one of those surgeons
to make the ornate case with gold tooling which passed to his
descendant _ who sold it Wednesday.
   A notebook covered in Burke's skin is still in the possession of
Edinburgh's Royal College of Surgeons.
   Mitchell is a partner in an Edinburgh guide business, which
takes tourists to the scenes of notorious crimes.
   ``We will be showing the case to our clients on the tours,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
