<HEAD>Radio Accord Reached Between Paris and Beijing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paris and Beijing have signed an accord for the
joint production of some radio programs and the cooperation between
radio correspondents in the two countries, French radio reported.
   The accord was signed Wednesday by Roland Faure, president of
Radio France, and Yang Zhengquan, director general of China's
Popular Central Radio.
   Under the agreement, the two radio networks will co-produce an
anthology of traditional Chinese music and other programs. Radio
reporters will receive technical assistance in the country they are
covering and radio trainees will be exchanged, the radio reported.
   The report said the exchange was timed to allow French radio to
carry reports on the 40th anniversary of the founding of Communist
China and for Chinese radio to broadcast reports on the celebration
of the bicentennial of the French Revolution, events that will take
place next year.
</TEXT>
