<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-08 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARKSPUR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quiba, Jamal, Zubag, Kubla Khan and six
pals give new meaning to the expression ``dog's life.''
   Every canine should be as lucky as the 10 silky Salukis who
share a posh Marin County doghouse with color television, art
gallery and raised beds with white fur blankets.
   ``I just thoroughly love them,'' Sandra Wornum said Wednesday of
her pampered purebreds.
   Wornum built the $15,000 enclosed kennels partly to appease
neighbors, who complain about noise and worry about property
values, but also out of devotion to her thin, elegant hounds,
believed to be the world's oldest breed.
   The carpeted dog home designed by Wornum's architect husband,
Michael, also features four redwood-and-glass bedrooms and a
bathroom with a Moroccan tile shower and claw-footed bathtub.
   Salukis, which resemble greyhounds, were developed in the Middle
East as early as 4000 B.C. for hunting gazelles. Wornum, like other
lovers of the breed, say their animals are delightfully different
from other dogs.
   ``Their demeanor is much more like a cat,'' she said. ``They are
reserved, quiet, intense. They like to sit up high and observe.
They are not ground sleepers.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baggage handler may keep the $10,000 he
found at Greater Pittsburgh International Airport, authorities say.
But his wife says she still feels bad for whoever lost the cash.
   ``We had kind of hoped the guy who lost it would have gotten
it,'' said Gloria Shergi.
   Allegheny County Deputy Solicitor Ira Weiss said Wednesday that
Patrick Shergi may keep the cash because the owner hasn't turned up.
   ``To date, no one has satisfactorily established that he or she
is the owner of the property,'' Weiss wrote.
   The law states that ``reasonable time'' must elapse before a
finder may claim the goods. Weiss said a month is sufficient.
   Shergi found the hundred $100 bills Aug 3 in a bag beside a curb.
   Publicity about the discovery brought claims of ownership from
more than a dozen people who telephoned police, but none was able
to provide convincing evidence.
   Mrs. Shergi said her husband never thought twice about turning
the money over to authorities.
   ``He is probably one of the most honest people I've ever met,''
she said. ``He never would have been able to sleep, worrying about
whether someone had lost the money and really needed it.''
</TEXT>
