<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVA-Nuclear     09-08 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TVA-Nuclear,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA Names Successor To Nuclear Chief White</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Kingsley Jr., a retired Navy
man with more than 20 years experience in nuclear energy, was hired
Wednesday to succeed Steven A. White as head of the Tennessee
Valley Authority's nuclear program.
   White, 59, has run TVA's nuclear program since January 1986,
five months after the federal utility shut down its five-reactor
system because of safety and management concerns.
   Since then, Unit 2 at Sequoyah Nuclear Plant outside Chattanooga
has returned to operation and Unit 1 is scheduled for restart later
this month. Browns Ferry Unit 2 is expected to be back on line by
next spring.
   Kingsley, vice president of nuclear operations for Systems
Energy Resources Inc., in Jackson, Miss., will join TVA on Oct. 1
and assume command of the nuclear program a month later.
   TVA Chairman Marvin Runyon revealed Kingsley's appointment and
White's resignation during a TVA board meeting in Tupelo, Miss.
   ``Steve White has done an excellent job of starting the TVA
nuclear program on its way to complete recovery,'' Runyon said in a
statement released in Chattanooga.
   ``His assignment is essentially complete and he has stated
several times that he wants to return home to his farm in Virginia.
TVA appreciates the work he has done in making our nuclear program
safer,'' Runyon said.
   White indicated in recent weeks that he would probably leave the
$355,200-a-year job in January 1989 when his contract expires to be
with his family in Charlottsville, Va.
   The retired admiral who once headed the Navy's nuclear submarine
program has also been under fire from congressional staffers
critical of TVA's nuclear program.
   The U.S. Department of Justice is still investigating claims by
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that White lied in March 1986
when he told the NRC that TVA's unlicensed Watts Bar Nuclear Plant
near Spring City, Tenn., met certain safety standards.
   White has denied the charges, and Gerald Charnoff, an attorney
for TVA, said he expects the investigation to be dismissed soon.
   Like White, Kingsley is an ex-Navy officer, retiring in 1971 to
join Alabama Power Co. as senior engineer in nuclear production.
   Unlike him, he will be paid as a TVA employee, not a contractor,
and his $77,200 salary will be governed by a federal pay cap. He
also will receive a $100,000 cash relocation incentive and $40,000
in retirement benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
