<DOCNO> AP880908-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Abrahamson-StarWars     09-08 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abrahamson-Star Wars,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Proposes Changes In `Star Wars' System, Lower Cost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force officer who heads the nation's
anti-missile program says tens of billions of dollars could be cut
from the program to develop a ``Star Wars'' system.
   Lt. Gen. James A. Abrahamson says in an interview in today's New
York Times that the design of the weapons to be used in the system
can be simplified and that the Reagan administration's deployment
date of the late 1990s still could be met.
   He said the savings can be made by changing the design of a few
major components, including the space-based anti-missile rockets
that would be the most expensive element of the program.
   ``We're not trying to restructure the program,'' Abrahamson
stressed.
   He said his proposal was developed over the last several months
at the request of Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and will be
presented to top Pentagon officials in about two weeks.
   The Pentagon told Congress last year that development of the
first phase of the Strategic Defense Initiative would cost between
$75 billion and $150 billion.
   Estimates of the long-term cost of the program have ranged as
high as $1 trillion.
</TEXT>
