<HEAD>Joyce Brown Charged with Possession of Small Amount of Heroin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who successfully fought the city's
attempt to confine her for mental illness has been arrested and
charged with possessing $40 worth of heroin and two hypodermic
needles, police said.
   Joyce Brown, who also has used the name Billie Boggs, was
arrested on the street Wednesday evening, shortly after she was
discharged from a hospital, authorities said.
   She was charged with criminal possession of a controlled
substance, a misdemeanor because of the amount of heroin recovered,
and issued a desk appearance ticket to return to court Sept. 28,
said Officer Peter O'Donnell, a police spokesman.
   Ms. Brown, 40, was admitted to St. Clare's Hospital on Aug. 29,
but neither the hospital nor her lawyers would say what was wrong
with her. She was discharged Wednesday, said Rose Viera, a nursing
supervisor.
   Ms. Brown was the first person picked up last fall under Mayor
Edward I. Koch's plan to hospitalize some of the mentally ill
homeless. She was released when a judge ruled that city doctors,
who contended she was psychotic, could not force her to take
medication for the condition.
   She later moved into a hotel.
