<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkiMaskRapist     09-08 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ski Mask Rapist,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Woman Details Church Confessional Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 84-year-old woman attacked in a
church confessional by the ``ski mask rapist'' retold her ordeal in
court but was unable to identify the man accused of sexually
assaulting her.
   Two other victims also testified at a preliminary hearing for
27-year-old George Anthony Sanchez. Sanchez is charged with 124
counts of rape, sexual assault, robbery and burglary against 27
women in the San Jose area over a three-year period ending in
December.
   The Santa Clara Municipal Court hearing, which began Wednesday,
is to determine if there is enough evidence for a trial and is
expected to last up to a month.
   Although the assailant usually wore a ski mask or other facial
covering, two of the women who testified said they caught glimpses
of their attacker, but could not identify Sanchez as the assailant.
   Two of the women identified items found in Sanchez's home as
property that had been stolen from them.
   The 84-year-old woman described in a steady voice how she was
accosted by a man who had asked to use a telephone at a San Jose
church.
   At first, the attacker wore no disguise, but the woman said that
after he forced her into a confessional and left her for about 10
minutes, he returned with a ``black face.''
   ``I was in a trance,'' she said. ``I couldn't think.''
   She said the man brandished a black gun and raped her in the
confessional.
   Prosecutor Alan Nudelman showed her a pellet gun recovered from
Sanchez's home and asked if it was similar to the the one used by
the assailant. ``It could be the same,'' she answered.
   She also identified a red, clutch-type purse and wallet she said
were taken by the assailant. The wallet, which authorities said was
found in Sanchez's home, contained her driver's license and
photographs of her and her husband and other family members.
  
</TEXT>
