<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BeachWaste     09-08 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Waste,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee OKs Bill To Fight Medical Waste Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disposable medical supplies of the type that
turned up on East Coast beaches this summer would have to carry
identifying marks under a bill passed by a House subcommittee.
   The measure, sponsored by Rep. James Saxton, R-N.J., was
approved Wednesday by the House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
subcommittee on oceanography.
   It would require creation of Environmental Protection Agency
regulations forcing manufacturers to imprint some identifying mark
on the items to help investigators track the origins of medical
waste that turns up on beaches and shorelines.
   The measure, one of a series of medical waste bills working its
way through Congress, also would impose stiff fines and prison
terms on illegal medical waste dumpers and require the EPA to issue
regulations for generators, haulers and disposers of the infectious
materials.
   ``It's time to end the litter and crack down on polluters,''
Saxton said.
   The original version of Saxton's bill provided maximum penalties
of $100,000 in fines and one year in prison.
   But the subcommittee, meeting on the first day Congress returned
from its August recess, approved an amendment by Rep. Claudine
Schneider, R-R.I., to increase the maximum penalties to $250,000 in
fines and five years in prison.
   Another amendment, by Rep. Robert Davis, R-Mich., would extend
the bill's coverage to the Great Lakes.
   In other action, the subcommittee approved a measure by Rep.
Mike Lowry, D-Wash., to move the U.S. sea boundary from three miles
to 12 miles offshore, a move designed to make it more difficult for
Soviet vessels to detect U.S. submarine movements.
</TEXT>
