<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignAds     09-08 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Ads,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Trades In Sharp Tongue For Soft Lens In Campaign Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Americans for Bush hold news conference at 12:30 p.m. EDT;
top unlikely.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, who stunned
Democrat Michael Dukakis with a barrage of tough attacks on the
presidential campaign trail last month, is trying for a different
image in his opening television ads.
   ``I want a kinder and gentler nation,'' Bush said in his
convention acceptance speech. That moment and others like it are
now being replayed for California audiences in two 30-second spots.
   The ``kinder and gentler'' pitch was designed in large part to
increase Bush's lagging support among women voters. It is being
replayed in an ad called ``The Future,'' in which domestic images
of Bush cooking at the stove, Bush eating at a picnic and Bush
kissing a grandchild are mixed in with excerpts from his speech.
   ``I'm a quiet man but I hear the quiet people others don't. ...
I hear them and I am moved,'' Bush continues.
   ``The president,'' intones a honey-voiced narrator. ``The heart,
the soul, the conscience of the nation.''
   A second Bush ad, also running in California, features another
moment in his acceptance speech. After describing his years serving
``a great president,'' Bush says it all comes down to ``the man at
the desk, and who should sit at that desk.''
   Cheers break out on the convention floor as he declares, ``My
friends, I am that man.'' Scenes of the convention alternate with
shots of the White House, strikingly lit in the dark of night.
   Dukakis is competing with Bush on both the compassion and
competence fronts, mostly in Texas _ like California, another
critical battleground.
   A Dukakis spot running in Texas shows a padlocked plant gate as
a narrator asks, ``Shouldn't there be a law to give you and your
community 60 days' notice? George Bush says no and Dan Quayle led
the fight in the Senate against making it a law.''
   The ad says the Massachusetts governor had one of the first such
laws in the country passed and touts Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, his
running mate, as ``the man who won the fight to make 60-day
notification law.'' The two are shown in their shirtsleeves,
chatting genially with a group of workers at a plant.
   ``Who cares about your life?'' a narrator asks in closing. ``The
choice is clear.''
   Dukakis also has revived an ad called ``New Era,'' which ran in
a limited fashion during the Republican convention and started up
Wednesday on national network television. The spot features
excerpts from his acceptance speech and a list of his
accomplishments as governor.
   Neither campaign is using negative ads yet, but the Democratic
National Committee unveiled one Wednesday and said it would start
airing late this week. Called ``Hey Pal,'' the spot charges that
the GOP is responsible for tripling the federal deficit from $900
billion in 1980 to $2.6 trillion this year. ``We can't afford the
Republicans,'' it concludes.
   The generic ad was scheduled to play in several battleground
states, but the campaign declined to specify which ones.
   A group called Americans for Bush, not associated with the Bush
campaign, has prepared two ads slamming Dukakis' record on crime
and plans to show them on several national cable networks. The ads
were to be shown at a news conference today.
 
</TEXT>
