<DOCNO> AP880908-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     09-08 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega, President Take Pay Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet voted to cut the pay of
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega and other top officials because of a
cash shortage caused in part by U.S. economic sanctions.
   A Cabinet resolution passed Tuesday mandates pay cuts of 12.5
percent to 30 percent for Noriega, President Manuel Solis Palma and
heads of state-owned companies.
   The government did not provide the individuals' salaries, but it
said they make more than $3,000 a month.
   Salaries will return to normal ``when public finances allow,'' a
government communique said. It acknowledged a ``deterioration'' in
state income and said the pay cuts will save the government
$230,000 a month.
   Business sources say the size of the economy is about half what
it was in early 1987, before the United States imposed economic
sanctions in an attempt to drive Noriega from power.
   Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces and the real power
behind the civilian government, is reputed to have become
independently wealthy during his military career. He is under U.S.
indictment on drug trafficking charges.
   Noriega denies the drug trafficking charges and says the United
States is trying to undermine the Panamanian government as part of
a plan to renege on the 1977 Panama Canal treaties. Under the
treaties, Washington must cede control of the canal at the turn of
the century.
   The United States on Wednesday marked the 11th anniversary of
the treaties, saying it would respect the accords but that
relations with Panama could improve only with a democratic
government in Panama.
   ``Panamanians and North Americans have worked together to
implement the treaties and to ensure the continued and efficient
operation of the Panama Canal. We promise that this will
continue,'' the U.S. Embassy said in a statement.
   It said, however, that the U.S. government ``continues believing
that relations between our two peoples will be stronger when
democracy is restored in Panama.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amnesty-Brazil     09-08 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Brazil,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Urges Brazil To End Land-Related Killings, Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 people have died since 1980 in
land disputes in northern Brazil, where landowners hire gunmen to
abuse or kill peasants, Indians, church workers and trade
unionists, Amnesty International said today.
   The London-based human rights group chastised Brazilian
authorities for not enforcing laws to stem the violence and said it
has evidence public servants were themselves involved in some
incidents.
   Land reform is a deeply divisive issue in Brazil, where 4
percent of the population of 141 million own almost half the arable
land.
   Amnesty said the report that although it takes no position on
land issues, it was ``alarmed at systematic and widespread failure
to enforce the rule of law which has led to serious human rights
violations in Brazil.''
   The report accuses authorities of allowing abuses to go
virtually unpunished and speaks of ``overwhelming evidence that the
intimidation and violence of landowners and land speculators is not
only sanctioned, but frequently assisted by state authorities.''
   In an example of official indifference, the report said, a
police chief at Goianesiua police station in Para state allegedly
told one woman whose husband and son were shot dead in October 1987
that he could not register the crime because he had no pen and
paper.
   In addition to the deaths of more than 1,000 people in land
disputes since 1980, hundreds more were tortured or ill-treated and
countless others were forced off their land, the group said.
   It said it sent its report to Brazilian authorities in April and
discussed its concerns with senior federal government officials in
the capital city of Brasilia in June.
   The officials acknowleged state action had been inadequate ``but
did not accept that this called for direct federal intervention,''
Amnesty said.
   The group said evidence suggested most of the killings were
carried out by gunmen hired by landowners to terrorize and evict
those considered a threat to their interests. Most victims were
peasants, native Indians, priests, nuns, church workers, lawyers
and trade unionists, it said.
   The report quotes the Brazilian Bar Association as saying
killings can allegedly be contracted through a ``death syndicate''
with offices in Imperatriz in Maranhao state. It says police are
reported to have been recruited by such syndicates.
   ``Local police treat these killings so lightly that they often
do not bother to register the crimes,'' the report says.
   ``Even when crimes are recorded, police have failed to collect
evidence and ignored routine procedures such as visiting the scene
of the crime and interviewing suspects,'' it says.
   Convictions or punishments were imposed only in two land-related
killings, the report says.
   It says police routinely carry out arbitrary arrests of
peasants, mistreat and sometimes torture them and evict them from
their land illegally, apparently to discourage them from pursuing
political activities.
   It says hired gunmen sometimes accompany police.
   In February 1987, military police are reported to have illegally
rounded up 50 peasants, including children, in the vicinity of Sao
Geraldo do Araguaia, south Para, and marched them at gunpoint to a
landowner's ranch house, Amnesty said.
   ``They are alleged to have raped two women, savagely beaten the
peasants with rifle butts and sticks, compelled some to eat
excrement, thorns and lighted cigarettes and forced bottles down
the throats of others,'' it said. ``None of the peasants returned
to their land afterward.''
   Peasants arrested after gunmen or landowners were killed were
held incommunicado without judicial order and mistreated or even
tortured to obtain confessions or statements that would incriminate
others, Amnesty said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yeats'Grave     09-08 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yeats' Grave,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poet's Son Denies Wrong Bones Were Reburied in Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of William Butler Yeats says he has the
documentation to disprove a biographer's claim that the poet's
bones are in a pauper's grave in France, not in Yeats' grave in
Ireland.
   English biographer Diana Souhami says Yeats was buried in France
in a mass paupers' grave and that when the bones were dug up for
transfer to Ireland in 1948, there was no way of telling whose
bones they were.
   Michael Yeats accused Ms. Souhami of ``whipping up cheap
publicity out of a great man's death,'' The Irish Times said
Wednesday.
   He called her claims ``the greatest nonsense'' and said, ``It is
absolutely certain that my father is buried in County Sligo. I have
the documentation to prove it,'' the newspaper said.
   Ms. Souhami based her claim Tuesday on a mix-up she said she
found in the papers of Yeats' friend, the painter Hannah Gluck. She
is working on a biography of the painter, who she said tried for
years to convince Yeats' friends of the mistake.
   She cited correspondence between Yeats' friends and the keeper
of the cemetery in Roquebrun, southern France, saying it was
impossible to establish that the remains were the poet's.
   The younger Yeats was quoted as saying when his father died in
1939, the body was not put in a pauper's grave but placed in a
temporary grave, and its transfer to Ireland was delayed by World
War II.
   Nine years later, the poet was exhumed, his bones measured and
the remains placed in a casket for transfer to Drumcliffe, County
Sligo, where he had asked to be buried, Yeats was quoted as saying.
   The Irish Times quoted Yeats as saying his mother oversaw the
whole operation to transfer the bones and that he had documents
from various officials who witnessed the procedure.
   Ms. Souhami said she never sought the kind of publicity to which
Yeats referred, and ``offending people certainly wasn't my
intention.''
   ``I'm sure he (Yeats) believes that story, but unfortunately the
letters among Gluck's papers don't confirm his account,'' she told
The Associated Press. ``Unfortunately I have the letters from the
priest in Roquebrun and letters from the undertakers.''
   She said Hannah Gluck spent years trying to convince Yeats'
friends the wrong bones went to Drumcliffe and that the affair
needed to go into the biography because it illustrated her
obsessive character.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
