<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsiderTrading-Milken     09-08 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Milken,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Milken Architect of `Junk Bond' Financing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Insider Training-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken, who was charged by
a federal lawsuit with insider trading, almost single-handedly
built ``junk-bond'' financing into the tool of choice for corporate
raiders during the past dozen years.
   Milken was seen for years as a Wall Street whiz kid, who had
helped transform Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. from a minor player
into a powerhouse.
   Even when it became known several months ago that he was under
investigation for insider trading, Milken and Drexel took the
offensive.
   Drexel waged a public-relations blitz, stressing the role of
junk bonds _ notes that are highly risky but offer high yields _ in
helping small companies get off the ground and downplaying their
role megabuck takeover battles.
   The normally secretive Milken, 42, began accepting speaking
engagements and granting some interviews _ with the condition that
questions about the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
investigation of him were off limits.
   His comments focused almost solely on his latest pet plan _ to
alleviate the Latin American debt crisis by swapping debt for
equity or selling securities backed by those countries' oil and
silver resources.
   Milken reportedly makes $40 million a year as the head of
Drexel's junk-bond operation. That is several times more than the
firm's chairman. Milken's personal fortune has been estimated at
more than $500 million.
   He lives with his children and wife, Lori _ his high school
sweetheart whom he married at age 22 _ in a house on the former
estate of the late actor Clark Gable in suburban Encino, an
upper-middle-class section of the San Fernando Valley two miles
from his childhood home.
   Milken's fascination with finance dates to his boyhood. At age
10, a favorite pastime was poring over tax returns prepared by his
father, an accountant.
   After studying business at the University of California,
Berkeley, and the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School,
Milken went to work for Drexel Firestone & Co. in Philadelphia as a
junior bond trader.
   Drexel merged with Burnham & Co. in 1973 and Lambert Brussels
Witter in 1976, and Milken's job was moved to New York. Milken
worked hard to make a name for himself but never became acclimated
to the East.
   In 1977, he persuaded Drexel to let him move the company's
junk-bond operations from Wall Street to Beverly Hills, just off
swank Rodeo Drive.
   Milken became enormously successful in California, building a
close-knit network of junk-bond investors. He is in charge of the
150 people who work at Drexel's junk-bond operation.
   He still works 12 to 13 hours a day, seven days a week and won't
tolerate lack of drive among those who work for him.
   Associates say they need to make appointments to meet with him
even on weekends.
   He once said he had no hobbies ``because what I do is fun.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0045 </DOCNO>
