<DOCNO> AP880908-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     09-08 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rivers Receding But Miseries Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rivers across this flooded nation
receded slightly today, but the change brought little relief to
people still boating and wading through murky waters to get food
and uncontaminated water.
   The death toll from the floods that started June 13 and subsided
only to rise with new vengeance on Aug. 27 was 416 according to the
government, whose count is generally considered low.
   The independent Bengali-language newspaper Khobar today reported
34 new drownings and snake-bite deaths, bringing the unofficial
toll to 1,301.
   The Buriganga and Sitlakhya rivers that wrap around Dhaka on
three sides fell between 1{ to 4 inches in the last 24 hours but
were still as much as 45 inches above flood level, the flood
control center reported.
   About three-fourths of Bangladesh, an impoverished low-lying
nation of 110 million people, remained under water ranging from a
few inches in some areas to at least 10 feet in others.
   In Dhaka, a city of 6 million, streets were turned into canals
clogged with boats ferrying people to work, to food markets and
relief centers and to spigots to get drinking water.
   At least half the capital was still under water.
   In the Shaymoli neighborhood in northern Dhaka, two young
seamstresses waded waist deep in front of the four-story building
that houses the small Fairy Fashion Factory where they work.
   ``Eleven of us are living in the factory because our homes are
flooded,'' said 20-year-old Shamima, who uses only one name.
``There has been no electricity for two weeks, so we can't work and
we don't know if we'll be paid, but the owner is bringing us food.''
   She and her friend, 17-year-old Lily, said they waded through
the flood each day to buy about five gallons of drinking water for
31 cents. They said the water proably wasn't pure, but it was all
they could get. ``Most of us have fevers and headaches,'' Lily said.
   Both young women said they had heard about water purification
tablets but weren't using any. ``No one has given us any, and we
don't have enough money to buy any,'' Lily said.
   The government says it is distributing water purification
tablets throughout the country, but they are in short supply.
   A diplomat from a Western nation that has been trying to buy
water tablets for relief distribution reported searching in vain
for sufficient quantities in Bangladesh and nearby countries. The
diplomat spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Of more than two dozen people questioned at random in Shaymoli,
only one man _ a pharmacy shopkeeper _ said he was using them.
   The government's health control center reported 16,813 new cases
of diarrhea Wednesday, bringing the total of known cases across the
country to 119,822 since Aug. 27. At least 83 of the afflicted
people died, and their deaths were included in the government's
toll of flood victims.
   The government says at least 25 million people have lost their
homes in the flooding.
   Relief camps have been set up in an effort to help people whose
homes were washed away or are filled with flood water, but many
other people have moved in with relatives, living on rooftops or
camping in makeshift shelters on bits of high ground.
   Abul Hashem, a 50-year-old auto mechanic, has been living for
the past two weeks on the roof of a corrugated tin shed in Dhaka.
He said he tried to find other shelter but relief centers where he
went were full. He and nine other men and boys pitched tents on the
roof of sheds facing their homes.
   ``I couldn't leave my things,'' he said, pointing to his own tin
house where the water reached nearly to the roof. ``There is
nothing important there, but whatever I have is mine and I'm afraid
of robbers.''
   Abul Hashem and others in the neighborhood said robbers came at
night in motorboats and looted abandoned houses and businesses.
Dhaka newspapers also have reported that robbers were operating
from boats, but the government denied there had been an increase in
break-ins.
   Home Minister Abdul Matin said the number of thefts had not
increased, and the only difference was that thieves were now coming
by boat instead of land.
</TEXT>
