<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Inches Down, Stocks Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose higher.
   The dollar closed at 134.20 yen, down 0.10 yen from Wednesday's
close. It had opened at 133.67 yen, dipping below the 134-yen level
for the first time since Aug. 29. Trading ranged between
133.67-134.35 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed higher at
27,740.11, gaining another 236.10 points, or 0.86 percent,
following Wednesday's 183.50-point increase.
   Railway-related issues attracted investors in moderate trading
that reached an estimated 850 million shares.
   ``Investors were less concerned about world-wide higher discount
rates and inflation,'' said a stock analyst with Nomura Securities.
``They're now starting to think the United States' economy is not
doing that well, considering the decline of petroleum prices in New
York.''
   Petroleum prices on the futures market Wednesday fell by 55
cents a barrel for the first time in two years.
   The stock market this week has been regaining its strength, the
analyst added, speaing on condition of anonymity.
   On the foreign exchange, the U.S. currency opened lower but
dollar-buying increased later in the afternoon, pushing the dollar
higher, according to an exchange dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``It seems that the dollar has hit its lowest level,'' he said.
``Some institutional investors have already started buying more
dollars.''
</TEXT>
