<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Solzhenitsyn     09-08 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Solzhenitsyn,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exiled Writer Refuses Soviet Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exiled Soviet writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn has
rejected an invitation to join an official Soviet committee
building a monument to the victims of Josef Stalin's rule, The New
York Times reported today.
   The reclusive writer sent a telegram to the monument's
organizing committee on Tuesday declining to join, the newspaper
said.
   Solzhenitsyn's masterwork, ``The Gulag Archipelago,'' traces the
history of political repression in the Soviet Union and dwells at
length on the purges and widespread repression during Stalin's
29-year reign.
   The writer, who spent eight years in labor camps under Stalin,
was expelled from the Soviet Union after the publication of the
``Gulag'' trilogy in the West. The 1970 Nobel laureate lives in
Cavendish, Vt.
   The Times said that according to the writer's wife, Natalya, the
cable said: ``To the memory of those who perished in 1918-1956, I
have dedicated `Gulag Archipelago,' for which I was rewarded with
the accusation of treason. It is not possible to pass over this.
Moreover, since I am located outside the country, there is no
possibility of actually participating in its civic life.''
   The range of time Solzhenitsyn mentioned dates to the years of
Vladimir Lenin, who is still venerated in the Soviet Union.
   On Friday, one of the project's organizers, Yuri Samadunov, said
the invitation did not necessarily mean an easing in official
attitudes toward Solzhenitsyn, but was due to the number of Soviet
citizens who think the dissident writer is among those best
qualified to serve on the committee.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Stalin and his legacy
have come in for increasingly severe criticism. In July, the ruling
Communist Party Politburo approved the building of a Moscow
monument to his victims.
   On Aug. 25, a public council was formed to supervise the
construction and maintenance of the monument, as was an executive
committee to submit a blueprint for its design.
   Samadunov, who is on the executive committee, said the members
of the public council were chosen in street polls and from names
submitted by readers to state-run publications.
   Among those selected along with Solzhenitsyn were fellow
dissident and Nobel Peace Prize laureate Andrei D. Sakharov, poet
Yevgeny Yevtushenko and Boris Yeltsin, recently ousted as Communist
Party boss in Moscow.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
