<DOCNO> AP880908-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     09-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Hunt For Killers of 10 Train Passengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of policemen aided by dogs
searched villages in northern Punjab today for 10 Sikh extremists
who raided a train, murdered 10 passengers and wounded 13 others,
police said.
   The militants, armed with AK-47 assault rifles, surrounded the
train carrying 450 passengers at Rureassal railway station
Wednesday and killed eight Hindus and two Sikh passengers, police
chief Sanjiv Gupta said.
   The train was on a 45-mile journey from the Sikh holy city of
Amritsar to Khemkaran, the last Indian railhead before the frontier
with Pakistan.
   All the victims were commuters who come to Amritsar daily to
work.
   The United News of India and Press Trust of India news agencies
reported 12 people died in the attack. But police confirmed only 10
deaths.
   Witnesses said the killers waited for the train to arrive at the
station at Rureassal, where it makes a brief stop.
   ``As soon as the train stopped, we heard some people shouting,
`Kill them, kill them,''' said Mansa Ram, a passenger who escaped
with bullet wounds on his legs.
   ``They first surrounded the train and fired from outside to stop
passengers from escaping... After few minutes they boarded the last
car and killed the passengers,'' Ram, a Hindu farm worker, said in
Amritsar.
   The killers fled after they were challenged by 10 policemen on
board the train, Gupta said.
   Bali Singh, another witness, said the killers separated Hindu
passengers from Sikhs in the last car and killed eight Hindus by
firing at point-blank range.
   Two Sikh passengers died later after being caught in cross fire
between the extremists and security forces.
   ``There were 35 passengers in the last car, about half Hindus.
We all could have been dead, had the security forces not come in
our rescue,'' said Singh, a Hindu.
   Under government order, trains in Punjab carry security forces
to thwart possible Sikh terrorist attacks.
   Militant Sikhs have been fighting since 1982 for a separate
homeland in Punjab state. More than 1,850 people have died this
year in violence blamed on the militants.
   Sikhs, who make up 2 percent of India's 800 million people,
allege they are discriminated against by Hindus, who comprise about
80 percent of the population. Sikhs are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeacherStrikeRdp     09-08 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teacher Strike Rdp,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Walkouts Affect Schools In Five States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7,000 striking teachers, many of them demanding bigger pay
raises, continued to disrupt classes for 110,000 students in six
states today.
   Some students returned to school Wednesday in two districts in
Louisiana and Michigan as teachers reached agreements on contracts,
but strikes continued elsewhere in Michigan and in Pennsylvania,
Massachusetts, Illinois, Ohio and New Jersey.
   ``We don't want to strike but we are forced to strike. Veteran
teachers earn less than rookie police and firemen. Why?'' said
Lowell, Mass., teacher Coe Kevghas as he picketed in front of the
Rogers School Wednesday.
   In the Cheltenham district in suburban Philadelphia, about 4,000
students missed their opening day of school today because of a
walkout by 325 teachers seeking a top salary of $61,251. The
district has offered a maximum of $60,000.
   Including Cheltenham, strikes by 2,700 teachers in 10
Pennsylvania districts are keeping 43,800 students out of
classrooms.
   Officials in southwest Louisiana's Vermilion Parish agreed
Tuesday night to collective bargaining with the Vermilion
Association of Educators representing 600 teachers, cafeteria
workers and school bus drivers, ending a three-week strike.
   And in Michigan, teachers in Fenton ended a one-day walkout
affecting 2,800 students pending ratification of a three-year
contract. Terms were unavailable. Elsewhere in the state, walkouts
continued in at least nine public school districts, affecting more
than 42,000 students and 2,200 teachers.
   Talks were scheduled to resume today for more than 1,400
professors and academic staff members at Wayne State University in
Detroit, who went on strike Tuesday over union work rules and
salary.
   In Massachusetts, where teacher strikes are illegal, classes
remained canceled today in Lowell and Peabody as walkouts entered
their second day. Peabody's 408 teachers on Tuesday rejected a 17
percent wage increase over three years, holding out for 42 percent.
   ``To sit at the table locked in at 42 percent is totally
irresponsible,'' said Mayor Peter Torigian. He called a ``teachers'
day'' for today so educators could prepare for classes Friday, but
Peabody Federation of Teachers spokesman David Whitmore said the
teachers planned to continue walking the picket line.
   Lowell's 970 teachers voted unanimously Tuesday to stay off the
job, a move that affected 13,100 students. The teachers are holding
out for raises of 25 percent over three years compared with an
offer of 15 percent over two years.
   The state Labor Relations Commission Wednesday declared
Peabody's strike illegal and ordered teachers back to work, and a
hearing was set for today to determine if the strike by Lowell
teachers is illegal. The move is a routine step designed to set the
contract negotiation process in motion.
   Around Massachusetts, teachers in 35 communities were still
without contracts Wednesday as classes began.
   In Illinois, 60 substitutes replaced striking teachers in Blue
Ridge, allowing schools to open. Negotiators for the teachers and
the school board plan to meet tonight and union President Larry
Swigart said ``the two sides are very close on a salary schedule
for a three-year agreement.''
   Negotiators in Granite City headed for the bargaining table in
the state's only other teachers' strike.
   Granite City's 444 teachers walked off their jobs Tuesday,
idling 8,200 students in the district's 12 schools, which have been
open since Aug. 25. Teachers have rejected a 4 percent pay raise
and are asking for a two-year contract with salary increases of 10
percent each year, Superintendent Gilbert Walmsley said.
   Classes for 1,450 students at Eastern Regional High School in
Voorhees, N.J., were canceled for the second straight day today
because of a strike by about 130 teachers, custodians and clerks,
despite a judge's order Wednesday that workers return to school or
face possible jail sentences.
   In Ohio, contract talks involving 357 striking teachers and
support personnel at five Cleveland schools serving 1,250
handicapped students will resume at the end of the week, school and
union officials said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
