<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 0623EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PotatoScandal     09-08 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Potato Scandal,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former State Official Pleads Guilty To Misdemeanor In Potato
Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state administrator escaped
bribery charges by pleading guilty to a misdemeanor in connection
with a failed attempt to sell potatoes to Honduras that rocked
state politics.
   ``It is time to put our lives back together,'' said Laurence
McMerty, the state Agriculture Department's former marketing
director. ``It has been an awfully emotionally draining affair for
my family.''
   The state agreed to drop bribery charges against McMerty after
he pleaded guilty Wednesday to unlawful compensation for assistance
in a government matter. He faces up to one year in jail and a
$1,000 fine. No date for sentencing was set.
   McMerty, 43, admitted taking $3,200 in cash from William
Messner, a Miami-based middleman in the botched 1986 deal involving
the sale of 4 million pounds of potato seed to a Honduran
cooperative. McMerty claimed the money was reimbursement for
expenses.
   The former administrator had been accused of accepting a
Caribbean cruise and up to $4,000 in cash from Messner, and jury
selection for a bribery trial had started in state district court
Wednesday morning before McMerty agreed to the misdemeanor plea.
   The bribery charges carried a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison.
   ``I am confident and comfortable justice has been served,''
Deputy Attorney General Bruce Quick said of the plea arrangement.
   The bribery charges were based almost entirely on circumstantial
evidence, Quick said. Some evidence would have indicated McMerty
was ``duped by Messner, at least partially,'' he said. ``I
characterize this case as one of criminal bad judgment.''
   The case is credited with ruining the political career of
Agriculture Commissioner Kent Jones, a Republican who was denied
endorsement for a third term because of the lingering scandal.
   The Honduras deal collapsed after Attorney General Nicholas
Spaeth raised questions about its financing, and the state has
never been paid $104,000 due for the only 400,000-pound potato
shipment that was delivered.
   Jones became embroiled in the controversy when he and the former
president of the state-owned Bank of North Dakota signed a $300,000
note meant to help finance the deal.
   
   Messner later sold the note to a Miami bank for $264,000,
putting $180,000 of the money in his personal bank account to cover
overdrafts, the state has said.
   Messner pleaded guilty July 8 to bribery as part of a plea
agreement that requires him to pay $60,888 in restitution to the
state. Messner, who was placed on probation, was in jail for six
months prior to the plea.
</TEXT>
