<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietSpacecraft     09-08 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Spacecraft,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Having Trouble Communicating with Unmanned Spacecraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists are having trouble
communicating with an unmanned spacecraft, and the problem is
jeopardizing a joint U.S.-Soviet study of the sun planned for this
month, the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   The extent of the problem is unknown but the plan to use the
spacecraft, Phobos 1, in the solar study is considered to be in
jeopardy, the newspaper said.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has been
informed ``that they are having a problem communicating'' with the
spacecraft, said Raymond J. Amorose of the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory in Pasadena. The Soviets have not asked for U.S.
assistance, he added.
   Phobos 1, launched July 7 as part of a major Soviet study of
Mars and its moons, was to have worked with NASA's Solar Maximum
spacecraft, which has been orbiting Earth for almost a decade, to
study the sun.
   The two spacecraft were to view the sun at the same time from
different angles, providing the first stereoscopic images of the
sun.
   Such views would allow scientist to study the narrow layer of
hot gases on the sun's surface, research scientist Keith Strong of
Lockheed Missiles and Space Co. said in a recent interview.
   Phobos 1 was expected to reach Mars in January and visit its
moon Phobos in April.
</TEXT>
