<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-08 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Euro Currencies, Down Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up on European markets today
after closing slightly down in Tokyo in what dealers said were
technical fluctuations anticipating the next batch of U.S. economic
data. Gold improved.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.10 yen to a closing 134.20. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 133.80 yen.
   ``It seems that the dollar has hit its lowest level,'' said a
dealer with the Bank of Tokyo. ``Some institutional investors have
already started buying more dollars.''
   But a stock analyst with Nomura Securities said: ``Investors
were less concerned about worldwide higher discount rates and
inflation. They're now starting to think the United States' economy
is not doing that well, considering the decline of petroleum prices
in New York.''
   In Frankfurt and Milan, dealers said markets were following the
currency charts and looking ahead to Friday's release of the U.S.
Producer Price Index for August and next week's U.S. current
account balance and trade deficit for July.
   ``There are now more bullish considerations in the market,''
said a dealer in Italy. ``The feeling is that inflation is coming
up again.''
   A Frankfurt trader forecast the dollar would stay between 1.84
and 1.85 West German marks until next week. Another said fears of
central bank intervention would hold dollar below 1.86.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8498 West German marks, up from 1.8435
   _1.5615 Swiss francs, up from 1.5545
   _6.3040 French francs, up from 6.2795
   _2.0852 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0810
   _1,383.25 Italian lire, up from 1,376.50
   _1.2388 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2392
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6980, compared with
$1.7060 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $427.15 a troy ounce, up
from $426.70 bid late Wednesday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $428.00.
   ``We're still entrenched in a range between $425 and $430,''
said a London bullion dealer.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.15, up from $427.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 0.32 to close at a bid $430.51.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.57 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.52.
 
</TEXT>
