<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AsiaDisasters     09-08 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asia Disasters,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods, Earthquakes, Storms and Heat Hit Asia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bangladesh Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of natural disasters
that have hit Asia since June:
   
   FLOODS:
   Aug. 27 _ Floods triggered by annual monsoons claim at least 416
lives in Bangladesh and leave more than 21 million people homeless.
Newspapers claim more than 1,200 people are killed. At one time,
three-fourths of the impoverished nation is under water. Because
wells and pumps are submerged, people begin drinking flood water,
prompting a rise in diarrhea cases.
   
   EARTHQUAKES:
   Aug. 20 _ An earthquake registering 6.5 on the Richter scale
jolts the Himalayan mountains, foothills and plains of India and
Nepal. It is the deadliest temblor in the region in 30 years. At
least 714 people are killed in Nepal and 281 in India. The official
tolls are considered understated because the monsoons cut off roads
to many remote villages. Tens of thousands of homes, mostly of
brick and mud, are destroyed.
   Aug. 6 _ An earthquake measuring 7.3 on the Richter scale shakes
Burma, Bangladesh, northern India and parts of Pakistan and
Afghanistan. Four people die in India.
   
   STORMS:
   Aug. 16 _ A storm kills 1,406 people and causes $1.2 billion in
damage to the central Chinese province of Shaanxi. It also triggers
mountain torrents that destroy 3,000 homes, 14,326 acres of
farmland and washes away 165 miles of highway. Officials call it
the most destructive storm in the country's history.
   Sept. 2 _ Landslides caused by torrential rains kill at least 35
people in various parts of Nepal.
   
   HEAT:
   June 4 _ Northern and central India swelter in the worst heat in
20 years, with temperatures climbing as high as 117 degrees for
nearly three weeks. The government says at least 450 people died,
most in the desert state of Rajasthan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
