<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BadBond     09-08 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bad Bond,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Offers Cocaine, Stolen Clothes To Bail Out Girlfriend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man trying to get his girlfriend out
of jail ended up behind bars himself after trying to use cocaine
and stolen clothing as collateral for her bail, authorities said.
   Wayne High, 33, of Elon College, was charged with drug offenses
and possession of stolen property after a meeting with bail
bondsman Barry Cohen, police said.
   High's girlfriend, Michelle Swann, 26, of Danville, Va., had
been charged with shoplifting $400 worth of dresses from a
department store. Cohen said High called him Sunday about posting
Ms. Swann's $1,000 bond.
   When asked about possible collateral, High took the bondsman to
a car and opened the trunk, Cohen said. Inside were about a dozen
dresses, the price tags still attached.
   ``He told me they stole them from Belk's,'' Cohen said. ``I told
him I don't know anything about clothes. I'll take TVs, cars, but I
don't know clothes.''
   High then produced a foil of white powder from inside the car,
claiming it contained high-grade cocaine, Cohen said.
   The bondsman protested that he knew nothing about cocaine,
either, and would have to get his friend Dave to vouch for the
value of the loot. High lent him a quarter to make the call.
   Dave _ Detective Dave Spagnola _ said, ``As he held up the last
piece, I put the handcuffs on him.''
   Magistrate Bill Hohenwarter set bail at $10,000, explaining that
the sum worked out to $1,000 for each charge and $7,000 ``for being
so stupid,'' according to Cohen.
   Neither High nor Ms. Swann posted bail.
   ``I don't know how we kept a straight face through the whole
thing,'' Cohen added. Afterward, ``even the guy being arrested was
laughing about it.''
   ``We did give him his quarter back,'' Cohen said.
</TEXT>
