<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySwap     09-08 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Sues Hospital for Allegedly Giving Them The Wrong Infant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple have charged in a lawsuit that a
Florida hospital exchanged their healthy baby for a congenitally
ill one a decade ago to facilitate an adoption.
   Ernest and Regina I. Twigg said blood tests and sophisticated
tissue-testing at a Johns Hopkins University immunogenetics
laboratory in Baltimore prove that the child they raised for nearly
10 years was not theirs.
   The child, Arlena Twigg, died of a congenital heart illness in
August.
   The Twiggs on Wednesday filed a $100 million suit against Hardee
Memorial Hospital in Wauchula, Fla., three physicians and a nurse,
accusing them of fraud and negligence.
   The suit charges that the defendants swapped ID bracelets and
altered hospital records to exchange the babies.
   Dr. Ernest Palmer, a family physician from Wauchula who was
named in the suit, said Wednesday, ``I certainly wouldn't switch
babies on anyone, but I guess you can be sued by anyone.''
   Harold Connelly, hospital administrator, said he had no
knowledge of the suit and was surprised by the allegations.
   In papers filed in U.S. District Court in Tampa, Fla., the
couple alleges that hospital records show their daughter was born
healthy in 1978 with O-positive blood. But before leaving the
hospital, Mrs. Twiggs said the child was diagnosed as having a
severe heart defect that proved fatal.
   Mrs. Twigg said she recalls a nurse telling her that another
woman had given birth at the hospital the same day and intended to
offer the child for adoption.
   ``What else could this be except for a case involving a payment
for delivery of a healthy child as opposed to a baby with a birth
defect?'' said Marvin Ellin, the couple's lawyer.
   ``We're totally devastated,'' said Mrs. Twigg, who lives with
her husband and seven surviving children in Langhorne, Pa. ``Our
lives have turned into a nightmare. We've not only lost our Arlena
... but also where is our own daughter? We're very much interested
in tracking down our own child.''
   The Twiggs said that when Arlena was admitted to a hospital
earlier this year, pre-operative tests showed that her blood type
was B-positive, which would be almost impossible if she were the
child of the Twiggs, both type O.
   More sophisticated tissue-matching tests concluded that the
child was unrelated to the couple, said Ellin.
   Dr. Wilma Bias, who performed the test, declined comment.
</TEXT>
