<HEAD>Hours-Old Infant Found in Drainage Ditch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant less than two hours old was found
in a drainage ditch by boys taking a shortcut to school, police
said.
   ``I think the baby's life was in danger,'' said police
spokeswoman Mary Schumacher. ``We were lucky the boys found her
because she was in a secluded ditch off the roadway.''
   The 5-pound, 2{-ounce girl was listed in fair condition at AMI
Presbyterian Aurora Hospital. Officials said she suffered from
exposure and abrasions on her feet but will be fine.
   Six boys were on their way to Sable Elementary School on
Wednesday when they found the unclothed infant on a bath towel
covered with birth fluid, her umbilical cord still attached,
authorities said.
   The boys summoned the school's health professional, Linda Hicks.
``She seemed to be in good condition, other than she was very
cold,'' Hicks said. ``Her limbs were kind of blue and her face was
pale.''
   Dr. Lee Thompson estimated the infant was no more than 2 hours
old and said she appeared to be a full-term baby.
   Police called area hospitals and schools in an attempt to find
the mother.
   Peter D. Gonzalez, 9, one of the fourth-graders who found the
baby, said the boys thought the newborn was a doll at first. ``Then
it moved,'' he said. ``I thought, `How could somebody throw away a
baby in a gutter like that?' ''
