<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0530,a0539,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Killed, Strike To Mark Uprising's Ninth Month Seen as Key
Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th graf pvs: `A rival...' to UPDATE
with Palestinians pleading innocent in trial. Pick up 6th graf pvs:
`A political...' TRIMS.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops opened fire today on a gang of
masked Palestinians who had ambushed their patrol with knives and
clubs, killing one assailant and seriously wounding another, the
army said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, meanwhile, troops shot and wounded
seven Palestinians, including four teen-agers and two 9-year-old
girls, Arab hospital officials said.
   A general strike was observed in the occupied lands to mark the
nine-month anniversary of the Palestinian uprising. Called by
pro-PLO underground leaders of the revolt, it was viewed as a key
test of their control in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   A rival underground group, the Moslem fundamentalist ``Hamas,''
called the anniversary strike for Friday, underscoring a growing
split in the uprising leadership.
   In Nablus, 14 Palestinians pleaded innocent today to charges of
taking part in a stone-throwing protest that resulted in the death
of a 15-year-old Jewish girl April 6.
   The defendants are among 20 charged in the death of Tirza Porat,
the first Israeli civilian killed in the uprising. Five Israelis
and 260 Palestinians have died since the unrest began Dec. 8.
   Yaffa Rothchild, the attorney for the defendants, said six of
the youths did not appear because military authorities had moved
them from the Nablus jail and were unable to locate them for the
hearing.
   Miss Porat was killed when a group of Jewish settlers she was
hiking with confronted Palestinians near the village of Beita,
three miles south of Nablus, and then walked into the village. The
army and Arab villagers contend Miss Porat was accidentally shot by
one of the Israelis.
   A political dispute broke out over a U.S. invitation to Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres to attend a Middle East peace meeting in
Washington Sept. 25.
   That will be a month before Israel's election, which pits Peres'
Labor Party against Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing
Likud bloc. President Reagan will host the meeting between Peres,
who supports a U.S. peace plan, and Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel
Meguid of Egypt.
   Shamir, who opposes parts of the U.S. plan, accused Peres of
engineering the invitation to influence the Nov. 1 Israeli
parliamentary election, which both he and Peres have billed as a
historic referendum on how to solve the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``The whole thing is so obvious. It's an election gimmick,''
Likud member Yitzhak Modai told Israel army radio. ``It is
unacceptable in the democratic world to involve foreign factors in
domestic elections.''
   Peres dismissed the charges, saying he accepted the U.S.
invitation to keep the Middle East peace initiative ``alive and
well.''
   Today's fatality occured in the village of Silat Al Harathiya,
in the West Bank's northernmost corner about 55 miles from
Jerusalem.
   Palestinian witnesses said the clash broke out when a gang of
masked Arabs trying to stop Arab workers from going to jobs in
Israel turned on an army patrol and attacked troops with stones,
knives and clubs.
   Hospital officials identified the dead man as Mohammed Ahmed
Abdullah Abu Salah, 36, and said he was shot in the head. A
21-year-old man was in serious condition with gunshot wounds to the
abdomen and legs, the officials said.
   The death brought to 260 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising.
   Today's PLO-ordered general strike was observed throughout the
West Bank and in the Gaza Strip, a stronghold of the rival Moslem
fundamentalist Hamas, which means ``zeal'' in Arabic.
   In Gaza City, however, graffiti scrawled across walls in red
paint called on residents to observe the strike called by Hamas for
Friday. Some of the messages were painted over pro-PLO slogans.
</TEXT>
