<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Missiles 1stLd-Writethru a0548 09-08 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Missiles, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0548,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Missiles Leave Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Molesworth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with missiles leaving Britain.
Pick up 4th graf pvs: `The small ...' EDITS to conform.
^By MAUREEN JOHNSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALCONBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Showered with confetti by anti-nuclear
campaigners, the first U.S. cruise missiles to leave Western Europe
under the superpower arms control treaty were flown out of Britain
today, less than a year after they arrived.
   ``Good riddance, don't come back!'' shouted the protesters
outside the U.S. air base at Molesworth, 50 miles north of London,
as two of the 18 cruise missiles, the most recent to be deployed in
Britain, were driven away aboard camouflaged mobile launchers.
   The vehicles headed to the nearby base at Alconbury, where the
missiles were put aboard a C141 aircraft and the launchers aboard a
Galaxy C5.
   The two giant transport planes took off at 2 p.m. (9 a.m. EDT)
for a 12-hour non-stop flight, with midair refueling, to Davis
Monthan Air Force Base in Arizona for destruction under Soviet
supervision.
   The small group of anti-nuclear campaigners watched the missiles
on board two 55-foot transporters lumber through the gates and
across the flat Cambridgeshire countryside for the last time. The
protesters carried banners saying: ``This is only the first step.''
   ``This is something we have been working for for nine years,''
said Meg Beresford, secretary of the Campaign for Nuclear
Disarmament.
   At Molesworth, U.S Ambassador to Britain Charles H. Price II
hailed the missile departure as an achievement for the unity of the
16-nation NATO alliance. Referring to the protesters, said: ``We
are not here because some individuals, well-intentioned and
innocent of the world's realities, kept vigils at our bases.''
   The credit ``also belongs in part to (Soviet leader) Mikhail
Gorbachev, who bargained in good faith to accept the wisdom of
President Reagan's zero-option and acted upon it,'' said Price.
   Reagan and Gorbachev signed the agreement in Washington last
Dec. 8.
   British Defense Secretary George Younger said the missiles
treaty was a ``stinging rebuke'' to the protesters.
   ``The Russians must show that they are prepared to change in a
very real way their offensive military posture,'' Younger said.
``There is, I regret to say, no sign of them doing this so far.''
   Younger did not rule out speculation that Molesworth, built at a
cost of $76.5 million specifically to take 64 missiles, may be
equipped with runways for the U.S. Air Force to deploy
nuclear-capable F-111 bombers.
   Younger said no new land-based weapons would be introduced.
   Missile deployment at Molesworth began last November, four years
after the first U.S. cruise missiles deployed in Europe arrived at
Greenham Common, another U.S. air base in Britain.
   No date has been set for the removal of 96 cruise missiles at
Greenham.
   Officials said all Molesworth's missiles would be gone in three
months.
   The Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty, ratified by the Senate
in June, set a 1991 deadline for the superpowers to eliminate their
2,700 land-based missiles from Europe. The missiles have a range of
about 300 to 3,000 miles.
   The first U.S. missiles to leave Western Europe under the
agreement were nine Pershing 2 medium-range weapons, removed Sept.
1 from a base near Stuttgart, West Germany.
   The Soviet Union began removing its medium-range missiles from
Czechoslovakia and East Germany in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
