<FILEID>AP-NY-09-08-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Amnesty-SouthKorea     09-08 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-South Korea,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Urged to Release Prisoners, Change Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea is improving its human rights record
but holds about 600 political prisoners, and torture still occurs,
Amnesty International said today.
   The international human rights group urged the Seoul government
to make further improvements. It called for the release of
political prisoners, an end to torture and other ill-treatment of
detainees and changes in laws to allow peaceful expression of
opposition to the government.
   The report comes a week before the opening of the Olympic Games
in Seoul.
   In a report called ``Detention of Prisoners of Conscience and
Torture Continue,'' Amnesty International noted that major
political changes since last summer have ushered in some
improvements in the human rights area.
   The government of President Roh Tae-woo came into power after
Roh, then chairman of the ruling party, pledged a package of
democratic reforms, including release of political prisoners, in
response to violent demonstrations in June 1987.
   ``There have been releases and amnesties, but we think they've
been too few,'' the group said.
   While the government says nearly 1,300 political prisoners have
been released since last year, Amnesty International claims the
number is 400. The human rights group also said 4,000 former
political prisoners' civil rights have been restored in this
period, about half the number claimed by the government.
   The report said ``arrests on political grounds have continued,''
with about 600 people imprisoned for political or trade union
activities.
   Among the 600, Amnesty International is calling for the release
of 28 it has adopted as prisoners of conscience, and is
investigating the cases of another 70.
   The group defines prisoners of conscience as those ``detained
for belief, color, sex, ethnic origin, language or religion
provided they haven't used or advocated violence.'' Students who
threw rocks in demonstrations could not be considered, an official
said.
   While constitutional amendments have strengthened laws
protecting the rights of prisoners, ``in practice these rights are
still not always respected,'' Amnesty International said.
   Government sensitivity to world attention during the Sept. 17 to
Oct. 2 Olympic Games may help improve the situation, but the Games
do not guarantee changes, a representative of the group said.
   The researcher said that in the long-term, ``of course the
attention of the whole world matters ... but things have changed
very quickly in Korea. We just don't know what might happen after
(the games.)''
   The researcher insisted on anonymity, saying it was Amnesty
International policy.
</TEXT>
