<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthKorea     09-08 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Riot Police At Anti-Olympics Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students engaged in running
street battles with riot police today to protest what they called a
``half Olympics,'' and an opposition leader predicted the Olympic
Games would bring political stability to South Korea.
   The most violent protest was in the southern city of Kwangju,
where 600 students at Chonam University tossed rocks and firebombs
at riot police at an anti-Olympic rally, the South Korean news
agency Yonhap said.
   The news agency said fighting erupted when riot police fired
tear gas to stop students from marching off campus, Yonhap said. No
injuries or arrests were reported. Authorities said about 500
radical students and 50 elderly people held a peaceful rally at
Seoul's Korea University.
   Students in Kwangju and other provincial cities have accused the
government of President Roh Tae-woo of using the Olympic Games to
suppress free movement. The Games will be held in Seoul from Sept.
17 to Oct. 2.
   Radical students have demanded that the Olympics, which they
term ``half-Olympics,'' be shared with communist North Korea to
ease tension on the Korean peninsula, which was divided in 1945 at
the end of World War II.
   Opposition leader Kim Young-sam said in an interview with The
Associated Press today that he believed the Olympics would unite
the South Korean people.
   Kim said Koreans wanted the Olympics to be a major success and
that he was confident there would be no attempt to disrupt the
Games.
   ``The absolute majority of the Korean people want to see
successful Olympics,'' the president of the Reunification
Democratic Party said.
   Kim also said he doubted communist North Korea would make any
attempt to disrupt the Olympics because of the participation of the
Soviet Union and China. He said North Korea could not afford to
anger its powerful communist allies by staging terrorist attacks on
the Games.
   ``With the participation of the Soviet Union and China in the
Olympics the safety of the Games is assured,'' he said.
   North Korea has boycotted the Olympics and says it won't
participate unless it is allowed to be a co-host at the Games. The
International Olympic Committee said only one city can be a host at
the Olympics.
   South Korean officials have said North Korea might try to stage
terrorist attacks to disrupt the Olympics. North Korea has a long
history of attacks on its southern rival.
   Kim and rival opposition leader Kim Dae-jung both ran in last
December's presidential election, splitting the vote against
government candidate Roh.
</TEXT>
