<HEAD>Afghan Refugees To Be Trained In Mine Disposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan refugees are to be trained to dispose of
the thousands of land mines left by Soviet and government forces
during the war in Afghanistan, a U.N. official said today.
   The proposed program by the U.N. office coordinating aid for
Afghanistan also calls for public information campaigns to warn
women and children who return home about the danger of mines
planted in Afghan fields and roads.
   ``The first step is to train one or two returnees per village to
have some idea of how to defuse a mine and dispose of it,'' said
the official, an aide to the chief of the Geneva-based office,
Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan. The official spoke on condition he not
be identified by name.
   The number of mines littering the Afghan countryside is
estimated at hundreds of thousands to several million, the aide
said.
   Using posters and radio programs, the campaign would ``try to
inform as many as possible on the hazards, so women and children
would be able to recognize a mine and not, for example, pick it
up,'' he said.
   Another aspect would be first aid training ``since there will
unfortunately always be people blown up by mines,'' he added.
   Two basic types of mines were used in Afghanistan: traditional
anti-tank devices placed on roads, mountain passes or around
garrisons, and smaller anti-personnel mines designed to maim people.
   Millions of Afghans fled to neighboring countries such as
Pakistan and Iran to escape the decade-long fighting between the
Soviet-backed Kabul government and Moslem guerrillas seeking its
overthrow.
   The Afghan government says 150,000 refugees have returned home
since the signing of the U.N.-sponsored Afghanistan accord last
April, but the figure has not been independently confirmed.
   Soviet troops intervened in neighboring Afghanistan in December
1978 to help prop up a Marxist government. Under the Afghanistan
agreement, Moscow pledged to withdraw half its contingent by last
month and to complete the pullout by mid-February.
   U.N officials have said the Soviets already have pulled out more
than half its troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
