<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TVA-Nuclear     09-08 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TVA-Nuclear,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White's Successor Has `Fix-It' Experience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Kingsley Jr., a utility
executive with a reputation for turning around problem nuclear
plants, has been picked to head the Tennessee Valley Authority's
troubled nuclear program.
   Kingsley, 45, succeeds Steven A. White, 59, a retired admiral
whose contract expires in January after 2{ years as senior vice
president of nuclear power at the government utility. TVA Chairman
Marvin Runyon appointed Kingsley on Wednesday.
   Kingsley, vice president of nuclear operations for Systems
Energy Resources Inc. in Jackson, Miss., will join TVA on Oct. 1,
heading a program still recovering from a 2{-year shutdown forced
by safety concerns.
   Kingsley, who helped turn around Farley Nuclear Plant in Alabama
and Grand Gulf Nuclear Plant in Mississippi, said thoroughness is
the key to fixing a nuclear plant.
   ``You've got to meet all the regulatory commitments,'' said
Kingsley. ``You've got to ensure you've got the right people in the
right jobs and they have to be trained. And then you go about that
in a very methodical way.''
   ``TVA's nuclear operation has problems, as do most nuclear
operations today,'' said Kingsley, also a former Navy man. ``But
Admiral White has brought us a long way toward recovery and I fully
intend to carry on that recovery.''
   White, who was hired to turn the troubled nuclear section
around, spent more than $1 billion to rejuvenate the program, which
was shut down in August 1985 because of safety concerns about its
five licensed reactors.
   Since then, Unit 2 at Sequoyah Nuclear Plant outside Chattanooga
has returned to operation and Unit 1 is scheduled for restart this
month. Unit 2 at Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant near Athens, Ala., is
expected to be back on line by spring.
   White, who will resign next month, had indicated recently he
would probably leave his $355,200-a-year job when his contract
expires to be with his family in Charlottesville, Va.
   The retired admiral who once headed the Navy's nuclear submarine
program has been under fire from congressional staffers critical of
TVA's nuclear program.
   The U.S. Department of Justice is investigating claims by the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission that White lied in 1986 when he told
the NRC that TVA's unlicensed Watts Bar Nuclear Plant near Spring
City, Tenn., met certain safety standards.
   White has denied the charges, and Gerald Charnoff, an attorney
for TVA, said he expects the investigation to be dismissed soon.
   Kingsley will receive $77,300 a year, the maximum for federal
employees, Runyon said. He will be eligible for performance bonuses
that could increase his income to more than $200,000 annually.
   White was hired on a consulting basis, allowing his pay to
exceed the limit.
   Kingsley retired from the Navy in 1971 to join Alabama Power Co.
as senior engineer in nuclear production.
   He became manager at Farley in 1977 and took a similar position
at Grand Gulf in 1984, improving the Mississippi Power and Light
Co. plant from one of the lowest-rated facilities in the South to
one of the highest.
   TVA was created by the government during the Depression to help
bring electricity to the rural South.
</TEXT>
