<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0493 09-08 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede PLAINVIEW, N.Y.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Nation Will ``Pay the Price'' for Deficits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with speech, picking up in 3rd graf
pvs, Texas law</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WOODBURY, N.Y. _ Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen told Long Island businessmen today that America will ``pay
the price'' for the huge federal budget deficits of the Reagan
administration.
   But the former Houston insurance executive said the Democratic
ticket understands the needs of business and will fight the
deficits with frugal management and an aggressive trade policy.
   ``During this election, you're going to hear a lot about a
five-year-economic boom,'' he said, referring to the current
expansion. But he said accomplishing that was no trick when the
government was writing ``hot checks'' with deficits of more than
$150 billion a year.
   ``If you listen to this administration, you would think they are
fiscal conservatives,'' he said. ``But they have not submitted one
balanced budget.''
   ``We're all going to pay the price for this borrow-and-spend
philosophy,'' he said.
   Bentsen received a polite reception from the largely Republican
Long Island Association at the breakfast.
   But he got a hearty hand when he said evacuation plans for
nuclear plants should be made at the local level. The Reagan
administration has said the federal government can make those
plans, a controversial stand on Long Island where the Long Island
Lighting Company's Shoreham nuclear plant has been kept from
starting operations for five years because of dispute over whether
Long Island could ever by successfully evacuated in case of an
accident.
   Bentsen arrived on Long Island, after weeks of concentrating in
his native Texas and the South, to begin a three-day,
coast-to-coast campaign trip today with a taste of the food and
money available in New York.
   After his Long Island speech, he was heading to Manhattan for a
fund-raiser for his Senate campaign. He held another Senate
campaign fundraiser Tuesday night in Connecticut.
   Texas law allows Bentsen to run for both the Senate and the vice
presidency. He says he's doing that because dropping out of the
Senate race would automatically hand his seat to a Republican.
   The Carnegie Delicatessan was on Bentsen's schedule this
afternoon. The deli, featured in Woddy Allen's movie ``Broadway
Danny Rose,'' is famous for huge helpings of pastrami, tongue, and
corned beef.
   Both Bentsen and presidential candidate Michael Dukakis are
slated to speak at a gala $5 million Democratic Party fund-raiser
in Manhattan tonight. It was expected to be the largest single
fund-raising event in the party's history.
   Then for Bentsen it's off to Iowa and Califorinia on Friday and
Saturday before returning to Washington on Sunday.
   Bentsen has stopped in Texas on every other campaign swing he
has taken since being named to the ticket, as his home state with
its 29 electoral votes could swing the election. Bentsen was in
Texas earlier this week, and he plans to campaign there again next
week.
   Recent polls show the Democrats trailing the Republicans
slightly in Texas, where George Bush also claims residence.
   The Senate returned from its summer recess this week and both
Bentsen and his GOP counterpart, Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana, were
in Washington on Wednesday to attend to business there.
   Bentsen told reporters that it will be difficult for the
Congress to do its work given the partisan political atmosphere.
   ``There's no question that it's complicating the process,'' he
said.
   Bentsen renewed his criticism of President Reagan's veto of a
defense bill recently as an attempt to help Bush. ``You're going to
see more and more of that, I'm afraid,'' he said.
</TEXT>
