<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0561 09-08 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0561,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Warmly Received by American Legion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis on SDI, poll results, inserting 6 grafs
after 4th graf pvs, ``After eight</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, KY. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis called for
strengthening America's non-nuclear conventional forces today in a
speech that won a warm reception from an American Legion convention.
   Dukakis praised President Reagan for signing the U.S.-Soviet
treaty banning intermediate-range nuclear missiles, and he lauded
the war record and patriotism of Republican presidential rival
George Bush. Both men had been received in friendly fashion by the
veterans group earlier this week.
   However, Dukakis criticized the administration in connection
with its spending on veterans' programs. And he suggested the
national debt, which has risen sharply during the Reagan
administration, would cramp efforts to build up the nation's
military might.
   ``After eight years and $2 trillion, we still don't have an
anti-tank weapon that can stop modern Soviet tanks,'' Dukakis said.
``We cannot build a strong national defense on a mountain of debt.''
   Dukakis gave no specifics on his plans to improve conventional
forces and said at a news conference later that he would give
details next week.
   Also at the news conference, Dukakis said he would support
deployment of the space-based Strategic Defense Initiative if
research proved it would work and if it was determined to be in the
national interest.
   However, when questioned on the issue, Dukakis said deployment
of SDI would be a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty with the Soviet Union and he did not want to scrap that pact.
   ``I think it is in our best interest to observe that treaty,''
Dukakis said. ``For our own sake, we have to continue with
research.''
   Dukakis said he was not worried about a new ABC-Washington Post
poll, showing him behind Bush by 8 percentage points.
   ``I don't think we're slipping, and I don't think we're in
disarray,'' he said.
   Wednesday night, in Baltimore, Dukakis promised a Jewish group
that he would provide ``generous'' aid to Israel, while he attacked
the Republicans for selling weapons to its Middle East enemies.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen and I are going to say `no' to Arab shopping
lists that endanger the security of Israel,'' Dukakis said.
   In interviews with Louisville television stations Wednesday
night, Dukakis said his call for a ``tough, strong lean defense''
will be tempered by the need for a strong economy.
   Speaking Wednesday to a convention of B'nai B'rith, the
Democratic presidential nominee referred repeatedly to his wife,
who is Jewish, and gave a new year's greeting in Hebrew as he tried
to demonstrate a sensitivity to Jewish culture and concerns.
   The Massachusetts governor drew cheers when he told the
convention that in a Dukakis administration ``there will be no
trips to Bitburg,'' referring to President Reagan's visit to a West
German cemetery where members of the Nazi SS were buried.
   As Dukakis was finishing his speech in Baltimore, his campaign
vice chairman, John Sasso, was meeting in New York with Jesse
Jackson, whose support for the Palestinians has angered American
Jews.
   Dukakis press secretary Dayton Duncan said he had no details on
the meeting between Sasso and Jackson.
   In his B'nai B'rith speech, which came shortly after one
delivered by Republican presidential nominee George Bush, Dukakis
referred only in passing to the Palestinian uprising in Israel's
occupied territories on the West Bank and said that as president he
would not recognize a ``unilateral'' declaration of a Palestinian
state.
   He pledged continued U.S. aid to Israel, which he praised as ``a
special place ... committed to peace.''
   ``From the day of Israel's rebirth four decades ago, we
Americans have understood that Israel's fate is our fate,'' he said.
   ``We're going to continue to help Israel defend itself by
providing generous levels of military and economic aid,'' Dukakis
said.
   However, he singled out Dan Quayle, the Republican vice
presidential nominee, for voting in Congress against packages
aiding Israel, and faulted Republicans for selling aircraft and
missiles to other nations in the Middle East.
   ``The Republicans have sold AWACS to Saudi Arabia, Mavericks to
Kuwait, Stingers to Bahrain and billions of additional dollars
worth of sophisticated arms to Arab countries that refuse to make
peace with Israel,'' Dukakis said. ``Mr. Bush has supported those
sales, and Dan Quayle has voted for them.
   ``We will not sell weapons that would threaten the security of
Israel to any nation,'' Dukakis said. ``And we will work to
persuade our NATO allies to join us in that policy.''
</TEXT>
