<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Space     09-08 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Space,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cosmonauts Discuss Problem-Plagued Spaceflight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmonauts just returned from a problem-plagued
space mission described cramped quarters, food and water shortages
and equipment problems but did not address questions about their
performance, a Tass dispatch indicated today.
   The government newspaper Izvestia had suggested Wednesday that
the commander of the Soyuz TM-5 capsule, stranded in orbit for a
day, may have worsened equipment problems by not following proper
emergency procedures.
   The capsule, carrying commander Vladimir Lyakhov and the first
Afghan in space, Abdul Ahad Mohmand, landed safely early Wednesday
in the Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan.
   At a news conference today for Soviet and Afghan reporters at
the Baikonur Space Center, near the landing site, the cosmonauts
said they had only 105 cubic feet between them.
   They were stuck in the capsule for 26 hours.
   ``Immobility was the biggest problem,'' Tass, the official news
agency, reported.
   The cosmonauts had an emergency supply of food and water, but
decided not to use it until absolutely necessary, Tass said.
   Other reports have said the capsule had no toilet, virtually no
room to move around, and enough air for only two days.
   The spacemen were asked about problems that forced postponement
of their reentry after their capsule undocked Tuesday from the
orbiting space station Mir.
   ``During the first landing attempt, undertaken on Sept. 6,
everything went as scheduled,'' Tass quoted Lyakhov as saying.
``But 30 seconds before the engine start-up, there occurred a
disruption in the operation of the infrared vertical sensor. The
computer was unable to judge whether the spacecraft was correctly
oriented, and the engine was shut off.''
   The engine Lyakhov referred to is supposed to brake the capsule
so it can safely pass through the atmosphere.
   The cosmonaut said a second attempt to fire the engine was made
later, but that it slowed the capsule too much and the burn was
terminated. Landing was put off until Wednesday.
   Tass did not report any comments by the crew at the news
conference about their performance.
   The newspaper said reporters asked deputy flight chief Viktor
Blagov whether the commander failed to follow proper procedure
during the second landing attempt.
   Izvestia quoted Blagov as saying: ``We still must painstakingly
study the whole situation.''
   Blagov said backup landing sites could have been used, so there
was no rush to fire the reentry engine. Then, appearing to defend
Lyakhov, he said it ``could be understood in a purely human way''
why the commander wanted to land at the designated time and place.
   Lyakhov had said in a capsule-side interview broadcast on
television Wednesday that he and Mohmand had wanted to make a third
attempt at landing on Tuesday but that the craft might have touched
down outside Soviet territory. He said the crew preferred to wait
until landing could be assured in Kazakhstan.
   Lyakhov, a 47-year-old veteran military pilot, flew in space for
175 days in 1979 and 150 days in 1983.
   The public questioning of a cosmonaut's performance was highly
unusual in the Soviet space program. It reflected the more open
discussion of problems encouraged by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev under his policy of ``glasnost.''
</TEXT>
