<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Quarter-TonMan     09-08 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quarter-Ton Man,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once 1,200, Says He's Now 520 Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Hudson, who weighed 1,200 to 1,400
pounds last year, walked out the door of his home for the first
time in 18 years today, announcing he was down to 520 pounds.
   ``It all looks pretty good,'' he said outside, with sunglasses
on. ``I shouldn't have waited this long.''
   With his every step covered on live television, Hudson pushed
himself up from a couch, walked through two interior doorways and
stepped out his back door onto a specially built patio. He sat in a
chair made of concrete.
   Hudson, 43 years old and 6 feet tall, came to public attention
last year when he became wedged in a doorway at his home in this
Long Island community. Firefighters had to cut him free.
   Comedian-turned-nutritionist Dick Gregory got him started on a
diet. Barbara Rosen, a psychologist, later took Hudson's case.
</TEXT>
