<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 09-08 0958</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0557,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Watching Missile Engines Being Destroyed; Dukakis Addresses
Veterans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush comments at missile destruction in top 9
grafs, picking up in 8th graf pvs, Both candidates; subs 1 graf for
grafs 23-25 pvs, In another ... Association with NEA endorsement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush today watched the destruction of U.S. missile stages
as part of a U.S.-Soviet treaty and called it ``a moment when the
tides of history turned.'' Michael Dukakis blended economic and
military messages, telling the American Legion the nation can't
build defense ``on a mountain of debt.''
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, flew to Texas to
watch the missile engines destroyed today as Democrat Dukakis got a
warm reception from the veterans group in Louisville, Ky.
   The night before, in Baltimore, the presidential rivals stressed
concern for Israel while sharply criticizing each other. Bush said
Dukakis waffles on creation of a Palestinian state and Dukakis
accused the Republican ticket of supporting the sale of arms to
Israel's foes.
   Bush, at the Pershing missile-engine destruction, said it was
``the day we began to reverse the arms race ... one of those unique
moments in the career of man, a moment when the tides of history
turned, that a new future dawned.''
   He joined other U.S. and Soviet officials at the Longhorn Army
Ammunition plant to see destruction of the engines, which are part
of the 859 weapons the United States has agreed to destory over the
next three years under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty.
   The Soviet Union has already destroyed several of its
counterpart SS-20 missiles.
   Dukakis, speaking today to the American Legion, one day after
Bush addressed the group, said the United States must improve its
conventional, non-nuclear forces.
   ``After eight years and $2 trillion, we still don't have an
anti-tank weapon that can stop modern Soviet tanks,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic presidential nominee, who has frequently
criticized the Reagan administration for allowing the national debt
to soar, said, ``We cannot build a strong national defense on a
mountain of debt.''
   Both candidates made their cases Wednesday as advocates of
Israel while addressing the convention of B'nai B'rith, the Jewish
service organization.
   ``Strength works better than weakness if you want to get both
peace and security,'' Bush said.
   He said he opposes creation of a Palestinian state but believes
Palestinians ``must be involved at every step'' in the peace
negotiations with Israel.
   The Republican vice president charged Dukakis lacks a clear
stand on creation of a Palestinian state, saying: ``Anyone who has
trouble making up his mind on this issue, or who proposes to leave
it open, just doesn't understand the dangers to Israel and to the
United States; just doesn't understand the very real threats that
continue to exist.''
   Dukakis, answering that he would ``never recognize a unilateral
declaration of a Palestinian state or government in exile,'' went
on to criticize Bush and running mate Dan Quayle for supporting
arms sales to Arab countries that are potential threats to Israel.
   ``We will not sell weapons that would threaten the security of
Israel to any nation,'' the Democratic nominee said, after reading
off a list of weapons sales to Arab countries with the support of
Bush and Quayle.
   Bush received a boost in the latest ABC News-Washington Post
poll, which showed the Republican candidate ahead of Dukakis 51
percent to 43 percent.
   The survey of 1,104 likely voters was conducted Aug. 31 to Sept.
6 and had a margin of error of 3.5 points.
   The Post cautioned that the results may be unusual because many
people were away from their homes during the Labor Day holiday.
Dukakis spokesman Dayton Duncan said the candidate always believed
it would be a tight race.
   In an apparent effort to defuse Democratic claims that he is
insensitive to the concerns of working people, Bush told
Knight-Ridder newspapers that he will soon propose boosting the
minimum wage.
   The administration opposes an increase, and campaign sources
said Bush was expected to link his proposal with a call for a
training wage, below the regular minimum wage, to cover new hires
and teen-agers.
   Top Bush aides were linked in published and broadcast reports to
lobbying activity for the Bahamas and Prime Minister Lynden
Pindling, who has been under investigation in this country because
of alleged drug activities.
   The reports centered on a 20-page contract proposal in which the
lobbying firm of Black, Manafort & Stone said it could create a
``backchannel relationship'' with the administration and counter
criticism by the Drug Enforcement Administration.
   Campaign manager Lee Atwater, senior adviser Charles Black and
scheduler Paul J. Manafort were named in the proposal. The firm
charged $800,000 for the lobbying activity from April 1985 to
September 1986.
   Bush at the time was head of a drug-enforcement effort that
included investigations of Pindling. Bush spokesman Mark Goodin
characterized the contract language as ``salesman's hyperbole.''
   Dukakis today received the endorsement of the 1.9 million-member
National Education Association.
   Quayle, tending to Senate duties Wednesday, was damned with
faint praise by Senate minority leader and former presidential
candidate Bob Dole.
   Dole said he thought Quayle was ``becoming an asset'' to the
Republican ticket, and he put the stress on ``becoming.''
   For Bush, Wednesday, Sept. 7, 1988, may not exactly live in
infamy but is at least a likely entry in the political blunder hall
of fame.
   Explaining how he wrongly told the American Legion crowd that
Sept. 7 was the anniversary of the 1941 Japanese bombing of Pearl
Harbor that brought America into World War II, instead of the Dec.
7 date Franklin Roosevelt declared would live in infamy, Bush said:
   ``I wanted to work Pearl Harbor in and just got carried away.''
</TEXT>
