<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 6thLd-Writethru a0555 09-08 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 6th Ld - Writethru, a0555,0846</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marches, Strike Cripple Rangoon, Foreigners Evacuated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with mob beheadings and government
shootings, Japan evacuating some dependents. Deletes reference to
soldiers and police marching. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1 million people, including
government officials and intelligence agents, marched in the
capital today demanding democracy. Mobs beheaded three people who
tried to poison the protesters.
   In a Rangoon suburb, security forces shot and injured 17 people
to halt looting.
   The capital came to a standstill as uniformed state factory
workers, Buddhist monks and Catholic nuns, housewives and a group
of 200 blind people joined in mass marches and a general strike to
demand an end to 26 years of authoritarian rule.
   The Soviet Union, China, Japan and other foreign governments
evacuated dependents of diplomats and other citizens, diplomats
said. An attempt by the United States to do the same was delayed by
an airport strike.
   Residents said more than 700,000 protesters marched in Mandalay,
350 miles north of Rangoon, and the same number in Monywa, an
important trading town 60 miles northwest of Mandalay. About
100,000 marched in Moulmein, the Mon State capital 50 miles
southeast of Rangoon.
   A Western diplomat in Bangkok said the evacuations were ordered
because embassies believed the country was ``sliding toward chaos.''
   Factory workers, Buddhist monks, Catholic nuns, students and
teachers marched through the capital to press for an end of
repressive, one-party rule. Opposition leaders are demanding an
interim government to usher in a multiparty system.
   Also participating were employees of the Council of State, the
Parliament office, the Bureau of Special Investigation, or civilian
intelligence, and uniformed officers of the state-owned shipping
line. Most held banners identifying their groups.
   The protest was the largest in Burma since Aug. 24, when
President Maung Maung lifted martial law in the capital and
nationwide curfews.
   Today's march was largely peaceful, but sources said a mob beat
to death two men and a woman who gave poisoned ice water to several
demonstrators, including schoolchildren, and then beheaded them.
   Demonstrators took the three to a monastery. After they
confessed to having been paid $42 each to poison protesters, a
waiting mob dragged them outside and beheaded them, hanging their
heads on posts at a major junction. It was not clear whether any
protesters had been poisoned.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said security forces today shot and
wounded 17 people as authorities moved to stop a mob of 500 people
from looting a cigarette factory in a Rangoon suburb. An army
officer was overpowered by mobs and beaten near the capital's
Swedagon Pagoda, it said.
   The radio said authorities the previous day retrieved from Inya
Lake seven bodies of people who had been stabbed and drowned.
   Government radio had said Wednesday that security forces had
shot dead five people and wounded six to halt widespread looting in
the capital the past two days. It said looting had broken out in 38
areas of the capital and that more than $43 million in state
property had been plundered since the beginning of August.
   The deaths brought to at least 117 the number of protesters
reported killed by security forces since last month. Foreign
diplomats say the death toll could be in the hundreds.
   Diplomatic sources said 37 dependents of Soviet Embassy
officials were evacuated Wednesday. The Soviet Union and the United
States, with about 50 nationals, have the largest missions in
Rangoon.
   The sources said China had recalled more than 100 technicians
and others would be evacuated.
   Japanese authorities said Japan, Burma's largest aid donor,
recently evacuated some dependents of embassy staff and has urged
businessmen and dependents of Japanese nationals to leave Burma.
   Others embassies also were evacuating dependents.
   The U.S. Embassy had planned to evacuate the first of its up to
100 dependents today, but their commercial flight to Bangkok,
Thailand, was canceled due to a strike at Rangoon Airport.
   Opposition leaders hoped today's would be the largest of the
many mass protests that have driven two governments from office in
less than two months.
   Demonstrators have not threatened foreigners and the U.S.
Embassy has been a popular rallying point, with protesters
applauding the American flag.
   Leaders of the Burma Socialist Program Party planned a meeting
Monday to consider a referendum on one-party rule, despite a
protesters' demand for an interim government first.
   The party has ruled since a 1962 military coup that brought Ne
Win to power. His rigid socialist and isolationist policies have
made Burma one of the world's poorest nations.
   Turmoil began in Burma with student riots in September 1987 that
led to street protests in March and June.
   Ne Win resigned July 23 and was succeeded by a hard-line former
general, Sein Lwin, who lasted only 17 days. He was replaced by
Maung Maung, Burma's first civilian leader since 1962.
   Maung Maung called for the referendum on ending one-party rule.
</TEXT>
