<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DetroitNewspapers     09-08 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper's Attorney Says JOA Should Be Allowed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge was urged today to allow
Detroit's two daily newspapers to complete a partial merger under a
joint operating agreement approved last month by then-Attorney
General Edwin Meese III.
   Attorney Clark Clifford dismissed suggestions by opponents of
the joint operating agreement (JOA) that Meese had ignored the
conclusions of an administrative law judge that the papers didn's
qualify for the anti-trust exemption.
   Meese ``is under no compunction at any stage of the proceeding
to accept any conclusion of the administrative law judge,'' said
Clifford, who represents Knight-Ridder, Inc., owner of the Detroit
Free Press.
   Before leaving office last month, Meese found that the Free
Press, a morning paper that has lost $100 million in nine years,
was a failing newspaper under the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act.
   Meese approved a joint operating agreement between the Free
Press and the Detroit News, owned by Gannett Co., Inc. The partial
merger was temporarily blocked by court order until U.S. District
Judge George Revercomb has a chance to rule on a legal challenge.
   Revercomb said he would issue a ruling by next week.
   William Schultz, an attorney representing Michigan Citizens for
an ndependent Press, charged that the two dailies engaged in a
bitter war of price cutting to either put each other out of
business or qualify for a lucrative joint operating agreement.
   ``Did Congress intend to give large corporations like Gannett
and Knight-Ridder the opportunity to gain a JOA simply by cutting
prices, thus creating a record of loss?'' Schultz said.
   Justice Department attorney Thomas Millet said ``there
absolutely was no evidence of collusion'' between the Free Press
and The News, which was bought by Gannett in 1986, several months
before the joint operating agreement was formally sought.
   ``The fact that these two papers considered the option and
discussed this over a period of time is not an argument that a JOA
shouldn't occur,'' Millet said.
   Those discussions were a ``natural consequence'' of the fact
that both papers sustained losses while cutting advertising and
circulation rates to gain dominance in the market, Millet said.
   Clifford, an elder statesman of the Democratic Party who served
as defense secretary under President Johnson, said the News had
rejected several Free Press overtures to joint their production and
commercial departments.
   The News was ``determined to keep the Free Press as far down as
they can because in the news business you try to become the
dominant paper,'' Clifford said. ``As soon as you find yourself in
the second position, you are probably on your way out.''
   While the Free Press was locked in bitter competition with the
News, ``every year except one, they lost more money than they lost
the year before.''
   ``Knight-Ridder, during the eight-year period, poured $176
million into the Free Press in an effort to keep it afloat,''
Clifford said. ``At the end of the period, the Free Press was
losing more money then they were at the beginning.''
   Knight-Ridder has threatened to close the Free Press if the
joint operating agreement is not allowed to go through.
   Clifford said closing the Free Press would cost 2,200 jobs while
between 600 and 800 jobs would be eliminated if the two dailies
combined their business operations.
   Schultz argued that Meese's decision was arbitrary because he
ignored the administrative law judge's recommendation.
   Meese disregarded the administrative law judge's conclusion that
if the partial merger were not approved, the News, which has also
posted significant losses, would eventually raise its prices,
thereby allowing the Free Press to do the same, Schultz said.
   Clifford said many of the administrative law judge's conclusions
``got so far beyond the question of fact that you get into the
realm of speculation.''
   Millet said the opponents have to prove ``the decision is
irrational, not that they don't like it or they think the
administrative law judge recommended a contrary result.''
</TEXT>
