<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0479 09-08 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BALTIMORE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Views Missile Engine Destruction; Hails INF Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 12 grafs new with Bush witnessing destruction of missile
engines, comments from vice president; picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Bush's embarrassing,' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNACK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George
Bush today viewed the fiery destruction of a set of U.S.
intermediate-range missile engines and said the demolition marks
``the day we began to reverse the arms race.''
   The vice president, who watched as the two Pershing missile
engines were fired _ the first to be destroyed deliberately under
the U.S.-Soviet arms reduction treaty, said this is ``one of those
unique moments in the career of man, a moment when the tides of
history turned, that a new future dawned.''
   Bush joined other U.S. and Soviet officials on the reviewing
stand at the Longhorn Army Ammunition plant here to witness the
demolition of the two engines, which are among the 859 weapons that
the two superpowers have agreed to destroy over the next three
years.
   Peering through binoculars from a distance of about 1,000 feet,
the vice president watched as the motor of a Pershing II missile
engine was fired to burn up its fuel followed by the firing of a
smaller Pershing 1a rocket engine.
   The destruction was accompanied by a thunderous blast that
lasted about a minute and then a loud cheer from those on the
reviewing stand.
   The Soviet Union has already demolished several of its
counterpart SS-20 missiles under the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty signed last December.
   ``We, too, are sending our INF missiles to the junkyards,'' Bush
said. ``The missile stages we destroy today are just a beginning.
It is a moment we will be able to tell our children and
grandchildren about _ this was the day we began to reverse the arms
race, this was the day we began destroying the weapons of
destruction.''
   Nuclear warheads of the missiles are to be dismantled under the
same agreement.
   Even though the Bush campaign paid for the trip, the GOP nominee
was attending the event in his official capacity as vice president,
aides said.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, told reporters he did not
believe the vice president had unfair advantage over Dukakis
because of his ability to participate in the program.
   ``George Bush has been associated with the efforts to achieve an
INF treaty for many years. It's something I think he is
legitimately entitled to participate in,'' Fuller said.
   On Wednesday, Bush said he ``just got messed up'' when he told
an American Legion audience that it was the 47th anniversary of
Pearl Harbor Day _ three months in advance of the actual day.
   Bush's embarrassing gaffe, which he corrected after noticing the
perplexed expressions in his audience, happened when ``I wanted to
work Pearl Harbor in and just got carried away,'' he told reporters
traveling with him on Air Force Two.
   ``I looked up and saw incredulity on the face of one particular
guy and I thought, `Whoops! My heavens I've done it!' So I was glad
to correct it.''
   Bush received a boost in the latest ABC News-Washington Post
poll, which showed the Republican candidate ahead of Democratic
Presidential nominee Michael Dukakis 51 percent to 43 percent.
   The survey of 1,104 likely voters was conducted Aug. 31 to Sept.
6 and had a margin of error of 3.5 points.
   The Post cautioned that the results may be unusual because many
people were away from their homes during the Labor Day holiday.
   In an apparent effort to defuse Democratic claims that he is
insensitive to the concerns of working people, Bush told
Knight-Ridder newspapers that he will soon propose an increase in
the minimum wage.
   The administration opposes an increase, and campaign sources
said Bush was expected to link the increase with a below-minimum
training wage for new hires and for teen-agers.
   Bush told the B'nai B'rith convention Wednesday in Baltimore
that the treaty ``to eliminate a whole class of nuclear weapons''
could not have been negotiated from a position of weakness.
   ``Strength works better than weakness if you want to get both
peace and security,'' Bush said.
   Bush did not refer to Dukakis directly in his speech to the
B'nai B'rith, a national Jewish service organization. But in his
earlier talk to the American Legion convention in Louisville, Ky.,
he suggested his rival's defense policies would ``leave America
hostage to Soviet ballistic missiles.''
   He said Soviets were now deploying two new intercontinental
ballistic missiles. ``So even with perestroika, Soviet military
modernization has not slackened,'' he said. ``Soviet military
spending continues to rise.''
   Bush also:
   _Told the B'nai B'rith that he opposes creation of a Palestinian
state but believes Palestinians ``must be involved at every step''
in the peace negotiations with Israel.
   _ Said anti-abortion demonstrators ``went too far'' in recent
noisy protests against Democratic rival Michael Dukakis.
</TEXT>
