<2ND_LINE>PM-Floods, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods Hit Florida's Central Gulf Coast; Thousands Forced To
Evacuate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with most evacuees told
they'll have to wait another day; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `It is
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 1,000 or so people evacuated
along the coast learned today they'd have to wait another day to
return to their homes, swamped by a four-day torrent that swept
away a motorist and drowned a toddler.
   ``We have to make sure everything is OK before we let people
back in,'' Red Cross spokeswoman Rita Dralus said before some
people were allowed to return this morning. ``There are water
mocassins and there are gators because ponds have overflowed, and
electricity and water definitely don't mix.''
   Much of the flooding in the Bradenton-Palmetto area of Tampa Bay
subsided by late morning, and most roads were declared passable and
reopened.
   All schools that had been closed Wednesday were reopened today
except for Bradenton Middle School, which had suffered water damage.
   The National Guard was put on alert Wednesday as residents
bailed out from the 9 to 15 inches of rain that have fallen along
the state's central Gulf Coast since Sunday, turning streets into
rivers and spilling sewage into living rooms.
   It is the area's heaviest rain in a decade, surpassing the
deluge that accompanied Hurricane Elena in 1985.
   ``We just cannot handle all that rain,'' said George Parks,
Manatee County's drainage superintendant. ``It's the worst we've
had in the 11 years I've been here.''
   The rain fell from a near-stationary cold front hovering across
the central Florida peninsula. The National Weather Service
predicted that 4 more inches could fall today before the front
slowly moved northeast.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also predicted today for southern
Georgia and coastal South Carolina, but no other flood warnings
were issued.
   Almost all low-lying areas were flooded in 10 Tampa Bay-area
counties. Most rivers were either flooded or forecast to reach
flood stage.
   In Tampa, divers were still searching for James Edward Mercer,
45, who disappeared in floodwaters after a car stalled in a
drainage ditch and began to float. Three passengers were rescued by
passersby.
   Witnesses saw Mercer surface in the murky water, his arms
flailing, but he was towed under by the strong current before
rescuers could reach him, said Tampa police spokesman Steve Cole.
   ``I feel certain that he is deceased, but we haven't found
him,'' police Lt. Mary Williams said late Wednesday.
   In New Port Richey, 2-year-old Matthew Rehm wandered behind his
home and drowned in a rain-swelled canal, authorities said.
   At least 1,000 people in the region evacuated their homes, with
some staying in shelters and others taking refuge in motels or with
friends in less-soaked areas.
   The 350 people spending Wednesday night in Manatee County's
three Red Cross shelters were told they would not be allowed to
return home until emergency officials declared the flood-damaged
areas safe.
   Nursing assistant Guy Hardin, 32, grabbed a blanket and a
toothbrush and spent Wednesday night in a Red Cross shelter at
Manatee Community College after his Bradenton duplex was flooded
out.
   ``The water was halfway up my calf and that was inside the
house,'' Hardin said. ``Everything on the floor was pretty much
ruined. The sewer backed up. In the house, it smells like a septic
tank. I don't want to go back.''
   Water depths of 4 to 5 feet were common on streets before levels
began dropping as the steady rain turned into a drizzle Wednesday
afternoon.
   ``We had police officers in dump trucks patrolling the city,''
said City Councilman Terry Wells in Palmetto, across the Manatee
River from Bradenton. The Red Cross also opened three shelters in
Tampa as floodwaters left cars in some sections of south Tampa
submerged to their windshields.
   Elsewhere in Florida, the bad weather was blamed for weakening
the clay foundation under a 500-ton construction crane that toppled
in Gainesville, trapping a 76-year-old woman in her car and pinning
the crane's operator.
   Evelyn Thompson was in stable condition Wednesday night after
being trapped more than an hour, and the operator was quickly
freed, Gainesville police Lt. Sadie Darnell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
