<DOCNO> AP880908-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ireland-Jews     09-08 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland-Jews,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historian Says Ireland Actively Barred Jewish Holocaust Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish government refused entry to
Jewish refugees from Nazi Germany and was heavily influenced by its
ambassador to Berlin, who said the Jews were a source of
corruption, according to a new book.
   ``Ireland and Europe 1919-1949,'' by historian Dermot Keogh of
University College, Cork, cites previously secret state documents
to show that the government regarded Jews as ``a potential irritant
in the body politic'' who had ``disproportionate wealth and
influence.''
   The book, published Wednesday, says Eamon de Valera, Irish prime
minister at the time, was advised by his ambassador to Germany,
Charles Bewley, a former ambassador to the Vatican and a Roman
Catholic convert from Quakerism.
   He cites reports in the state archives in which Bewley blamed
Jews for ``the appalling moral degradation'' of pre-Hitler Germany
and claimed that they creates ``grave moral scandals and are a
source of corruption of the populations among which they dwell.''
   Keogh writes that de Valera did not share these views and
frequently would ``deviate substantially'' from the policy. About
150 Jews from Germany were admitted temporarily, he says.
   But he also says de Valera rejected pleas from Irish Jewish
leaders to give refuge to a German Jew who had jumped ship in Cork
in 1939. The Jew ended up in a concentration camp, Keogh writes.
   He says there is evidence that government departments opposed
any entry of Jews even after the Nazis' extermination of Jews
became known. The policy, he says, continued after the war.
   Keough quotes a Justice Department memorandum saying Jews should
be treated less liberally under the immigration law because ``the
wealth and influence of the Jewish community in this country
appears to have increased considerably in recent years and there is
some danger of exciting opposition and controversy if this tendency
continues.''
   Even in 1953, a Justice Department memorandum referred to Jews
as a people who ``appear to have disproportionate wealth and
influence,'' Keogh writes.
   Ireland, a country of 3.5 million, has about 1,900 Jews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
