<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ChannelSwimmer     09-08 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Channel Swimmer,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Breaks Record For France-to-England Swim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old Briton today broke the speed
record for swimming the English Channel from France to England,
making the crossing in just over eight hours.
   Richard Davey, a chemical engineer from Folkestone, swam in calm
seas and clear weather from Cap Griz Nez, France, to St. Margaret's
Bay near Dover, England, in eight hours and five minutes.
   He cut by 10 minutes the record for a crossing from France to
England set by Philip Rush of New Zealand last year.
   The fastest swim for a channel crossing in either direction was
set in 1978 by Penny Lee Dean of the United States, while swimming
from England to France in seven hours, 40 minutes.
   The distance from Dover in a straight line to the nearest point
in France is 21 miles, but winds, tides and currents usually add 10
miles or more to the distance for swimmers.
   Davey, an experienced long-distance swimmer, failed by 57
seconds on Saturday to break the all-time record for a crossing of
the 10.5-mile long Lake Windermere in northeastern England. He made
the crossing in three hours, 50 minutes, and 53 seconds.
</TEXT>
