<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0544 09-08 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0544,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle Calls for Repealing War Powers Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Quayle speech in top 16 grafs, picking up in 5th
graf pvs, ``No matter; trims at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle, who has concentrated on
Democrat-bashing in recent days, switched today to a detailed
national defense speech touting the Strategic Defense Initiative
and calling for repeal of the War Powers Act.
   The Republican vice presidential candidate, in remarks prepared
for delivery to the City Club of Chicago, also said that Japan and
the European allies should share more of the cost of their own
defense.
   On SDI, Quayle said, ``The next president should make every
effort to determine whether he or his successor could develop and
deploy a second red button _ not just the button of retaliation but
the button of protection.''
   The speech was designed to spotlight Quayle's experience as a
member of the Senate Armed Services Committee. He spoke in great
detail on the justifications for SDI, popularly known as Star Wars,
as well as other weapons systems and national security philosophy
in general.
   He called for a cautious approach to U.S.-Soviet agreements.
``We must probe the Soviet position on START, working to conclude
an agreement while modernizing our forces,'' he said.
   ``We must probe the Soviet position on conventional forces while
continuing initiatives to strengthen our conventional force
posture. And we must probe Soviet willingness to restrain their
clients and to determine whether Soviet `new thinking' will in fact
lead to behavior that can lower the possibilities for regional
conflicts,'' he said in the prepared statement.
   Quayle's text did not mention Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis, whom he has heatedly attacked as being weak on
defense in recent days.
   He attacked congressional ``interference in the president's
ability to conduct foreign policy.'' He said the War Powers Act
``is unconstitutional and should be repealed or drastically
rewritten.''
   The act, enacted by Congress in 1973 over President Nixon's
veto, is a Vietnam-era law limiting a president's ability to commit
U.S. troops to dangerous situations.
   The law says a president must send a report to Congress within
48 hours after U.S. military personnel are sent to areas of
``imminent hostilities.'' The forces would have to be withdrawn in
60 days, in some cases, unless Congress votes to permit them to
stay.
   All presidents since Nixon have argued the law is an
unconstitutional restriction on the executive branch.
   There is widespread criticism _ from Democrats and Republicans
alike _ that the law is unworkable and there is now a bipartisan
push to rewrite the law, although there is not yet agreement on
details.
   On Wednesday in Washington, Quayle got a warm welcome from his
colleagues his first day back on the job since becoming George
Bush's running mate, but the message from Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole was mixed at best.
   Dole praised Quayle as ``a rising young star in our party'' at a
Capitol reception, but later he stopped short of calling Quayle an
asset to the Republican ticket when pressed by reporters.
   ``I think he's becoming an asset,'' Dole said. Did that mean the
senator thought Quayle had achieved that status yet, he was asked.
``Becoming,'' Dole repeated.
   Quayle told his GOP colleagues, ``I can't wait to get back out
there'' on the campaign trail. There were cheers from the senators
as Quayle spoke, some of them calling out, ``Hear, Hear!''
   ``No matter what happens in this election, the people who know
me best and the people I am closest to are the people right here in
this room,'' Quayle said. ``I hope you never forget. Believe me,
I'll never forget.''
   Quayle said he would return to Washington for key Senate votes
as he was needed.
   ``I know you've been on a roller coaster ride,'' Dole said as he
welcomed the Indiana senator back after a summer recess in which
Quayle became the party's vice presidential nominee.
   Since his nomination, Quayle has been dogged by controversies
over his military service, personal life and academic record, and
some in his own party have expressed skepticism about whether the
41-year-old senator should be on the ticket.
   Dole, a onetime presidential hopeful who was on George Bush's
short list of vice presidential prospects, has himself expressed
reservations about Quayle. Dole said recently that people of his
generation might have problems with allegations that Quayle used
his wealthy family's influence to get into the National Guard
during the Vietnam War.
   He repeated that view after the reception Wednesday, telling
reporters, ``If he did get certain breaks ... that would create a
problem in the minds of many, particularly, I would say, in my
generation.''
   At the reception, Dole presented Quayle with a small fire
extinguisher, which he said Quayle could ``spray on the press from
time to time.''
   He also gave Quayle a framed copy of the Pledge of Allegiance.
The Republicans have criticized Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee, for vetoing a Massachusetts bill that would
have required teachers to lead students in the pledge. Quayle
devoted his Labor Day fall campaign kickoff speech to the pledge.
</TEXT>
