<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KingPapers     09-08 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-King Papers,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Calls For Trial in King Papers Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered a trial to decide who owns the
papers of Martin Luther King Jr. _ his widow or Boston University.
   In a ruling received by lawyers today, Superior Court Judge John
L. Murphy said a letter by King bequeathing the papers to BU is not
a formal will and therefore Coretta Scott King has the right to a
trial on her claim to the documents.
   Murphy ruled that BU was the rightful holder of the papers at
the time of King's death in 1968, but he said Mrs. King also has
the right to stake a claim.
   One issue in the trial, Murphy said, will be whether her 23-year
delay in making a claim strengthens the university's case.
   Murphy rejected a counterclaim by BU to ownership of King papers
stored in Atlanta. The decision was dated Aug. 31.
   At issue is the collection of 83,000 documents entrusted to BU
by King in 1964, four years before he was assassinated in Memphis.
Mrs. King sued in December after negotiations over her bid to
reclaim the papers broke down.
   Mrs. King wants to consolidate the papers with 100,000 other
King documents at the King Center for Nonviolent Social Change in
Atlanta.
   Central to the case is a one-page, typewritten letter dated July
16, 1964, from King to the BU library.
   King, who received his doctorate in theology from BU in 1955,
wrote that the library would be ``the repository of my
correspondence, manuscripts and other papers.''
   ``In the event of my death,'' he wrote, ``all such materials
deposited with the university shall become from that date the
absolute property of Boston University.''
   Mrs. King, however, claims her husband had privately indicated
his wish that the archive be stored permanently in the South.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
