<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RajneeshReunion     09-08 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rajneesh Reunion,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Hundred Expected for Reunion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 200 West Coast disciples of Bhagwan
Shree Rajneesh are expected for a weekend reunion at their former
central Oregon commune, a spokesman for the Indian guru said.
   State police patrols are being increased in anticipation.
   ``We are not expecting trouble. We plan on being prepared for
trouble if it occurs,'' State Police Maj. John Collins said
Wednesday.
   But the reunion is ``just what we're calling it, a reunion,''
said Swami Anand Vibhavan, spokesman for the Rajneesh Press Service
in Lake Oswego.
   The reunion, by invitation only, will be on private property at
the 64,000-acre Rancho Rajneesh and will be closed to the public
except for a news conference Sunday by Swami Prem Niren, the guru's
attorney who now carries the title of Rajneesh's ambassador to the
United States.
   When the commune was its most active, thousands of red-clad
disciples lived on the ranch, incorporated as Rajneeshpuram. There,
they showered the self-proclaimed ``rich man's guru'' with
Rolls-Royces and jewelry.
   The sect members spent a turbulent 4{ years at the commune that
were marked by confrontations with non-believers.
   Rajneeshees took over the nearby town of Antelope and later, in
an alleged bid for political control of the county, bused in
thousands of transients as potential voters. Sect members boycotted
the election and deposited the transients in nearby communities
after state officials required eligibility hearings for all new
voter registration applicants.
   Rajneesh's feisty personal secretary, Ma Anand Sheela, is in
federal prison on a variety of convictions stemming from her
conduct at the commune. Among other crimes, she was convicted of
poisoning salad bars in nearby The Dalles, causing more than 750
people to become ill; giving glasses of poisoned water to county
officials, and setting fire to the county planning office.
   Rajneesh, 56, returned to India in 1985 after pleading guilty to
federal immigration charges. As part of a plea agreement, he
received a suspended 10-year sentence, paid a $400,000 fine and
agreed not to return to the United States for five years without
the written permission of the U.S. attorney general.
   He now lectures and meditates at a commune in Pune, India.
   The commune disbanded after the guru's departure. The property
is scheduled for auction next month under foreclosure proceedings.
   Wasco County residents have expressed concern about the weekend
gathering, but Sheriff Art Labrousse said he expects no trouble.
``We're just going to be business as usual,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
