<DOCNO> AP880908-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirRaces     09-08 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Races,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Crowds Expected in Reno Championships Despite German
Disaster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 25th annual National Championship Air
Races next week are expected to attract record crowds despite the
tragic crash into a German air show audience.
   The possibility of a similar disaster is remote here because of
strict Federal Aviation Administration and air race rules,
according to Thornton Audrain, executive director of the Reno Air
Racing Association.
   ``The planes are not allowed to fly toward the crowd,'' he said
Wednesday. ``In fact, they are only allowed to fly parallel to and
away from the crowd. We've always been very safety conscious and
have never had any spectators injured.'' Eight participants have
been killed, however.
   Audrain said he expects attendance this year to at least match
the record 148,000 who flocked to Stead Airport 10 miles north of
Reno in 1987. Time trials for the various classes of airplanes
begin Monday, and the races are Sept. 15-18.
   A record field of nearly 120 entrants is expected to compete at
speeds of up to more than 450 mph for a total purse of $450,000,
according to race officials. Entrants range from independently
wealthy flying buffs to corporate sponsored pilots.
   The Air Force Thunderbirds also are scheduled to demonstrate
their precision moves, and stunt pilots will entertain between
races.
   ``People expect the stunt flying. It's part of the show,''
Audrain said.
   At Ramstein Air Force Base in West Germany, more than 50 people
died after three jets from an Italian military precision flying
team collided at an air show Aug. 28 and one hurtled into a crowd
of spectators, exploding into a fireball.
   ``That type of maneuver would never be permitted under our
rules,'' Audrain said. ``It would have to be a very, very unusual
circumstance for the audience to be at risk at all. I just don't
see it happening.
   ``We have insurance, although that wouldn't prevent an
accident,'' he added.
   The air races began in 1964 with 24 entrants competing for a
purse of $31,774. Since 1966, the event has attracted many of the
best racers and stunt fliers in the world.
   The eight participant deaths during the history of the race
included one just last year, a pilot whose plane crashed after an
apparent engine malfunction.
   ``We have had some deaths associated with the races, but all in
all we've had a very good safety record,'' Audrain said. ``Some
things you just can't prevent, but with the strict FAA rules, we
think we're as safe as you can get.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
