<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Amnesty-SouthKorea Bjt   09-08 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-South Korea, Bjt,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korea Urged to Release Political Prisoners, End Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea has made significant improvements in
human rights as it prepares to host the Olympics, but the
government still holds 600 political prisoners and tortures some of
them, Amnesty International said Thursday.
   The human rights group said in a report that some political
prisoners were jailed after unfair trials but that torture has
decreased.
   Government sensitivity to world attention during the Sept. 17 to
Oct. 2 Olympics may help improve the situation, but the Games do
not guarantee changes, a representative of the London-based group
said.
   ``The limits of freedom of expression have expanded ... the
atmosphere is remarkably more free than before,'' Amnesty
International researcher Francoise Vandale said at a briefing on
the report, entitled ``Detention of Prisoners of Conscience and
Torture Continue.''
   The report said South Korea should release more political
prisoners, end torture and ill-treatment of detainees, and change
laws to allow peaceful expression of opposition to the government.
   Major political changes since last summer have ushered in some
improvements in human rights, the report noted.
   The government of President Roh Tae-woo came to power after Roh,
then chairman of the governing party, pledged democratic reforms,
including release of political prisoners, in response to violent
demonstrations in June 1987.
   National Assembly elections last April gave the opposition a
majority, a startling change for a country long ruled by a party
with almost complete power.
   The assembly is debating several changes in laws on national
security and demonstrations, and Amnesty International called for
amendments ``to exclude from their scope peaceful acts of
opposition to the government.''
   The changes have given political prisoners limited hope. ``There
have been releases and amnesties but we think they've been too
few,'' Ms. Vandale said.
   The government says nearly 1,300 political prisoners have been
released since last year, but Amnesty International says the number
is only 400.
   The organization also said 4,000 former political prisoners'
civil rights have been restored in this period, about half the
number claimed by the government.
   ``Arrests on political grounds have continued,'' with about 600
people imprisoned for political or trade union activities, the
report said.
   Of these, about one-third have been convicted, as far back as
1958, for anti-state activities such as espionage, and given
sentences from five years to life.
   Another one-third were arrested during nationwide strikes in
1987, and the rest are thought to be students arrested in the past
year during anti-government demonstrations.
   Among the 600, Amnesty International is calling for the release
of 28 it has adopted as prisoners of conscience, and it is
investigating the cases of another 70.
   Amnesty International defines prisoners of conscience as those
``detained for belief, color, sex, ethnic origin, language or
religion provided they haven't used or advocated violence.''
Students who threw rocks in demonstrations could not be considered,
an official said.
   Constitutional amendments have strenthened laws protecting
prisoners' rights, but ``in practice these rights are still not
always respected,'' Amnesty International said.
   It said relatives and lawyers have been denied access to any
information about detainees, and prisoners have been isolated,
beaten and deprived of sleep in the first days after their arrest.
   The group has not heard of water torture cases since several
instances in the last two years in which police were arrested for
torture or abuse of a detainee.
   Asked if Amnesty International felt the government was making
changes with the Olympics in mind, the researcher said, ``I suppose
the government is sensitive to its political image, but I believe
the release of political prisoners has more to do with the balance
of political parties.''
   She said that in the long term, ``of course the attention of the
whole world matters ... but things have changed very quickly in
Korea. We just don't know what might happen after (the Games.)''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StrandedPanamanians     09-08 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stranded Panamanians,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Change in Canada Visa Rules Strands 60 Panamanians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60 Panamanian refugees were stranded here
Thursday after the Canadian government abruptly began demanding
entry visas for travelers from that strife-torn nation, a U.S.
immigration official said.
   ``These people do not want to return to Panama _ they have made
that clear,'' Perry Rivkind, district director of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service here, said Thursday.
   Rivkind said that among the Panamanians are more than 20
children. The Panamanians were housed overnight by the airlines,
and on Thursday were given temporary permission to stay in the
United States until their situation is revolved, he said.
   ``It all rests with Canada,'' Rivkind said. ``That policy should
not have been changed in midstream.'' He said he had requested the
U.S. State Department to complain to Canadian officials about the
situation.
   On Wednesday, Canadian Immigration Minister Barbara McDougall
announced that, effective immediately, Panamanians could no longer
enter the country with only a valid passport.
   She said the visa requirement was necessary to preserve the
integrity of the Canadian immigration system, adding that 1,600
Panamanians have asked for refugee status this year.
   Panama has been wracked with political and economic turmoil
since its military ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, was indicted
for drug trafficking in February. The United States has declared a
financial embargo against Panama in a so-far unsuccessful effort to
topple Noriega's government.
   The stranded Panamanians arrived on Delta Air Lines and Air
Canada flights in the past two days with U.S. transit visas, which
ordinarily would allow them to stay only long enough to catch
another flight on to Canada.
   But they were informed that Canada now demands entry visas for
Panamanians, and were prohibited from boarding flights to that
country.
   He said that an additional 15 Panamanians were stranded in New
York.
   So far, the Panamanians stranded here have expressed no desire
to stay in the United States permanently, Rivkind said.
   Should the situation drag out, the INS, which usually refuses to
change transit visas to U.S. entry visas, might make an exception,
Rivkind said.
   ``I would have to weigh the implications,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
