<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialPoll     09-08 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Poll,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Week Poll Finds Shift Toward Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' image as a decisive leader has
declined in the past month while George Bush's has improved,
costing Dukakis support among independent voters, a national poll
released Thursday said.
   Bush was supported by 50 percent of all likely voters in the
Business Week poll, to 44 percent for Dukakis. That was a reversal
of their standings in a survey for the magazine done Aug. 4-9,
before the Republican National Convention.
   The new poll of 1,299 likely voters had a margin of error of
three percentage points, putting the race at a statistical dead
heat. However, based on the underlying movement to Bush, ``We feel
he's clearly ahead at this point,'' said David Krane of Louis
Harris & Associates, which conducts the Business Week polls.
   The 50-44 margin in the survey was similar to a 51-43 Bush lead
in an ABC News-Washington Post poll released Wednesday. The
ABC-Post poll was done Aug. 31 through Tuesday; Business Week's,
Sept. 1 through Tuesday.
   Both polls were conducted in part during the Labor Day weekend,
when many people are not home and samples may be less
representative. The Post warned that its results ``should be
interpreted cautiously.'' Krane said he did not believe the
Business Week poll had sampling problems.
   Respondents to the survey expressed some concerns with both
candidates. They split evenly on whether Dukakis is ``too soft on
crime'' and said by a 63-28 percent margin he is too inexperienced
in foreign affairs.
   On the other hand, they said by 51-42 percent that Bush
``demonstrated poor judgment in the way he picked Senator Dan
Quayle as his running mate,'' and agreed by 62-27 that Bush ``is
too willing to defend policies of the Reagan administration, such
as the Iran arms deal, whether they worked or not.''
   Asked who is the more decisive leader, 46 percent picked Bush to
40 percent for Dukakis. In the August poll, it was 50 percent for
Dukakis to 39 percent for Bush. The remainder were not sure.
   Bush had the support of most Republicans and Dukakis was favored
by most Democrats, as in August. But then independents were split,
49 percent for Bush and 46 percent for Dukakis; in the new poll
they went for Bush, 54-39.
   The August poll put the race overall at 51 percent for Dukakis
to 45 percent for Bush.
</TEXT>
