<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Western Leaders, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0593,520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with quotes from White House spokesman.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan Invites Allied Leaders To New York Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan wants to use a U.N. visit
later this month to hold individual talks with allied leaders, but
is not trying to set up a New York summit, White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said today.
   Deluged with questions about a series of stories suggesting
Reagan was trying to get world leaders together, Fitzwater said the
president merely had invited the leaders of delegations to the U.N.
General Assembly session to see him while he is in New York.
   Saying the president will travel to New York Sept. 26 and
address the General Assembly the next morning, Fitzwater told
reporters that news accounts suggesting a summit was being
attempted were incorrect. State Department spokesman Charles Redman
called one such account ``wildly inaccurate.''
   Fitzwater, answering questions at the daily White House news
briefing, said Reagan will ``hold a number of meetings with heads
of delegations, some on a bilateral basis and some in larger
groups.''
   He confirmed previous reports that Reagan had invited the
foreign ministers of Egypt and Israel to meet with him in New York
to discuss sagging Middle East peace prospects.
   ``In addition the president will meet with foreign ministers or
heads of state from several other countries during the visit,'' the
spokesman said. ``We're not prepared to announce any specific
meetings at this time. However, there are erroneous reports ... of
a so-called meeting of industrialized nations, and that story is
false.''
   Fitzwater said that ``undoubtedly the president will meet either
informally or at lunch and for dinners with representatives from
several countries'' but said that none of these meetings ``can be
construed as summits.''
   ``What's happened is, the president's having a number of
meetings and we have, of course, extended invitations to a number
of heads of delegations for those meetings,'' he said. ``In some
cases, a head of state intends to be the head of the delegation,
and in many cases, it will be the foreign minister.''
   ``I think what's happening is we have sent the invitations,
those countries are reporting it, and then in the process it gets
labeled slightly incorrectly,'' Fitzwater said.
   In Paris today, the office of President Francois Mitterrand said
Reagan had asked him to meet Sept. 27 in New York, and that the
invitation was still ``under study.''
   A spokeswoman at the Elysee Palace, speaking on condition of
anonymity in keeping with the practice on these matters, said she
did not know which other leaders had been invited, but understood
that West Germany would be represented by its foreign minister.
   Mitterrand already is scheduled to meet Reagan at the White
House on Sept. 29.
   In London, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office said there
had been ``a communication'' on the matter to which Mrs. Thatcher
has not yet responded.
   A spokesman for the prime minister, requesting anonymity, said
she had no plans to be in the United States in September. He noted
that Mrs. Thatcher has accepted an invitation extended by Reagan in
May to visit him in Washington after the election and to meet with
whoever wins the election.
</TEXT>
