<1ST_LINE>u a PM-C&NWStrike     09-08 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-C&NW Strike,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached To Avoid Rush-Hour Strike in Chicago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago & North Western Railway and a union
representing 2,600 brakemen today agreed to delay any strike until
9 a.m. Friday, after the rush-hour commute of 41,000 suburban
Chicago riders.
   ``Both sides agree that this is a step that is in the best
interest of commuters,'' said David Carle, a spokesman for U.S. Sen
Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Simon is expected to try to push legislation through Congress to
settle the dispute before the evening rush hour Friday.
   Members of the United Transportation Union planned to walk out
at 12:01 a.m. Friday when a 36-day cooling-off period ended, but
compromised in exchange for a promise from the railroad to delay
layoffs that were to occur on Friday.
   The railroad and the union are bickering over the size of train
crews. C&NW wants to dump 1,150 brakemen whose jobs it says are
obsolete; the union believes the jobs are necessary to maintain
safety.
   C&NW spokesman James Foote said that in delaying the layoffs,
the railroad ``preserves the commuter rush here in Chicago and
avoids the disruption that would come from a strike at midnight.''
   Talks between the company and the union broke off late Wednesday
and were scheduled to resume today, said Mike Bushman, a spokesman
for U.S. Rep. Terry Bruce, D-Ill.
   Foote said Wednesday that the company and the union were ``still
quite a ways apart.''
   ``Because of the positions of the two parties, we're putting our
strike plans in effect,'' Foote said.
   The C&NW recalled about 8,000 replacement workers and mobilized
management personnel in anticipation of a strike against its
10-state Midwest freight system, Foote said.
   The UTU went on strike against C&NW for four hours Aug. 4 after
an earlier cooling-off period imposed by President Reagan. Congress
ended that walkout by imposing a second cooling-off period.
   While the dispute involves C&NW's freight operations, a strike
would shut down the railroad's commuter service, forcing an
estimated 41,000 people from Chicago's suburbs to find some way
else to get to work.
   Officials at Metra, a suburban commuter rail service that
purchases service from C&NW, said a strike would cripple service
and cause rush-hour chaos.
</TEXT>
