<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-08 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candi Imming would have been on time to pick
up the keys to the new car she won in a shopping mall promotion _
if she had a car.
   ``I missed the bus,'' she said, explaining why she was 30
minutes late.
   Ms. Imming hadn't owned a car in four years and had let her
driver's license lapse.
   Ms. Imming, a sales coordinator at First Data Resources Inc.,
said she takes the bus to work, a 45-minute ride that includes a
20-minute layover. She also walks a lot.
   ``Everyone thinks it's so weird to walk, but you can get used to
it,'' she said.
   Ms. Imming, who said she is ``30-something,'' was one of about
10,000 entrants in the drawing for a new vehicle in the re-opening
celebration for the remodeled Crossroads Mall.
   Ms. Imming had her pick of six vehicles and chose a Pontiac
Grand Am. She said she liked its roomy interior.
   ``I owe people rides,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rick and Linda Vincent plan on
celebrating their newborn baby's first birthday at McDonald's _ an
obvious choice for a baby born in the fast-food restaurant's
parking lot.
   The Newaygo couple were racing to Blodgett Memorial Medical
Center in Grand Rapids at 4:40 a.m. Wednesday and were still 15
miles away when it became obvious the baby wouldn't wait.
   ``I knew his head was already coming out when I told Rick to
pull over,'' Mrs. Vincent said Thursday from her hospital bed.
   The McDonald's along Route 37 in Sparta wasn't open yet, but its
lights were on, so the couple pulled their van into the parking lot.
   A manager inside called for an ambulance, but David Michael
Vincent arrived before it did.
   The baby, at 7 pounds, 6 ounces, is healthy, though the cold
weather dropped his body temperature. He was placed under heat
lamps at the hospital.
   The couple say the baby's first birthday won't be the last one
celebrated at McDonald's. Restaurant officials said they will have
a free birthday party for David Michael Vincent every year.
</TEXT>
