<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-UN     09-08 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-UN,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Planning Busy Schedule During UN Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plans a series of meetings
with allied officials during his visit late this month to the
United Nations, but the president has not attempted to turn the
occasion into a Western summit, his spokesman said Thursday.
   Chief spokesman Marlin Fitzwater confirmed earlier reports that
Reagan had invited the foreign ministers of Egypt and Israel to
meet with him to discuss the stalled Mideast peace-making process.
He also said that Reagan had invited other world figures to meet
individually with him during Reagan's two-day stay Sept. 26-27.
   But Fitzwater vigorously denied a report that Reagan had sought
to use the opening of the U.N. General Assembly session to hold a
summit with the heads of government or heads of state of Western
allies.
   News accounts suggesting such a move, he said, ``are incorrect.''
   At the State Department, spokesman Charles Redman dismissed such
speculation as ``wildly inaccurate.''
   Fielding several questions on this subject at the daily White
House news briefing, Fitzwater confirmed that Reagan will ``hold a
number of meetings with heads of delegations, some on a bilateral
basis and some in larger groups.''
   ``In addition the president will meet with foreign ministers or
heads of state from several other countries during the visit,'' he
said. ``We're not prepared to announce any specific meetings at
this time. However, there are erroneous reports ... of a so-called
meeting of industrialized nations, and that story is false.''
   Fitzwater said that ``undoubtedly the president will meet either
informally or at lunch and for dinners with representatives from
several countries'' but said that none of these meetings ``can be
construed as summits.''
   ``What's happened is, the president's having a number of
meetings and we have of course extended invitations to a number of
heads of delegations for those meetings,'' he said. ``In some
cases, a head of state intends to be the head of the delegation,
and in many cases, it will be the foreign minister.''
   ``I think what's happening is we have sent the invitations,
those countries are reporting it, and then in the process it gets
labeled slightly incorrectly,'' Fitzwater said.
   In Paris Thursday, the office of President Francois Mitterrand
said Reagan had asked Mitterrand to meet with him Sept. 27 in New
York, and that the invitation was still ``under study.''
   Mitterrand already had been scheduled to meet Reagan at the
White House on Sept. 29. These and other responses to the
invitations sent by the White House evidently spurred the reports
of attempts to arrange a summit.
   Fitzwater said he knew of no plan by Reagan to try to see each
of the heads of state or government of the Western allies before he
leaves office next January.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, who singled Reagan out
for praise in a warm farewell speech at the conclusion of the
seven-nation economic summit last June in Toronto, is scheduled to
visit here in November.
</TEXT>
