<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolBusing     09-08 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Busing,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts 1971 Desegregation Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has lifted a 1971
busing order in the city's schools, ruling that segregationist
practices have been eliminated.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II, in a decision issued
Tuesday, lifted the 17-year-old desegregation order that ushered in
crosstown busing.
   The school system is now free to redraw boundary lines, reduce
crosstown busing and set its own standards for an integrated school
system, said Jannell Byrd, an attorney for the NAACP Legal Defense
and Education Fund Inc.
   School Board Chairman Billy Parker said today there would be no
immediate changes, but predicted at least 25 percent of the 9,000
students being bused for desegregation reasons could return to
their neighborhood schools next fall.
   Some busing will continue in places where it would otherwise be
impossible to maintain an integrated school system, he said.
   School Superintendent Herb Sang predicted today that the
students being bused with be able to attend classes in their
neighborhoods in two years.
   Willye Dennis, the leader of the Jacksonville branch of the
NAACP, said the organization maintains the school system is not
desegregated.
   ``We need to get the message out to the community that if this
case is not appealed, we are going to be in a bind,'' she said.
   Moore found that segregationist practices do not exist, despite
some imbalances in the school system's racial makeup. The
104,000-student school system's ratio of white students to black
students is 65 percent to 35 percent.
   The judge said the school system had done a reasonable job of
attempting to maintain racial balance, although he said practical
problems got in the way.
   Moore wrote that Duval County's size, about two-thirds the size
of Rhode Island, made it difficult to rectify shifts in population
patterns through busing.
   He judge ruled that the facilities and curriculum were equal at
all county schools. Jacksonville and Duval County have the same
borders.
</TEXT>
