<2ND_LINE>AM-Homesick Panda,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panda to go Back on Public Display</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chia Chia, the homesick giant panda, is
adjusting to his new home and will begin receiving vistors again on
Saturday, officials at the Cincinnati Zoo said Thursday.
   Public viewings of the 290-pound panda on loan from the London
Zoo were halted Sept. 3 because the panda apparently was homesick
and jet-lagged, officials said.
   Cincinnati Zoo spokeswoman Barbara Brady apologized to the as
many as 4,000 spectators who were turned away from the panda
exhibit. The zoo issued rain checks, Ms. Brady said.
   The 16-year-old panda has lived at the London Zoo since his
capture at age 2 in his native China. He is to stay in Cincinnati
until the end of November before moving to his new home at Mexico
City's Chapultepec Zoo, where it is hoped Chia Chia will take part
in a successful breeding program. His former mate at the London Zoo
died in 1985.
   Cincinnati zookeepers have helped Chia Chia adjust by enhancing
the accommodations, including building a new platform for him. The
animal has spent much of the time inside his den.
   Zoo executive director Edward Maruska said revenues from Chia
Chia's three-month display will be used for new housing at the
Mexico City zoo for the panda, and to set up a conservation fund
for the animals.
</TEXT>
