<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WPPSSTrial     09-08 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins In Mammoth Utility Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection in one of the biggest civil
cases in U.S. history began today with the judge warning
prospective jurors that the Washington Public Power Supply System
fraud trial could last several months.
   However, U.S. District Judge William Browning also said he would
do what he could to accommodate those selected as jurors, including
providing parking and lodgings in town for people from beyond the
metropolitan area.
   Jury selection was expected to be completed Friday.
   Twenty jurors will be seated to hear the lawsuit, which arose
over WPPSS' default on $2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance
construction of two nuclear plants.
   The plants were scrapped after they were partially built, and
the subsequent 1983 default was the biggest in the history of the
municipal bond market, leaving 40,000 people holding worthless
bonds.
   More than 24,000 people who bought the bonds sued, alleging
fraud in the planning and construction.
   The trial had been expected to take eight months to two years,
but settlements with many of the 100-plus defendants are expected
to cut the duration to a year at most.
   The case was moved to Arizona because jurors in the Northwest
might have to pay for any jury award through their electricity
rates and might therefore be ifluenced in their verdict.
   Named as defendants were WPPSS, its member utilities, the 88
utilities that contracted with WPPSS to build the plants, bond
underwriters and engineering and financial consulting firms.
   Settlements totaling $351 million have reduced the number of
defendants to 20 Washington utilities, an Oregon utility, two
engineering firms and a company that gave financial advice to WPPSS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
