<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan     09-08 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Shoot Down Aircraft, 2 Generals Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas shot down an Afghan
military transport aircraft, killing 16 people, two of them
generals, Radio Kabul said today.
   The guerrillas shot down the Soviet-built AN-32 military
transport aircraft on Wednesday with a stinger missile, said the
radio, monitored in Islamabad.
   The plane's 12 passengers and four crew all died when the plane
was hit by the missile, the radio said.
   The passengers included Brig. Gen. Mohammad Ismail Noori; Brig.
Gen. Abdul Ahad Razmenda, vice attorney of the defense ministry;
and Col. Mohammad Hassan Koshyar, in charge of political affairs of
the regional forces in Kunduz.
   The aircraft was on a flight from Kabul to Kunduz city, 162
miles northeast of Kabul, when it was shot down. Kunduz is close to
the Soviet border.
   The Soviet-built AN-32 is a two-engined turboprop, which has a
cruising speed of 317 mph. It can carry up to 39 passengers, 30
paratroopers or 24 stretchers.
   Major fighting between the guerrillas and Soviet and Afghan
security forces has been reported in recent days. Kunduz was
heavily bombed by Soviet aircraft flying from the Soviet territory
in late August soon after the guerrillas gained control of the city.
   The Soviets have been withdrawing their 115,000 soldiers from
Afghanistan under an agreement signed in Geneva in April. U.N.
officials say more than half the troops have left. The Soviets have
said they will pull out the rest by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
