<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WIPPHearing     09-08 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WIPP Hearing,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Department Asks For Nuclear Waste Dump Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department urged Congress on
Thursday to give speedy approval to legislation allowing the
government to open in New Mexico the nation's first permanent dump
for radioactive garbage resulting from nuclear weapons production.
   But Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., said he will insist that the
Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, or WIPP, meet standards still being
developed by the Environmental Protection Agency before any nuclear
trash is stored at the 10,000-acre site east of Carlsbad.
   Troy E. Wade II, acting assistant energy secretary for defense
programs, countered that limited storage of nuclear wastes is
necessary for an experimental five-year period to help scientists
determine compliance with EPA regulations.
   Richard J. Guimond, director of the EPA's office of radiation
programs, agreed, saying experimental storage would ``better
information to make that determination.''
   Richardson said there is no way the WIPP facility can begin
receiving the first of 210,000 tons of radioactive trash by next
month's target date, because the steel containers for transporting
the wastes have proved unsatisfactory in performance tests.
   Wade said tests of a redesigned container are nearing
completion, and certification is expected before the end of the
year.
   Richardson presided over a House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee hearing on a compromise bill that would withdraw
federal lands from other uses at the Carlsbad site, with permanent
jurisdiction going to the Energy Department for operation of the
WIPP facility.
   WIPP is designed to provide permanent disposal of 6.3 million
cubic feet of radioactive garbage from nuclear weapons factories _
such as plutonium-contaminated gloves, bottles, pipes and valves _
in rock salt beds 2,150 feet below ground.
   The trash would be transported to New Mexico by truck from
nuclear weapons plants around the country, the bulk of it from the
Idaho National Engineering Laboratory and the Rocky Flats Plant
outside Denver.
</TEXT>
