<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DelawarePrimary     09-08 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Primary,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beard, Woo in Primary for Senate Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delaware's maverick lieutenant governor, the
nation's highest-ranking elected official of Chinese descent, faces
a civic activist in a Democratic primary Saturday for the right to
challenge Republican Sen. William V. Roth Jr.
   Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the
University of Delaware, was a political unknown four years ago when
he bucked the Democratic Party leadership, defeated two legislators
in a primary and won election to his mainly ceremonial post by 479
votes.
   Instead of seeking re-election, Woo now is hoping to go after
Roth, who is running for a fourth term.
   But first he must defeat Samuel S. Beard, a 49-year-old former
staffer to the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy who later launched a
non-profit company which helps obtain grants and designs plans to
attract economic development.
   A poll conducted late last month for the Wilmington News Journal
showed Woo supported by 45 percent of likely voters, Beard by 31
percent and 24 percent undecided.
   But Beard has heavy support from unions and unofficial backing
from Democratic leaders, and some observers think the outcome could
depend on voter turnout.
   ``If it's a light vote, Sam Beard can win because most of the
party people are going to vote for him,'' said state party Chairman
Samu 70 percent of
his million-dollar-plus campaign warchest from Chinese-Americans
across the nation.
   ``People are very proud that a Chinese-American is running for a
high office,'' said Charles Siegel, Woo's spokesman.
   Going into the primary, Woo had $407,998 on hand, compared to
Beard's $65,008. Roth, who has no primary opponent, had $734,933.
   Woo's ethnic background became an issue in the campaign when
Edward ``Pete'' Peterson, president of the state AFL-CIO, wrote an
open letter backing Beard in which he said, ``It is up to you and I
to save this country not only from the Asian influences the Lt.
Gov. refers to, but all foreign influence.''
   Earlier this week, Peterson wrote another letter apologizing to
anyone offended by that statement. He said he was referring to
Woo's claims that he has many contacts with business leaders in
Asia.
</TEXT>
