<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kidnap-Reward     09-08 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnap-Reward,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Millionaire Offers $100,000 Reward in Kidnap Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN EVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The millionaire husband of a woman
kidnapped six weeks ago offered a $100,000 reward Thursday for
information leading to her safe return.
   The offer came in a three-paragraph statement by Robert M.
Hearin released by the FBI.
   Annie Laurie Hearin, 72, was taken July 26 from her Jackson
home. Hearin has paid nearly $1 million to 12 people whose names
were on a crude ransom note found the day of the kidnapping.
   ``My family and I have heard nothing from her since receiving a
letter in her handwriting dated Aug. 10, 1988,'' the statement
said. ``We continue to pray for her safety and safe return.
   ``I am offering a reward of $100,000 for information leading to
her safe return to her family, or information leading to the
identification and conviction of those responsible for her
kidnapping.''
   The statement added that anyone with information should contact
the nearest office of the FBI.
   Wayne Taylor, special agent in charge of the FBI in Mississippi,
said there was no immediate response to the reward but ``it's still
early.''
   Taylor said he could not comment on specific leads but added,
``We are working all day every day.''
   The ailing Mrs. Hearin suffers from ileitis, an intestinal
condition that doctors say could result in her death without
medication.
   The typewritten ransom note ordered Hearin to pay an unspecified
amount of money to people he allegedly wronged.
   On Aug. 23, the FBI announced that Hearin had followed
instructions in the note, and that payment was mailed to the 12
named in the letters _ or their survivors _ on Aug. 16, a day after
Hearin received a hand-written letter from his wife of 48 years.
   The 12 are current or former franchisers with School Pictures of
Mississippi Inc. The company, whose largest stockholder at one time
was Hearin, filed suit against the 12 in the early 1980s claiming
they owed money from operating loans, materials and film processing
fees. Hearin researched the monetary amounts involved in the
lawsuits for each of the 12 in figuring how much to pay.
   Neither the FBI nor Hearin has given out the exact amounts he
paid.
   Mrs. Hearin's letter was the first indication she was alive. The
letter, which the FBI said was in Mrs. Hearin's handwriting, had an
Atlanta postmark.
   His wife's letter promised that she would be returned if the
payments were made. At least one who received the payments refused
to accept the money, while the others declined comment.
   Hearin is co-owner of Mississippi Valley Gas Co. and he and his
partner, New Jersey oil man Leon Hess, own controlling interest in
Lamar Life Corp. The businessman's net worth exceeds $100 million.
</TEXT>
