<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wallach-Media     09-08 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wallach-Media,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wallach Says He Was Victim of Drive to Oust Meese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E. Robert Wallach, awaiting trial on
racketeering charges in the Wedtech bribery case, came to the
National Press Club Thursday and asked reporters to help him repair
his reputation.
   The San Francisco lawyer said he may have made ``honest
mistakes'' in his dealings in Washington after the Reagan
administration and his longtime friend Edwin Meese III came to
power.
   But Wallach, 54, said he bore no resemblance to the venal
influence-peddler depicted in news accounts. That Bob Wallach, he
said, ``never existed, does not exist, did not exist.''
   Wallach portrayed himself as the victim of a vendetta by the
media and investigators to drive Meese from office. Meese, the
former White House counselor, resigned last month after 3{
embattled years as attorney general.
   Wallach goes on trial in New York Jan. 3 on federal racketeering
and conspiracy charges. He allegedly tried to influence Meese and
other public officials on behalf of Wedtech Corp., the Bronx, N.Y.,
defense contractor that collapsed in a bribery scandal.
   Independent counsel James McKay reported in July that Meese
helped Wallach in his efforts in 1981 and 1982 to secure a $32
million engine-building contract for Wedtech from the Army, and
also aided his friend in 1985 in connection with a $1 billion Iraqi
oil pipeline project. Wallach was paid $150,000 by a partner in the
pipeline project.
   The $150,000 was pooled with Meese's money and that of other
investors by financial manager W. Franklyn Chinn, who turned a
$40,000 profit for Meese on a $50,000 investment in 18 months.
   McKay said Wallach steered Meese to Chin, arranged two loans for
Meese and helped line up a $40,000 job for Meese's wife, Ursula.
   But McKay decided not to seek any indictment of Meese and said
there was ``no direct evidence that Mr. Meese accepted anything of
value from Mr. Wallach with the requisite state of mind for a
gratuities violation.''
   Wallach, who was paid from $1.3 million to $1.4 million by
Wedtech, said Wedtech's officers ``have conned everybody'' and
falsely accused him of soliciting money to quash the investigation.
   ``I'm telling you, I am an innocent man. I'm telling you the
system caught an innocent man and the media played a role in it,''
Wallach said.
   ``I am persuaded that much of what went on was an effort to
drive Ed Meese from office. ... I proved to be a most attractive
vehicle to help accomplish that goal,'' he said.
   Wallach said a ``great senior figure'' of the Washington
community had commiserated with him, telling him, ``I should have
explained to you where the paths were in the jungle.''
   ``Is that what it's about? If a person comes here and makes an
honest mistake _ and I think I made some mistakes _ does that mean
you fall into the pit with stakes and it's all over with, you're
finished and that's the end? Is there no forgiveness for honest
mistakes? Must it always be read in the light of malevolence and
evil-doing and wrong-doing? Is the only access to success in your
career to destroy someone?'' he asked the reporters.
   He depicted himself as a self-made man, a grandson of Jewish
immigrants who won a scholarship and worked his way through college
to become a pillar of the San Francisco bar and backer of liberal
causes.
   ``I want you to know that I am not one of the great money-makers
of the California legal profession. I frankly never really was
that. I always made a very good living, but only practiced about
half-time because I was doing a lot of other things, including a
lot of pro bono activities and teaching,'' he said. ``My practice
died because of the media coverage.''
   But he said his friendship with Meese ``has never been breached.
The friendship is intact.''
   Wallach lodged the same complaints Wednesday night at an
American University forum on the press, where he was joined by
former White House political director Lyn Nofziger, who is
appealing a conviction on illegal lobbying charges.
</TEXT>
