<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Fires     09-08 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Fires,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Orders Cabinet Officials to Fire Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan ordered a Cabinet-level team
Thursday to visit the forest fire zones in the West to see what
more the federal government can do to help, but the White House
said nobody knows when or whether the fires can be put out.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater also said that no
federal officials are expected to resign or be discharged because
the blazes were allowed to spread.
   There has been criticism of the National Park Service for
following, during the early stages of this summer's disastrous
fires, its usual practice of allowing them to burn to encourage
reforestation.
   Some critics, including lawmakers, have called for the
resignation of William Penn Mott, the director of the Park Service.
   Fitzwater said Reagan directed Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng, Interior Secretary Donald Hodel and Deputy Defense Secretary
William H. Taft IV to go to the Western states this weekend to
confer with governors, ``assess the situation'' and report to the
president next week.
   He said one likely outcome is that more Army troops will be sent
to supplement the 2,500 now on the firelines.
   The spokesman said Hodel brought up the subject of the calls for
Penn's resignation, but there was no discussion of it.
   ``There are no plans to fire anybody,'' Fitzwater said. ``That
call represents an understandable frustration by people who have
been living with a great natural disaster, but that hasn't really
been a significant issue. We don't expect any departures.''
   As to the outlook for the future, Fitzwater said, ``The feeling
from the two secretaries is that we can be effective up to a point,
but no one is willing to speculate on whether or not the fire can
be totally extinguished or in how long a period of time.''
   The Agriculture Department is the parent of the Forest Service
and the Interior Department includes the Park Service. Together,
the two agencies control much of the 1.5 million acres of
timberland on which fires are raging.
   Of the Park Service's policy of allowing the fires to burn,
which has since been abandoned with regard to the current
conflagrations, Fitzwater said: ``Everyone accepts that that was
the right course, in the sense that good forest practice for the
past several years has been to allow a certain amount of burning
for purposes of resforestation.''
   ``I think there is a general expectation that we can hold the
line, but we have got to stay with it and probably will need some
resources,'' he said.
   He said the fire season in the Pacific Coast states is now
beginning, ``so while we may be able to see some control occur in
the Montana-Wyoming-Yellowstone area, it may be starting up in the
West and that is going to demand more resources.''
   ``We could well be moving a lot more military resources into
this,'' the spokesman said. ``I would expect that out of this trip
will come some recommendations along this line.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan called the meeting after Sen. Alan
Simpson, R-Wyo., told the president during a meeting with
Republican congressional leaders on Wednesday that he ``wanted to
express the anguish of his constituents and others in the region''
who have lost homes and jobs because of the fires.
   The spokesman said Reagan received a status report at Thursday's
meeting saying that 2,600 firefighters from 39 states were fighting
34 major blazes covering 1.5 million acres.
</TEXT>
