<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Fires 2ndLd-Writethru a0653 09-08 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Fires, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0653,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet-Level Team Sent to Gauge Need for Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 15th graf, Of 13 fires, to delete reference to
Peterson, who no longer head of forest service.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today dispatched a
Cabinet-level team to the West to see what additional federal help
is needed in fighting forest fires, and the White House said the
number of troops on the fire line is likely to be increased.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan met with Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng, Interior Secretary Donald Hodel and Deputy
Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV.
   The three official are expected to leave for the West tomorrow.
Fitzwater said they would visit Yellowstone National Park and other
areas suffering from fires that have now covered 1.5 million acres
in six states.
   Fitzwater said 2,500 military personnel are now fighting the
fires and this number may very well be increased.
   ``I would expect that out of this trip will come some
recommendation along this line,'' the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater said Reagan called today's meeting after Sen. Alan
Simpson, R-Wyo., expressed concern about the fire situation at a
meeting of Republican congressional leaders with the president on
Wednesday.
   Although some critics of the Park Service's policy of allowing
many fires that begin naturally to burn have called for the
resignation of the director of the Park Service, Fitzwater said,
``We have no plans to fire anybody.''
   He said Hodel, whose department encompasses the Park Service,
brought the subject of these calls for resignation up briefly
during the meeting but there was no discussion of it.
   ``Our feeling is that the Agriculture Department and the
Interior Department have responded very effectively'' and were
right to let the fires burn, Fitzwater said.
   The policy was abandoned July 22, he said, because of the
unparalleled intensity of the blazes.
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., met Wednesday with Hodel and
suggested that William Penn Mott, the Park Service director, ought
to resign.
   Hodel and Mott have clashed in the past, but today Hodel
rejected Wallop's suggestion, saying in a statement:
   ``I don't know anyone with greater love and concern for the
national parks than Bill Mott. He and the National Park Service
professionals advising him assure me they are doing everything in
their power. ... What they need at this time is our understanding
of the difficulties they face and our support.''
   In a news conference Wednesday, Mott and forest service
officials admitted that in hindsight they should have fought every
fire from the beginning.
   Of the 13 fires now burning in Yellowstone, five started before
July 22 and initially were allowed to burn. The other eight were
fought from the beginning, the officials said.
</TEXT>
