<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-08 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pathologist Says He Believes British Shot IRA On The Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British commandoes who shot to death three
Irish Republican Army guerrillas fired into the head of one Irish
nationalist as he lay bleeding on the ground, a pathologist
testified Thursday.
   Glasgow University Professor Alan Watson said at least four of
the bullets fired into the head of Sean Savage, 24, were fired
downward by a soldier as he stood over the IRA member's body.
   A second pathologist, called as a witness by the attorney for
the family, supported Watson's view.
   Watson, who conducted autopsies on the men, testified on the
third day of an inquest by Coroner Feliz Pizzarello and an 11-man
jury into the March 6 shooting deaths in this British colony of IRA
members Savage, 24, Mairead Farrell, 31, and Daniel McCann, 30.
   The IRA has acknowledged the trio were on ``active service''
when they were killed by British soldiers. The IRA regularly
employs the phrase to refer to members on missions to attack
British military targets.
   The inquest is being held to determine whether the shooting
deaths were lawful, but it has no power of prosecution. Still,
Gibraltar's attorney general is expected to return criminal
indictments if the jury finds that the killings were unlawful.
   A senior British intelligence official who testified Wednesday
said the British soldiers shot the three unarmed IRA members
because they wrongly believed they were armed and on the verge of
detonating a car bomb in the British fortress colony.
   The official, only identified as `O' for security reasons,
testified to the court behind a curtain.
   At the start of his testimony, Watson spent 10 minutes detailing
the wounds to the three IRA members.
   He said Savage was shot 18 times, five times in the back, five
times in the head and eight times in various parts of the body.
   Farrell received five shots to the head and neck and three shots
in the back, Watson said, while McCann received two bullets in the
head and two more in the back.
   Watson's statements were based on the post-mortem examination he
conducted the day after the shootings.
   Michael Hucker, the attorney for the seven soldiers involved in
the shootings and believed to be members of the elite British
anti-terrorist regiment Special Air Services (SAS), sought to show
that the soldiers believed the three men may have still been
dangerous despite having fallen to the ground.
   Watson said it would have been possible for the injured men to
push a button, a reference to the car bomb British intelligence had
thought the group was preparing to set off in the center of the
colony at Spain's southernmost tip.
   A second pathologist, Derek Pounder, professor of forensic
medicine at Dundee University in Dundee, Scotland, told the inquest
he also had concluded that Savage was shot in the head while lying
face-up on the ground.
   ``It is clear from the scrapes around the margins of the wound
(on the left side of Savage's neck) that the bullet was coming from
the feet of Mr. Savage,'' Pounder said.
   The intelligence official `O' told the inquest Wednesday that
British commandoes had been informed prior to the shooting that the
IRA members ``were dangerous terrorists who almost certainly would
be armed and, if confronted by Security Service personnel, would be
likely to use their weapons.''
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
say the killings were part of an unofficial ``shoot-to-kill''
policy against IRA members. British authorities said the three men
were planning a car bomb attack at the site where the Royal Anglian
Regiment band accompanies a weekly changing of the guard ceremony.
   The inquest, which is to hear about 70 witnesses, including the
seven soldiers involved in the shootings, is expected to continue
through the next four weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
