<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-08 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Down Military Plane, 2 Generals Among Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas shot down an Afghan
military transport plane, killing two army generals and all 14
other people aboard, Afghanistan's government radio said Thursday.
   It said insurgents brought the Antonov-32 transport down
Wednesday with a U.S.-built Stinger missile. The plane carried 12
passengers and four crew members, according to the Kabul radio
report.
   Among the passengers were two brigadier generals, Mohammed
Ismail Noori and Abdul Ahad Razmenda, and Col. Mohammed Hassan
Koshyar, political affairs director for military forces in the
Kunduz region, the radio said. It described Razmenda as a Defense
Ministry lawyer.
   The plane was bound from Kabul to Kunduz City, 160 miles
northeast of Kabul near the Soviet border, the broadcast said.
   Major battles between guerrillas and Soviet and Afghan forces
have been reported in the Kunduz area. Warplanes flying from Soviet
territory bombed insurgent positions late last month.
   The Soviet-made An-32 is a twin-engined turboprop that can carry
39 passengers, 30 paratroopers or 24 stretchers, and is built for
short runways.
   Soviet soldiers began withdrawing from Afghanistan May 15 under
a U.N.-mediated agreement and half the estimated 115,000 had left
by Aug. 15. All are to be gone by Feb. 15, 1989.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a Communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet military forces entered the country in December
1979. The insurgents were not a party to the agreement reached
April 14 in Geneva and have continued fighting.
   A separate Kabul radio report said two of Pakistan's U.S.-built
F-16 jet fighters intruded into Afghan air space over Asmar in
eastern Kumar province on a reconnaissance mission Wednesday.
   It also quoted the government as denying Pakistan's report that
an Afghan warplane was shot down Wednesday in Pakistani air space.
   Pakistan said Wednesday that four Afghan warplanes flew over its
territory near Nawagai, 12 miles from the border and one was downed
by Pakistani fighters.
   In Geneva, a U.N. official said Afghan refugees will be trained
to dispose of mines left by Soviet and Afghan government forces,
which are estimated to number from hundreds of thousands to
millions.
   The proposed program by the U.N. office coordinating aid for
Afghanistan also calls for public information campaigns to warn
women and children returning to the country about mines.
   ``The first step is to train one or two returnees per village to
have some idea of how to defuse a mine and dispose of it,'' said
the official, an aide to the chief of the Geneva-based office,
Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   More than 5 million Afghans have fled the country since the war
began and nearly all live in Pakistan and Iran, Afghanistan's
eastern and western neighbors. The Geneva agreement includes
provisions for their return.
</TEXT>
