<2ND_LINE>AM-Canyon Murders,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Are Charged in Notorious Murders of Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nightclub owner and his one-time
bodyguard were charged Thursday in the 1981 bludgeoning murders of
four people in a Laurel Canyon home, authorities said.
   Adel Nasrallah, also known as Eddie Nash, and his former
bodyguard, Gregory Diles, were charged with four counts of
first-degree murder and the attempted murder of a survivor, said
Andy Reynolds, spokesman for the district attorney's Office. If
convicted, the two could face the death penalty.
   The slayings, near a home owned by then-Gov. Edmund G. Brown
Jr., have been one of the city's most notorious unsolved murder
cases.
   Before his death, pornographic film star John Holmes was charged
and acquitted in 1982 of the slayings.
   Prosecutor Ronald S. Coen, now a Superior Court judge, alleged
at trial that Nash ordered the killings in revenge for a robbery at
his Studio City home a day earlier. Nash, who allegedly helped
supply Holmes with drugs, wasn't charged at the time because of
insufficient evidence.
   Killed were William DeVerell, 42, Joy Audrey Miller, 46, Barbara
Richardson, 22, and Ronald Launius, 37. His wife, Susan Launius,
was also beaten but survived.
