<1ST_LINE>r w AM-VietnamWomen'sStatue     09-08 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam Women's Statue,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Vietnam Women's Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scaled-down version of a Senate-approved
bill authorizing a monument to American women who served in the
Vietnam War was approved Thursday by a House subcommittee.
   The Senate bill, approved 96-1 in mid-June, specifies that a
bronze statue of an Army nurse be erected on the 2.2-acre grounds
of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial near the Lincoln Memorial.
   But the measure approved Thursday by the House Administration
subcommittee on libraries and memorials, written as a substitute
for the Senate version, says only that a monument to the 10,000
American women who served in Vietnam can be built somewhere on
federal land in the Washington metropolitan area.
   This will force separate votes by Congress on a specific site
and design for the monument, as well as review by three federal
agencies.
   Critics including Sen. Daniel J. Evans, R-Wash., who cast the
dissenting Senate vote, say a women's statue would violate the
artistic integrity of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial and create a
``sculpture garden'' for special-interest groups.
   The names of more than 58,000 U.S. military personnel killed or
missing in the Southeast Asian conflict, which are inscribed on the
black granite wall of the Vietnam memorial, include those of eight
female nurses.
   Some critics have suggested that a tribute to women who served
in Vietnam might be included in a monument to all women of the U.S.
armed forces, which is to be built at the entrance to Arlington
National Cemetery.
   The proposal to erect a women's statue at the Vietnam memorial _
the most popular tourist attraction of all national monuments in
Washington _ has been endorsed by the Interior Department but
opposed by the Commission on Fine Arts and the National Capital
Planning Commission.
   The approval of all three federal agencies is required for the
site, design and construction of any federal monument.
   If the full House Administration Committee approves the
subcommittee's version, as expected, a House vote is tentatively
scheduled for Sept. 19, followed by Senate action.
   Any such monument would be built with private funds and
maintained by the National Park Service.
</TEXT>
