<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-RedArmy     09-08 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Red Army,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports: Japan Warns Of Renewed Threat To Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion-dollar kidnapping ransom could be
bankrolling efforts by the Japanese Red Army to disrupt the
Olympics, Japanese news reports said Friday.
   The reports quoted police sources as saying that the Red Army
masterminded a 1986 kidnapping in the Philippines that netted the
terrorist group up to $3 million in ransom.
   Japan warned foreign countries Thursday that the Red Army's
possible windfall from the hefty ransom would increase dramatically
the chances that the terrorist group is planning to disrupt the
Games, which begin a week from Saturday in Seoul, South Korea.
   Red Army members who are under arrest or being sought by
international security authorities used Filipino operatives to
cover their tracks, police sources were quoted in the reports as
saying.
   Nobuyuki Wakaoji, then 53 and head of the Philippine branch of
the Japanese trading giant Mitsui and Co., was kidnapped in
November 1986 by a gun-wielding band of Filipinos as he was
returning home from a golf game.
   He was released four and a half months later after Mitsui
reportedly paid a ransom of up to $3 million. Police, Wakaoji and
Mitsui officials have denied knowledge of any ransom.
   The case strained relations between Manila and Tokyo and
resulted in a drop in Japanese tourism to the Philippines and
worries over Japanese investment in the Southeast Asian country.
   Red Army members Osamu Maruoka, 37, arrested in Tokyo last
November for traveling on a forged passport, and Norio Sasaki, 40,
who is wanted for traveling on a bogus passport, were behind the
kidnapping, the reports said.
   Night duty officers at the National Police Agency and Foreign
Ministry said they could not confirm the reports.
   When Maruoka was arrested he had a one-way plane ticket to
Seoul, leading police to suspect he was planning to set up or make
contact with a radical network to interfere with the Olympics.
   The reports did not say how police concluded that Wakaoji was
kidnapped by the Red Army. It did say that the kidnappers' skillful
manipulation of the Japanese media and similarities with a bungled
Red Army kidnapping case in West Germany in 1974 led police to
suspect a connection with the Japanese terror group.
   ``I never thought it might have been the Red Army,'' Wakaoji
told Kyodo News Service in a telephone interview early Friday.
   ``When I was taken there was no sign of any Japanese, and the
Filipinos spoke among themselves in Tagalog. They never spoke the
names of Maruoka or Sasaki,'' said Wakaoji, who now heads Mitsui's
Sapporo branch in northern Japan.
   The Red Army, formed in the late 1960s, was behind a machine gun
and grenade attack on Lod Airport in Israel in 1972 that left 26
people dead.
   Suspected groups of Red Army members hijacked a Japan Air Lines
jet to North Korea in 1970 and another JAL plane to Saudi Arabia in
1977.
   Italian police are looking for two Red Army members believed to
be behind a bomb blast outside a U.S. military club in Naples in
April. The same month another suspected member was arrested in the
United States in possession of a large amount of explosives.
   The group called for ``simultaneous world revolution'' and had
an estimated 300 members in its heyday. It had been dormant for a
decade until the spate of arrests and incidents in the last year.
</TEXT>
