<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Women,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Prods Congress On Women Appointees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan reminded Congress on Thursday
that some 10 million more women than men will be voting this fall,
and criticized legislators for not acting on some 40 female
appointees he's named.
   ``The hand that pulls the voting lever rules the nation,''
Reagan quipped at a Rose Garden ceremony honoring a group of female
administration executives.
   The Republican party is said to suffer from the so-called gender
gap, in which the party has a lower level of support from women
than the Democrats.
   But Reagan argued against that idea, saying he believed that
neither men, nor women, vote as a bloc.
   ``They look at the record and vote on the issues _ and those are
the people who, on election day, will decide the outcome,'' Reagan
said.
   The president took the opportunity to lambast Congress, faulting
the fact that some 40 females he's nominated to senior executive,
advisory and judicial posts have not been approved.
   ``The liberal ledership in the Senate can talk about their
interest in women taking senior positions in government, but
they're not delivering,'' Reagan charged.
   ``They say they applaud the idea of putting more women on the
bench. Well, if so, let them expeditiously move to confirm the five
excellent judicial nominees they have before them,'' Reagan said.
   In his remarks, Reagan boasted that out of the 10 women who have
served in Cabinet posts, four have served during his term.
   He also noted that he had been the first to appoint a woman,
Sandra Day O'Connor, to the Supreme Court.
   ``You do represent the leading edge, as I say, of the great
progress for American women, and because of what all of you and so
many other women have done, even greater opportunities for women
lie ahead,'' Reagan said.
   ``The progress that we're witnessing is just the beginning and
it can only move in one direction: it can only move forward,'' he
added.
