<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GatorPoaching     09-08 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gator Poaching,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Face Federal Charges For Poaching On Preserve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOXAHATCHEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were charged with poaching an
alligator, less than a week into Florida's legal alligator hunt.
   One of the men, 20-year-old Eric Brooks, had lost in the lottery
to license 238 hunters, said Burkett Neely, manager of the Arthur
R. Marshall Loxahatchee National Wildlife Refuge.
   Each licensed hunter is permitted to take up to 15 gators in
designated areas this month as part of the state's first hunt in a
quarter-century. But no one is permitted to hunt alligators or
disturb any animal or plant in the refuge.
   John Tommie, 24, was allowed to post bond Wednesday, and Brooks
was likely to be released Friday, according to attorneys.
   Brooks and Tommie, who said they work as roofers in Loxahatchee,
were arrested Monday as they drove out of a refuge entrance.
   They were wet after their canoe tipped in the L-7 canal and they
had a .22-caliber rifle, a flashlight and a 28-inch section of
alligator tail, Neely said.
   After the arrest, ``Brooks stated that he and Tommie knew there
were lots of `lizards in the canal' and decided to go out and get
some,'' court documents said.
   Later, the officers found a dead, tailless alligator with
multiple gunshot wounds, Neely said.
   Although estimates place the alligator population in Florida at
1 million, federal law considers the alligator to be ``threatened
by similarity,'' Neely said.
   He said that the American alligator looks similar to the
American crocodile, which is endangered. In order to protect the
refuge's crocodiles, alligators are also protected.
</TEXT>
