<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCHomicides     09-08 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Homicides,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capital Homicides Already At Total For Previous Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With almost four months remaining in 1988, the
nation's capital has matched the number of homicides _ 227 _ that
occurred in all of last year.
   The shooting death of the latest victim, a 17-year-old boy, was
drug related _ as were three out of every five of the homicides
this year, police said.
   ``Homicides and shootings go hand in hand with drugs,'' said
Metropolitan Police Chief Maurice Turner.
   In addition, the number of assaults involving guns have climbed
to more than 940 so far this year, an increase of at least 54
percent, Turner said.
   ``The numbers are astounding,'' he added.
   Until the demand for drugs decreases, Turner predicted the city
will see ``more homicides and more shootings.''
   Police spokesman Capt. William White III estimated that if
homicides continue at the current pace, 335 persons will be killed
in Washington this year _ far exceeding the all-time record of 287,
set in 1969.
   So far, 95 homicides this year, including the latest, remain
unsolved.
   During August, there were 41 Washington homicides, a record for
one month. The old standard of 37 was set in January.
   Police blame the upsurge on the growing popularity of crack, a
highly-potent cocaine derivative.
   Many of the killings have come in turf battles as drug dealers
have fought for selling rights for the drug in the city's 88
open-air drug markets, according to police.
   Of the 227 homicides so far this year, 156 have involved
firearms, White said. Last year, guns were used in 129 homicides.
</TEXT>
