<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FetusTransplant     09-08 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fetus Transplant,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah Fetus With Lethal Heart Defect May Receive Transplant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `Greggory' is cq in 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HILARY ISRAELSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors in a California hospital will
search for a donor heart to be transplanted into a child at birth,
an operation performed only once before, officials said Thursday.
   Cynthia Petersen of Murray, Utah, who is 33 weeks pregnant, was
to fly to Loma Linda University Medical Center on Thursday night to
await a suitable donor heart for her fetus.
   ``Baby Paul'' from Canada is the only other baby with the heart
defect known as hypoplastic left ventricle to have had a transplant
right after birth, doctors said. The baby, who was operated on at
Loma Linda 11 months ago, is growing normally, authorities said.
   Mrs. Petersen's obstetrician found an abnormal fetal heart beat
during a pre-natal examination and referred her to Dr. Greggory
DeVore, director of the Intermountain Fetal Diagnostic and
Treatment Center at Salt Lake's LDS Hospital.
   DeVore said the left chamber of the heart does not develop with
the fetus' condition, and most babies who have it die within three
to four weeks of birth.
   Doctors at Loma Linda will monitor the fetus while they look for
a donor. If a donor is found, DeVore said doctors will perform
surgery immediately following the birth.
   ``When the baby is born, the immune system of the infant is not
yet keyed in to reject a donor organ, '' DeVore said.
   ``We know there is only a 50 percent chance they will even
locate a donor, but we are optimistic,'' said Mrs. Petersen's
husband, Daymon.
   ``The more people know about this, the better,'' Mrs. Petersen
said.
   The fetus was named Whitney Ray Petersen in advance by his
parents. The Petersens have two other children, a 5-year-old girl
and a 2-year-old boy. Petersen is a maintenance worker for the Utah
National Guard and Mrs. Petersen is a nurse.
   The Petersens' insurance company will not cover the
$100,000-plus pricetag of the surgery. The couple said they don't
know how they are going to pay it.
   DeVore said Mrs. Petersen and the baby will be required to stay
near the hospital for about a year following the operation.
Petersen said he would return to Utah after his wife is settled at
Loma Linda and will try to visit her whenever finances permit.
</TEXT>
