<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfTalks     09-08 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Talks May Move to New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's foreign minister said Thursday his
delegation will stay in Geneva as long as needed, but the stalled
U.N.-mediated peace talks with Iraq may adjourn soon and move to
New York.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati accused Iraq of
trying to ``derail the discussions'' by introducing such
``extraneous elements'' as freedom of navigation in the Persian
Gulf and conflicting claims to the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which
forms the southern frontier.
   Velayati told reporters Iran ``is eager to continue these talks
at any level deemed appropriate by the secretary-general.''
Negotiations began Aug. 25, five days after a cease-fire halted the
8-year-old war, with U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
as mediator.
   Velayati said Iran agreed in principle ``with small
reservations'' to a compromise formula proposed by Jan Eliasson,
the Swedish diplomat who has temporarily replaced Perez de Cuellar
as mediator, but Iraq rejected it. He gave no details.
   Asked in an interview with Iran's official news agency whether
he foresees early adjournment and a shift of venue to New York, the
site of U.N. headquarters, Velayati replied:
   ``Yes, I think. It will start in maybe two or three weeks from
now, but the ending of this round of talks depends on the decision
of the secretary-general.''
   Velayati said his delegation is ``prepared to stay here as long
as necessary'' and has no objection to resuming direct talks with
the Iraqis, which have not been held since Aug. 26.
   He thanked the U.N. for ``tireless and sincere'' efforts toward
peace.
   In Israel, a military analyst said the United States caused Iran
to accept a cease-fire by increasing its naval strength in the
Persian Gulf.
   Aharon Levran said the war stalemated when Washington sent more
ships in July 1987 to protect shipping, and ``Iran realized that if
it couldn't win the war while confronting Iraq alone, it certainly
could not do so after a superpower like the United States came to
the gulf.''
   Levran, an analyst with Tel Aviv University's Jaffee Center for
Strategic Studies, was elaborating on the center's annual Middle
East Military Balance report, published last month. He is a reserve
brigadier general and edited the study.
   Iran accepted the U.N. Security Council's cease-fire resolution
a year after it was adopted unanimously in July 1987.
</TEXT>
