<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietSpacecraft 1stLd-Writethru a0686 09-08 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Spacecraft, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Spacecraft Could Endanger Sun Study</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd to UPDATE with no mention in Soviet
media.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists have lost contact with
an unmanned spacecraft hurtling toward Mars, one of two probes
designed to orbit the red planet and study its moon Phobos, a NASA
official said Thursday.
   A Soviet message to NASA headquarters in Washington didn't say
whether the problem endangered Phobos 1's mission to Mars, said
Raymond J. Amorose, Deep Space Network operations manager at the
space agency's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   ``They said they had lost communications with Phobos 1 ... but
Phobos 2 is in fine shape,'' he said. ``They have not asked for our
help. We have offered, and they said they do not need our help
yet.''
   Soviet media was silent on the matter Thursday.
   The problem is jeopardizing a joint U.S.-Soviet study of the sun
planned for this month, the Los Angeles Times reported Thursday.
   Phobos 1 was to have worked with NASA's Solar Maximum
spacecraft, which has been orbiting Earth for almost a decade, to
view the sun from different angles, providing the first
stereoscopic images of the sun.
   Phobos 1 was launched July 7 and Phobos 2 on July 12. During the
$480 million mission, the two probes were scheduled to go into
orbit around Mars and just behind Phobos in January so they could
study the Martian surface, atmosphere and magnetic field.
   Plans called for Phobos 1 to drop a lander onto the moon Phobos
on April 7, and for Phobos 2 to deploy its lander _ nicknamed the
``hopper'' because it literally would hop around the moon's surface
_ on May 25, Amorose said.
   Starting Oct. 10, NASA was to help track both probes with its
Deep Space Network, which consists of 230-foot, dish-shaped radio
antennas in Goldstone, Calif.; Canberra, Australia; and Madrid,
Spain, Amorose said.
   The purpose is to help the Soviets ``navigate the spacecraft to
their aim points at Mars'' and also help receive data transmitted
to Earth by the two probes, he added.
   Solar Max and Phobos 1 were to perform their solar studies later
this month and again after Phobos 1 deploys its lander.
   The images from the spacecraft would allow scientist to study
the narrow layer of hot gases on the sun's surface, said research
scientist Keith Strong of Lockheed Missiles and Space Co. in Palo
Alto, Calif.
</TEXT>
