<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LotteryReaction     09-08 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery Reaction,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors: Lottery Winner Thought Prize `Too Big'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTER SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sheelah Ryan was ``just churning
inside'' when she walked over to her neighbors' house and blurted
out that she had won the record $55 million Florida lottery, says
her friend Nancy Damron.
   And Ms. Ryan, 63, kept saying, ``Everything is just too big.
It's just hard to believe.''
   When Ms. Ryan showed up at their door on Tuesday, ``She was so
upset she could hardly talk,'' said Mrs. Damron. ``I thought, `Oh,
my God, something's wrong.''
   But she only wanted Mrs. Damron and her husband, Jim, to watch
her neat mobile home and her cats and feed the wild birds that come
to her yard daily, because she would be out of town for a few days.
   Was it an illness or a death in the family? the Damrons wondered.
   Then she told them, ``I'm sure I won the lottery.''
   ``I don't think Sheelah really believed it herself when she came
over,'' Mrs. Damron said.
   ``She told us she had already gotten a lawyer and they'd called
Tallahassee, so she knew she had the right numbers,'' Mrs. Damron
said.
   Ms. Ryan flew to the capital Wednesday and presented her ticket,
becoming the richest lottery winner in the U.S. history.
   Before she returned to this Central Florida community, phone
calls began pouring into her home. They included calls from
well-wishers, marriage proposals, requests for money and people
claiming to be relatives, said two security guards who fielded the
calls.
   One caller even wanted her to accompany him on a trip to India.
   In an interview Thursday on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' Ms.
Ryan said, ``The only downside is my lack of sleep and what I feel
is a great deal of stress for doing something that I'm not familiar
with, and that is being in the limelight.''
   A person answering the phone at her house Thursday afternoon
said she was spending the day with friends.
   After realizing she had the winning numbers in Saturday night's
drawing, Ms. Ryan contacted two attorneys. On their advice, she
spent the Labor Day weekend at home.
   She said she became upset about speculation on television about
who the Lotto winner was, and the story that a North Florida school
janitor claimed to have the winning ticket.
   But the part-time real estate saleswoman told a press conference
at the Lottery Department's headquarters that her main reason for
coming forward Wednesday was not to dispel the rumors.
   ``I came forward to pick up $55 million,'' she said. ``No one
waits for that kind of money.''
   Ms. Ryan, who is single and lives alone, didn't tell reporters
what she plans to do with the money. And the Damrons said they
could only guess.
   ``One thing she said she'd like to get is a car that wouldn't
wake up her neighbors every time she starts it,'' Damron said,
pointing toward Ms. Ryan's well-worn Mercury.
   ``She told me she'd kind of like to stay here with her friends
and maybe even keep her job,'' Mrs. Damron said.
   Ms. Ryan's only real hobby is her cats, they said.
   ``She just adores those cats,'' Mrs. Damron said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
