<HEAD>NKorea Complains About Seoul Addressing General Assembly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Korea-40 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea accused America and Japan on
Thursday of trying to involve the United Nations in a scheme to
perpetuate the division of Korea by inviting South Korean diplomats
to address the General Assembly.
   North Korean Ambassador Pak Gil Yon told reporters ``attempts to
create an atmosphere for creation of so-called `two Koreas' on the
40th anniversary of the establishment of the South Korean
government will only help expand the confrontation between the
North and South.''
   South and North Korea are not member nations of the United
Nations, but have permanent observer missions.
   Pak was reacting to a request by the United States, Japan,
Britain, Canada, Costa Rica, Colombia, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Oman
and Morocco that South Korea be allowed to address this fall's
General Assembly on the occasion of its anniversary as an
independent nation.
   Pak complained that the discussion ``will involve the United
Nations and its members in the crafty moves of the United States
and South Korea to have the present division of Korea and the
so-called `two Koreas' legalized.''
   ``The United States and Japan are working to get the United
Nations and its members entangled in their attempts to freeze the
division of Korea,'' he said.
   Pak asked the sponsors to withdraw the request.
   The United Nations sponsored national assembly elections in
South Korea that resulted in creation of the Seoul government on
Aug. 15, 1948.
   U.N. officials wanted to hold the elections in the entire Korean
peninsula, but Soviet occupation forces that remained in the North
after World War II refused to allow them into the North.
   The Communists in the North announced formation of their
goverment on Sept. 9, 1948. Both governments claim to represent the
entire Korean peninsula.
</TEXT>
