<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolBusing     09-08 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Busing,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts 17-year-old Desegregation Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has lifted a 1971
court order which required the desegregation of Duval County
schools by crosstown busing.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II on Tuesday declared the
school system is integrated and lifted the 17-year-old order,
effectively removing the federal role in the district's
desegregation efforts.
   Moore said he examined the status of students, faculty,
transportation, extracurricular activites and facilities and
determined that segregative practices do not exist.
   He rejected a 1985 lawsuit by the NAACP alleging that the
original 1971 order was not being followed, and also then lifted
the order itself.
   ``I live here, work here and go shopping here,'' the judge
wrote. ``And the feeling I get is that the leadership of the NAACP
is promoting this lawsuit, contrary to the rank and file of the
black people of this community.''
   Despite the ruling, Willye Dennis, the leader of the
Jacksonville branch of the NAACP, said the civil rights
organization stands by its claim that the school system is not
desegregated.
   ``We need to get the message out to the community that if this
case is not appealed, we are going to be in a bind,'' she said,
adding that a decision has not been reached on whether to appeal.
   As a result of the ruling, the school system will be free to
redraw boundary lines, reduce crosstown busing and set its own
standards for an integrated school system, said Jannell Byrd, an
attorney for the NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund in New York
City.
   School Board Chairman Billy Parker said Thursday that there
would be no immediate changes, but he predicted that at least 25
percent of the students now being bused could be returned to
neighborhood schools next fall.
   Parker said ``some busing for racial desegregation will continue
in places where it is impossible to return to local schools and
still keep an integrated school system.''
   ``There's no question that every place where youngsters can
return to neighborhood schools, a move will be made to do so,'' he
said.
   The school system has 104,000 students, 35 percent of them
black. About 30 percent of the teachers and 25 percent of the
faculty are black, the court order said.
   Duval County buses 20,000 students each day. Officials have said
that 45 percent of the busing is for integration. Many students
riding buses from 25 minutes to an hour each way during the school
year.
   In his ruling, Moore said the school system had done a
reasonable job of attempting to maintain racial balance at the
schools, but he said practical problems got in the way.
   Moore wrote that Duval County is so large, about two-thirds the
size of Rhode Island, that it is difficult to rectify racial
imbalance brought about by shifts in population patterns by busing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
