<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoPhones     09-08 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Phones,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hinsdale Fire: Not Arson, But Probe Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire that cut telephone service for 42,000
customers for as long as 26 days was not arson but the cause is
still unknown, according to a report Thursday.
   A preliminary report on the fire that destroyed an Illinois Bell
Co. switching station in Hinsdale offers few conclusions, but said,
``No evidence has been found that the (blaze) was deliberate.''
   The report was prepared by Forensic Technologies International
Corp. of Annapolis, Md., and adopted as the official, preliminary
summary by the staff of the Illinois Commerce Commission.
   ``Clearly there is international interest in what is going on
with this investigation,'' said ICC spokesman David Farrell.
``Other telecommunications companies throughout the world want to
prevent what happened in May in Hinsdale.
   ``This appears to be one of the largest telecommunications
disasters that has ever occurred,'' he said.
   Forensic Technologies is expected to release its final report in
November, Farrell said. The company was hired by the ICC, but
Illinois Bell is paying the bill _ $290,000 so far, he said.
   At first, the Mother's Day fire was expected to be only a minor
inconvenience for residents in Du Page County. But as Illinois Bell
crews examined the damaged hardware, it was clear that what became
known as the Great Phone Outage would last more than a few days.
   It wasn't until June 4 that full telephone service was restored.
   The fire in the switching station started in the ceiling, in
metal trays that hold cable above the telecommunication equipment,
the report said.
   ``The fire department's use of water produced an immediate
reduction of flame and heat,'' the report says. ``However, because
the building power supply was designed to be very reliable, the
source of electric power was continuous and the fire rekindled.
   Illinois Bell is conducting its own investigation and expects to
release its report in November, spokeswoman Pat Montgomery said.
</TEXT>
