<HEAD>Vice President's Oldest Son Reprises Pearl Harbor Gaffe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's son defended his father's error
on the date of Pearl Harbor Day but in the process got it wrong
himself during a radio talk show Thursday.
   Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, said during a
speech to the American Legion Wednesday that the Japanese attack on
Pearl Harbor occurred on Sept. 7, 1941 _ not on Dec. 7, one of the
best-known dates in U.S. history.
   George Bush Jr., during a discussion about the campaign with
Michael Jackson, the syndicated talk show host, lamented on
Thursday that ``the problem is that so much of what we see in
presidential politics is the 15-second sound bite on TV.''
   ``Last night for example, the 15-second sound bite on my dad on
the national networks was the fact that he slipped for 45 seconds
on whether Pearl Harbor was on Sept 9 or Dec. 9.
   ``And they made a big deal of that on TV. I didn't quite get the
point, because he, you know, corrected himself.''
   Jackson did not note the younger Bush's mistake during the
interview.
   Vice President Bush said Wednesday, ``I wonder how many
Americans remember. Today is Pearl Harbor Day. Forty-seven years
ago to this very day we were hit, and hit hard at Pearl Harbor. We
were not ready.
   ``In a Bush administration, that lesson would not be forgotten.''
   Within a minute or so, after prompting from the audience and
from others on the speakers' platform, Bush corrected himself.
