<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     09-08 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Flies Aid to Refugees; Flood Damage to Crops Estimated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army airlift is carrying relief
supplies to a refugee camp 500 miles southwest of Khartoum where 40
people a day have been dying of starvation, a newspaper reported
Thursday.
   Al-Ayam said the airlift had supplied the El-Meiram camp with
canned goods and 1,000 sacks of sorghum so far.
   Relief official El-Tayeb Tahir told reporters a trainload of
relief material arrived at El-Meiram last Monday and the Transport
Ministry had been asked to allocate one train a week for the south.
   Thousands of southern Sudanese displaced by civil war, drought
and recent floods have been moving north and many die of starvation
or disease on the way.
   On Thursday, a month after the floods, the government said it
estimates the damage to crops at about $365 million. Unofficial
estimates put the cost much higher.
   The Rev. Aengus Finucane, director of the Irish aid agency
CONCERN, said last month 40 people were dying every day at
El-Meiram and starvation threatened about 2 million Sudanese in the
south.
   According to Al-Ayam's report, the army stepped in when
international relief groups said they could not move goods to the
south because of the heavy rains and floods.
   It did not mention the proximity of rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army forces besieging Wau, 160 miles from the El-Meiram
camp.
   Rebel gunners shot down two civilian planes in 1986 and 1987 and
the insurgent army, led by former Col. John Garang, has threatened
to fire on relief planes. The rebels claim the government uses
civilian aircraft to move ammunition and troops.
   Garang's rebels began fighting the Moslem-dominated Khartoum
government in 1983. They seek autonomy for the south, most of whose
people are Christians or animists, and claim to control more than
90 percent of the countryside.
   Tahir said without elaboration that contacts were under way on
arrangements for international agencies to fly aid to the south,
but a Western official said privately the rebels were reluctant to
approve such an airlift.
</TEXT>
