<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Senate-Kurds     09-08 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-Kurds,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pell Proposes Sanctions Against Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation imposing sanctions against Iraq
for its purported use of poison gas against Kurdish inhabitants was
introduced on Thursday by Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., who told the
Senate ``A crime of unthinkable proportions is emerging.''
   ``For the second time in this century a brutal dictatorship is
using deadly gas to exterminate a distinct ethnic minority,'' said
Pell, the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   ``There can be no doubt but that the Iraqi regime of Saddam
Hussein intends this campaign to be a final solution to the Kurdish
problem,'' Pell said. ``While a people are gassed, the world is
largely silent.''
   The Iraqi embassy in Washington has denied that poison gas was
used against the Kurds, asserting that such charges have been
spread by Kurdish leaders living in Europe.
   The Pell resolution declares that the Iraqi actions against the
Kurds ``appears to constitute an act of genocide, a crime abhorred
by civilized people everywhere and banned under international law.''
   The resolution would ban all U.S. aid to Iraq, ban sales of U.S.
military equipment and ban the provision of credit or credit
guarantees. It would prohibit the transfer of sensitive technology
to Iraq and bar the import of Iraqi petroleum products into the
United States.
   It also would instruct the U.S. representative to the United
Nations to vote against all loans to Iraq.
   Pell noted that the Iraqi army moved against the Kurds after the
Aug. 20 ceasefire in Iraq's war with Iran with the objective of
ending Kurdish control over a large section of northeast Iraq.
   ``The offensive was accompanied by the dynamiting of Kurdish
villages throughout the region,'' Pell said. ``Poisonous gas was
used on the people.''
   ``It is said we do not have much influence over Iraq,'' Pell
said. ``This may be true, but I believe we must use whatever means
at our disposal to get their attention.
   ``The Iraqi regime is a vicious dictatorship toughened by years
of conflict,'' he said. ``Hand wringing alone will not change their
course; immediate action is essential.''
</TEXT>
