<HEAD>Officials Say President's Health Is Good, But Rumors Persist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government spokesmen insist President
Alfredo Stroessner enjoys good health, but his absences from
official functions has provoked rumors that he is recovering from
surgery.
   ``I'm no doctor, but his health is very good,'' Mario Abdo
Benitez told a radio station Wednesday night when asked about
Stroessner's physical condition. He is the 75-year-old general's
private secretary and vice president of the ruling Colorado Party.
   Juan Jose Benitez Rickmann, the presidential press secretary,
was asked to comment on rumors that Stroessner had prostrate
surgery Aug. 31 at an Asuncion hospital. He replied that it was
only a checkup for a scheduled visit to Taiwan in October.
   Officials at the state-run Institute of Social Security Hospital
refused comment. Activity at the hospital was normal Thursday and
security precautions that usually signal the leader's presence were
not in evidence.
   Stroessner, who has ruled since a coup in 1954, was
conspicuously absent Wednesday at the commemoration of the death on
Sept. 7, 1940 of army Marshal Jose Felix Estigarribia. The marshal
led victorious Paraguayan forces in the 1930s Chaco War against
Bolivia and served briefly as president.
   The usual accounts of Stroessner's daily official activities
have been absent from newspapers and official radio broadcasts
since late last week. Stroessner normally arrives at his office
early and spends the day receiving delegations and attending to
state business.
