<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FloridaFloods     09-08 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Floods,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flooding Subsides, Some Evacuees Return to Soaked Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SPB1,2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half of the 1,000 people forced from
their homes by waist-deep water headed home Thursday as floodwaters
subsided, leaving roads passable and letting businesses and schools
reopen.
   Scattered showers continued Thursday, but Manatee County was
spared the torrential downpours of the previous three days that
turned streets into rivers. All but one school reopened Thursday.
   Damage in the rain-soaked Bradenton-Palmetto area of Tampa Bay
was estimated at more than $1 million. The area has been drenched
by more than 14 inches of rain this week.
   Gov. Bob Martinez planned to view the area by helicopter on
Friday.
   ``The heavy rains and flooding have caused a severe dispruption
in the lives of Manatee County residents and I want to see
firsthand whether condiions might require additional assistance
from the state,'' he said.
   The flooding was blamed on a near-stationary cold front hovering
across the central Florida peninsula. The National Weather Service
said the front Thursday was drifting north to the Tampa-St.
Petersburg area, where the Red Cross opened two shelters for
possible evacuees from low-lying areas.
   The steady rains were expected to fade to occasional showers and
thunderstorms overnight.
   Floodwaters Wednesday swept away a motorist and drowned a
toddler, authorities said. James Edward Mercer, 45, was pulled
under by a strong current in a drainage ditch and presumed drowned.
He disappeared after a car stalled in the ditch and began to float.
   In New Port Richey, 2-year-old Matthew Rehm wandered behind his
home and drowned in a rain-swelled canal, authorities said.
   On Thursday, teams of inspectors went out at daybreak in
high-riding vehicles and airboats to evaluate neighborhoods along
the Manatee River, which overflwed Wednesday and forced the
evacuations.
   Homeowners near the river were advised to stay away one more day.
   Floodwaters in some areas had not receded significantly by
Thursday, and emergency crews said some riverside homes had several
feet of water inside, said Tom Strickland of the county's Emergency
Management Services.
   ``The problem now will be shelter fever and people not feeling
well because of high stress, worrying about their homes and
belongings,'' said Marilyn Sapharas, shelter coordinator at Christ
Episcopal Church, where nearly 200 people were staying.
   At the church shelter Thursday morning, children passed the time
watching television. Adults sat around tables in the parish hall,
talking, after a breakfast of scrambled eggs, sausages and biscuits.
   The elderly and frail were given quieter quarters in the library
and choir rooms of the church center.
   ``I'm worried about when I finally do get home, what condition
my furniture will be in and what kind of mess I'll find,'' said
Anne Williams, a single parent with five children ages 8 to 17.
``We'll have to start all over again.''
   Although disappointed, shelter residents were glad to be in
dryer quarters.
   ``It's nice here, no complaints,'' said Larry Hunter, 31, who
spent all day Wednesday helping neighbors evacuate through
knee-deep water. ``When they let us go home I hope I don't find a
snake or an alligator looking out at me,'' he said.
   Residents returning home were urged by county public health
officers to disinfect sinks and showers, discard any food touched
by flood waters and to check wells for broken pipes or flooding.
</TEXT>
