<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugBust     09-08 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Bust,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Seize 183 Pounds Of Heroin Found In Bean Sprout Machine</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ALAN COOPERMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the bean sprout washing machine was shipped
from Hong Kong, police were waiting. When they opened its hollow
steel rollers, they found 183 pounds of nearly pure heroin worth up
to $260 million on the street.
   On Thursday, after six men were arrested in the case, state and
federal law enforcement officials said the heroin seizure was one
of the largest in U.S. history.
   ``This is a very rare event to see this much heroin concentrated
in one location,'' said John J. Coleman, special agent in charge of
the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in New England.
   He said the heroin was probably enough to supply all the addicts
in New England for more than a year.
   State police and U.S. Customs officers, acting on confidential
information, were watching for the machine when it arrived by truck
at a Boston warehouse Aug. 30. According to court documents, they
replaced most of the heroin with sand and waited for someone to
claim the device.
   The heroin was hidden in the airtight, stainless steel rollers
of the machine, said Coleman.
   Four men were arrested Tuesday after they allegedly picked up
the machine in a rental truck, distributed parts of it to two
locations in Boston and then took the remainder to a scrap metal
dealer.
   Undercover DEA agents later delivered some of the heroin to New
York City, where they arrested two more men Wednesday night.
   All six suspects have been charged with possession of heroin and
conspiracy to distribute the drug, said Frank L. McNamara Jr., U.S.
attorney for Massachusetts.
   McNamara said authorities believe the men are important figures
in the drug trade, not merely ``mules,'' or carriers of drugs, and
may have ties to Chinese organized crime groups.
   Police in Hong Kong have conducted several raids in recent days
in connection with the case, but no arrests have been made there,
he said.
   Five cardboard cartons of heroin were displayed at the news
conference, along with the disassembled parts of the bean sprout
machine, a contraption of prongs and rollers used by Oriental
restaurants and produce merchants.
   ``The concealment effort was outstanding,'' said Williams S.
Simmons, acting special agent in charge of the U.S. Customs Service
for the Northeast region.
   Regional Customs Director Philip W. Spayd said the amount of
heroin seized was one of the largest in the country and the largest
ever in New England. Approximately 200 pounds was discovered in a
shipment of ice buckets in Seattle in 1985, and 378 pounds was
found in Miami in 1971.
   Once diluted, the street value of the seized heroin would have
been between $200 million and $260 million, he said.
   Police said the four men arrested in Boston were of Vietnamese
origin and gave their names as Hung Ta, 24; Dang Phu, 23; Hieu Ly,
24; and Tuong Luu, 45. They were in the custody pending arraignment
Friday.
   The two men arrested in New York were identified as Wai Kwok
Wong, 40, and Sik-Sze Yan, 36. McNamara said they are of Chinese
origin. They appeared Thursday before a federal magistrate in U.S.
District Court but did not enter pleas and were held without bail
pending a detention hearing Sept. 14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
