<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-08 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Continue Along South Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The only rain in the nation Thursday was in the south Atlantic
Coast states and Florida, and Tropical Storm Florence stalled far
out in the Gulf of Mexico.
   Florence was about 500 miles south of New Orleans on Thursday
afternoon, with winds up to 55 mph. Florence has moved only
slightly north since its inception Wednesday.
   As long as Florence continues in the Gulf, seas and swells will
build throughout the Gulf of Mexico.
   Rains in the south Atlantic coastal states and Florida were
gradually spreading to the north and west as southeast winds pushed
a warm front back to the northwest.
   Breezy conditions continued across the north-central part of the
nation. Winds gusted to 45 mph across parts of North Dakota.
   A cold front extended across the upper Mississippi Valley and
the central Great Plains. The front has produced few clouds or rain
due to the lack of moisture.
   Thursday afternoon temperatures were mostly in the 70s over the
Atlantic coastal states, the Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio
valley.
   Readings were in the 80s across the middle and lower Mississippi
Valley and the central Plains, with some lower 90s in Texas.
Temperatures were also in the 80s to lower 90s across the southern
Plateau region. Temperatures were also in the 80s to lower 90s in
southern Florida. Readings in the desert Southwest were in the 90s
to near 100 degrees.
   To the north, temperatures were in the 60s and 70s from the
upper Mississippi Valley across the northern Great Plains, the
northern Rockies and the Pacific Northwest. Readings in the desert
Southwest were in the 90s to near 100 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 102 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The low in the nation Thursday was 23 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo., and about 20 cities set low temperature records.
   Friday's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms across the
middle and southern Atlantic coastal states, the southern
Appalachians and the central Gulf Coast. Showers and thunderstorms
were to be most numerous over Georgia, Alabama and northwest
Florida. Widely scattered showers were predicted for western New
York and eastern Michigan.
   High temperatures were to be in the 70s and 80s across most of
the nation. Readings were expected to climb to the 90s over the
southern Great Plains, New Mexico, the central and southern Plateau
and southwest Oregon. Highs were to be in the 90s to near 105
degrees over the desert Southwest and interior valleys of
California.
</TEXT>
