<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DyingRefusenik     09-08 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dying Refusenik,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Jewish Mathematician Denied Exit Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 63-year-old Jewish ``refusenik'' dying of
cancer has again been denied permission to leave the Soviet Union
for urgently needed medical treatment, a Soviet Jewry group said
Thursday.
   The Union of Councils for Soviet Jews said it had learned that
Soviet authorities have refused to grant an exit visa for Georgi
Samoilovich, a Moscow mathematician suffering from a deadly throat
lymphoma.
   Last month, Samoilovich was removed from a waiting list to enter
the Blokhin Cancer Institute in Moscow for treatment.
   Samoilovich has been seeking permission to emigrate to Israel
for 11 years. His wife, a physician, also is a refusenik.
   Americans who have been urging the Soviet government to let
Samoilovich emigrate include Dr. Richard Rosenbluth, chief
oncologist at Hackensack Medical Center in Hackensack, N.J.
   ``We will be starting a last, desperate, all-out campaign to
save his life, and I hope the world will be with us,'' Rosenbluth
said.
   Soviet authorities have been denying Samoilovich permission to
emigrate on grounds that he once did classified research work. But
Rosenbluth noted that Samoilovich ``has not worked in his
profession in over 10 years.''
   ``The injustice of this case is overwhelming, especially in
light of the new humanitarian facade the Soviets are putting on,''
Rosenbluth said.
</TEXT>
