<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsInstitutions     09-08 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Institutions,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deposits Flow Out For Third Consecutive Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposits flowed out of the nation's savings
institutions for the third consecutive month in July, the
government said Thursday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said net withdrawals from the
3,088 savings institutions were $123 million in July after hitting
a revised $3.3 billion in June, up from a previous estimate of $2.9
billion.
   In May, S&L customers withdrew $1.1 billion. But, before that
deposits grew for seven consecutive months as investors battered by
the October stock market crash sought a safe haven for their money
in government-insured accounts.
   Bank Board economist James Barth said in a statement that a
slowdown in withdrawals is normal for July. Consumers typically
take money from their accounts at the start of summer to pay for
vacations and other seasonal expenses.
   Mortgage lending by thrift institutions in July declined to
$21.1 billion, 14 percent below the same month last year when many
people were refinancing their mortgages, the bank board said.
   Barth said the drop in mortgage lending reflects the climb in
interest rates this summer.
   The bank board also reported that the institutions' capital
declined by $573 million in July after falling by $3.0 billion in
June. For the first seven months of the year, it's off $6.4 billion.
   Declines in capital, which is the difference between an
institution's loans and other assets and what it owes to depositors
and other creditors, often reflect losses.
</TEXT>
