<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-FEC-PACs     09-08 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FEC-PACs,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Growth In Spending By PACS Slows As Races Are Less Competitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spending by political action committees to
influence the 1988 elections is on the increase, but the rise is
far smaller than in previous years, the Federal Election Commission
said Thursday.
   Several political scientists said the money figures compiled by
the FEC indicate that the PAC movement may be leveling off and
reaching its saturation point.
   The FEC said that for the 18 months ending June 30, PACs
representing business, labor, ideological and other interest groups
spent $215.4 million, a 4.8 percent increase over the same period
in the 1985-6 election cycle.
   The increase, however, was well below the 38 percent rise in PAC
spending that occurred in the corresponding 18 months of the 1985-6
cycle when compared to the 1983-4 cycle, which itself was up 44
percent over 1981-2.
   Receipts by PACs showed a similar slowing in growth. The $266.6
million collected during the first 18 months of the current cycle
was 4.7 percent above 1985-6, which saw 18-month receipts running
30 percent above 1983-4, which was 42 percent over 1981-2.
   As of June 30, PACs had given $94.9 million to candidates for
federal office: $3 million to presidential races, $32.7 million to
Senate candidates and $59.2 million to House candidates.
   This represented a 21 percent increase over the same 18 months
in 1985-6. This rate, however, was below the 38 percent rise from
1983-4 to 1985-6 and the 49 percent growth from 1981-2 to 1983-4.
   Incumbent senators and representatives got got nearly 90 percent
of the money contributed by PACs to congressional races in the
first 18 months of this election cycle. Democrats led Republicans
$60.9 million to $33.9 million.
   Norman Ornstein, a congressional analyst with the American
Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank, said the
double-digit percentage increases in PAC receipts and spending
couldn't continue indefinitely.
   ``We may have reached a saturation point,'' he said. ``That's
good news for all of us except campaign vendors.''
   Ornstein said that ``it's hard to say whether we've got a
long-term trend.''
   He said the reduced rates of increase could be partly
attributable to ``to so few competitive races in the House. There
isn't the demand from incumbents to put the screws to PACs.''
   Janet Grenzke, a political science professor at Holy Cross
College in Worcester, Mass., said the figures could indicate ``the
saturation point is nearing'' for PACs.
   ``Those people who were going to form PACs and who were going to
participate in the political process through them have pretty much
done so,'' Grenzke said.
   She said some political money that previously might have been
channeled through PACs now could be ending up as ``soft money,''
the less-controlled and little-reported cash flow increasingly
finding its way to places like political party committees.
   Herb Alexander, a political science professor at the University
of Southern California, said the number of PACs has leveled off, as
has the number of PACs that are really active.
   ``A couple of hundred PACs do half the business,'' he said.
``There's an ingrown limitation on how much they can raise. ...
While it's not at a standstill, the growth rate isn't as explosive.
...
   ``The PAC phenomenom is reaching a point of natural limits,''
said Alexander.
   Randy Huwa of Common Cause, the self-described citizens lobby
that has been urging Congress to outlaw PACs, said he was not
heartened by the latest FEC figures.
   ``The first thing I look at is contributions to candidates, and
that's continuing to grow,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
