<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-PoliticalLetter 1stLd-Writethru a062milliondrivers
09-08 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Political Letter, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Aid Dismissed After Dukakis Letter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS two grafs with comment by Clews.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Trade Commission aide has been
dismissed after sending a letter to newspaper editorial boards
criticizing Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Carter Clews, associate director for media relations, was
dismissed on Wednesday, said FTC general counsel Robert Paul, who
said his office has been assigned to investigate the case.
   The letter was sent Aug. 4 by Clews to newspapers, offering to
rebut criticism of the agency by Dukakis and questioning statements
made by Dukakis in a controversy over advertising by optometrists.
   Paul said he was not prepared to say whether Clews' action
violated the Hatch Act, which prohibits political acitvity by
federal workers. He said the investigation is continuing.
   Meanwhile FTC commissioners Mary L. Azcuenaga and Andrew J.
Strenio issued a statement dissociating themselves from a second
latter sent by Clews to broadcast talk show hosts offering
appearances by commission members.
   That letter contains a postscript saying that Dukakis has been
critical of the commission and adds that commission members are
willing to discuss the records of the FTC and of the Massachusetts
governor.
   Azcuenaga, an independent, and Strenio, a Democrat, said they
are happy to make appearances to discuss consumer affairs and other
commission activities but will not discuss candidates for public
office.
   Clews said later Friday, ``I don't believe I violated the Hatch
Act, and the general counsel himself has not said I violated the
Hatch Act. And if I had violated the Hatch Act, there are certain
procedures that by law they have to go through to give me a fair
hearing. None of that was done.''
   ``I think this whole thing is political and I was targeted
because Commissioner Strenio and Commissioner Azcuenaga want to
prevent Mr. Dukakis from being criticized for his own attacks upon
the commission. All I did was try to set straight the record of the
Federal Trade Commission,'' he said.
</TEXT>
