<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SunkenVessel 1stLd-Writethru a0596 09-08 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sunken Vessel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0596,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede OSLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Report Four Missing in Oil Rig Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An offshore oil rig explosion on
Thursday left four Indonesian workers missing in the Makassa
Strait, 935 miles northeast of Jakarta, a newspaper reported.
   The evening paper Suara Pembaruan said the search was continuing
for the missing workers of the French company Total Indonesie
operating off east Borneo. It gave no details about the cause of
the explosion or the extent of damage caused.
   Indonesian authorities were not immediately available for
comment.
   Earlier, Norway's national NTB news agency identified the
stricken facility as the 16,900-ton, Norwegian-owned drilling
vessel Viking Explorer and said it capsized and sank off the Borneo
island town of Balikpapan, with one Indonesian worker reported
missing.
   Both accounts said 100 workers were involved and NTB said all
but one man were rescued.
   NTB said three Norwegians were working on board during test
drilling. All the others were from the United States, Britain,
Canada, Singapore and Indonesia, it said.
   Total Indonesie is a major foreign oil firm operating under a
production-sharing contract with the state-owned Pertamina oil
company, the newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
