<DOCNO> AP880908-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NaziDenaturalization     09-08 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi Denaturalization,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Stripped Of U.S. Citizenship Because of Death Camp Activity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey man was stripped of his U.S.
citizenship Thursday after his attorney did not rebut government
claims that he served as a guard at a Nazi death camp during World
War II, federal prosecutors said.
   U.S. District Judge Clarkson S. Fisher ordered 62-year-old
Stefan Reger denaturalized after a telephone conference during
which Reger's attorney did not contest government motions for
summary judgment.
   Prosecutors alleged in court papers that Reger concealed his
wartime activities as a member of the SS Death's Head Battalion and
guard at the Birkenau section of the Auschwitz concentration camp
in Nazi-occupied Poland.
   The government said Reger was a native of Filipovo, Yugoslavia.
   In court papers filed in February, Reger acknowledged being a
member of Hitler's SS but denied guarding prisoners at Birkenau,
U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr., said in a statement.
   Alito said Reger is believed to be in Germany. Alito was not
available for further comment, and it was not immediately known
what further action the government might take against Reger.
   Reger, of the Trenton suburb of Yardville, has an unlisted
telephone number and could not be reached for comment. His son,
Michael, a contractor, was not at home Thursday and a woman who
said she was his wife declined to discuss the matter.
   Reger's attorney, John Barry, did not return a telephone message
left on his answering machine Thursday afternoon.
   Summary judgment occurs when attorneys ask that a judge rule in
their favor based on documents and testimony presented before the
case goes to trial.
   The Justice Department's Office of Special Investigations filed
a complaint in December 1987 seeking Reger's denaturalization. OSI
Director Neal M. Sher said Reger entered the United States in 1952
and became an U.S. citizen in 1957.
   According to the complaint, Reger, beginning in 1943, guarded
prisoners as they performed forced labor and were being transported
between camps.
   The complaint accused him of no specific acts.
   In his application to enter the United States, Reger said he
served in the 91st Grenadier Regiment of the German Army between
1943 and March 5, 1945, and as a Waffen-SS private until April 29
that year.
   Sher contended Reger should not have been allowed to become a
U.S. citizen because his activities during the war helped in the
persecution of civilians because of their race, religion or
national origin.
   The government's complaint said Reger joined the Waffen-SS in
1943 and served at Birkenau until January 1945, when he left to
guard a prisoner transport to another concentration camp.
   All documents related to the camps were destroyed by Hitler's
SS, making it difficult to determine how many people died at
Auschwitz, but the figure is put at 4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-House-Drugs 3rdLd-Writethru   09-08 0961</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Drugs, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0808,940</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs. bgng ``The death
penalty... to UPDATE with House adjourning, future schedule for
bill, and illegal evidence amendment. Pickup 4th graf pvs.
``Opponents of...federal assistance.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved amendments to an anti-drug
bill Thursday that would permit federal death sentences for
murderers in drug felonies and deny many federal benefits to anyone
convicted of two narcotics offenses.
   Sponsors of the amendments rolled over opponents with arguments
that these criminal and administrative penalties would deter those
who use and profit from drugs.
   The death penalty amendment authored by Rep. George Gekas,
R-Pa., passed 299-111 and the benefit denials _ sponsored by Rep.
Bill McCollum, R-Fla. _ was approved 335-67. The provisions were
attached to a bill that would add some $2 billion to the nation's
existing $3.9 billion attack on illegal drugs.
   The House was unable to finish the bill Thursday night, and is
not expected to resume debate until next Wednesday. Before ending
debate, the lawmakers voted 259-134 for an amendment that would
permit introduction of illegally seized evidence in federal court
if police acted in ``good faith.''
   Opponents of the benefit denials offered an amendment to water
down the potential loss of student loans, public housing, veterans
benefits and other federal assistance.
   But they couldn't sway their colleagues, even by pointing out
the amendment would prevent burial of Medal of Honor winners in
Arlington National Cemetery.
   Battered death penalty opponents had argued that capital
punishment wouldn't stop hardened drug killers from murdering
someone.
   The death penalty provision would give federal judges the option
of handing down a death sentence to anyone convicted of
intentionally killing someone during a drug felony.
   The House also approved, 410-1, a measure providing for a
mandatory life term for such killers. That language _ opposed by
Rep. George W. Crockett Jr., D-Mich. _ was proposed by death
penalty foes as an alternative, but those backing capital
punishment refused to stop there.
   McCollum's amendment would deny benefits for five years for
anyone convicted of two or more drug-related offenses within a
10-year period; and denial for 10 years for persons convicted of
drug distribution.
   Heads of federal agencies could restore benefits for those who
completed a drug rehabilitation program or were otherwise been
rehabilitated.
   Veterans benefits would be denied only to those convicted of
drug distribution. Retirement, welfare, health and disability
benefits would be exempted from the penalty.
   McCollum argued that ``education and rehabilitation are not
enough'' to stop demand and added, ``If we don't have a deterrent,
we won't win the war on the demand side. And if we don't win on the
demand side we won't win the war, period.''
   Rep. Dan Lungren, R-Calif., asked if the House wanted to let a
drug trafficker send the message that ``I got involved in drugs in
Vietnam and therefore I'm excused.''
   Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y., whose watered down version of
the benefit denials failed 278-124, told the House that entire
families in public housing could be thrown into the street if the
head of household had two drug convictions.
   And he asked, ``Does it make any sense, on the eve of
graduation, that we would cut off benefits'' to college students?
   Gekas said the death penalty amendment would provide a ``swift
and certain'' deterrent against drug killings.
   A Democratic supporter, Rep. James A. Traficant Jr. of Ohio,
said, ``Drug dealers don't have to read anyone their rights. The
drug dealers who kill have no conscience.''
   Rangel, D-N.Y., said the sentiment for capital punishment was
linked to the upcoming election.
   ``We're now reaching the point, because it's on the eve of an
election, that we may find ourselves thrown into a position where
we have to explain to voters ... just who was the toughest on crime
... who was the toughest on drug traffickers,'' Rangel argued.
   ``Sometimes it's those who say `Let's kill the rascals' who
prevail.''
   Rangel said 36 states already have the death penalty, and ``if
the other 14 states want it, they can get it.''
   While the Senate has yet to consider its own anti-drug bill, it
already has expressed sentiment on capital punishment this year. A
separate bill approving the death penalty against drug dealers and
kingpins passed in June by a 65-29 margin.
   In 1986, the Senate's refusal to support the death penalty in
drug-related murders resulted in Congress eliminating the measure
from an anti-drug bill that year. The House had inserted capital
punishment in the 1986 bill by a vote of 296-112.
   Off the House floor, members were pressured by gun-control
advocates and opponents over a provision for a seven-day waiting
period for handgun purchases. The language also includes an
optional background check of the purchaser by law enforcement
authorities.
   The National Rifle Association is lobbying to remove the waiting
period, and pro-regulation groups are trying to save it. Both sides
have brought police officers to the Capitol to help in the lobbying
effort.
   Gekas' death penalty provision would permit _ but not require _
a judge to impose the death sentence on anyone convicted of
intentionally killing someone during a drug felony.
   If the death penalty was not imposed, the amendment would
require a sentence of 20 years to life.
   The Senate legislation approved last June would permit the death
penalty for narcotics dealers convicted of murder in drug crimes;
and for drug ``kingpins,'' defined under law as those who supervise
five or more people, commit at least three federal drug felonies
and derive substantial income from a continuing criminal enterprise.
   Most federal death penalty provisions are not enforceable
because, unlike some state laws, they were never brought into
compliance with Supreme Court guidelines on capital punishment..
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880908-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Diplomat-Gun     09-08 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diplomat-Gun,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Diplomat to be Questioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese diplomat who allegedly waved a gun at
protesters will surrender his immunity so British government
officials can question him, the Foreign Office said Thursday.
   Vietnamese Ambassador Tran Van Hung ``handed over a toy gun
which he said was the weapon the official had brandished'' in front
of Vietnamese refugees demonstrating outside the Vietnamese Embassy
on Sunday, a ministry spokesman said.
   During a meeting Thursday afternoon with Junior Minister Timothy
Eggar, the ambassador agreed the diplomat, third secretary Khang
Than Nhan, will surrender his immunity and visit the Foreign Office
for questioning, said the spokesman.
   It has not yet been decided whether police will attend the
interview, he said, speaking on condition he not be identified.
   The Foreign Office on Wednesday warned the ambassador he could
expect ``the gravest consequences'' if he refused to allow the
diplomat to be questioned. It also insisted the embassy surrender
any other weapons.
   Vietnamese protesters sent two photographs of the diplomat
holding a gun which were published Wednesday in the Daily Express
newspaper.
   The pictures showed a man with a pistol standing on the steps of
the embassy. The paper said the demonstrators were Vietnamese
refugees opposed to the current communist regime.
   Under the terms of the 1961 Vienna Convention on diplomatic
practice, embassies are treated as foreign territory.
   Although diplomats and other embassy staff are required to obey
local laws, they cannot be prosecuted unless the country concerned
agrees to waive their diplomatic immunity.
</TEXT>
