<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Burma 1stLd-Writethru a0790 09-08 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0790,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Finds Exile in Europe Discussed for Ne Win</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with House passing resolution, INSERTS two grafs
after 2nd graf bgng ``Rep. Stephen J. Solarz ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former leader Ne Win appears to be retaining
some control over the Burmese government and one suggestion in the
South Asian country's deepening crisis is for him to go into exile
in West Germany or Austria, a congressman just back from Rangoon
said Wednesday.
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., told reporters that hundreds of
thousands of Burmese have already demonstrated ``they are ready to
lay down their lives'' for freedom, and the population will not
retreat from demands for swift change from dictatorship to
multi-party democracy.
   Also on Wednesday, the House approved by unanimous consent a
resolution introduced by Solarz urging democratic change in Burma.
   The resolution called for ``the establishment of a transitional
body, consisting of Burmese citizens who are unquestionably
committed to democracy and who have the confidence of the Burmese
people, to organize the holding of multi-party elections and
otherwise facilitate the establishment of a genuinely democratic
government.''
   Solarz, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on
Asian and Pacific affairs, met numerous prominent Burmese during a
24-hour stopover in Rangoon last weekend en route home from Moscow
and Beijing. They included President Maung Maung, Prime Minister
Tun Tin and several student and opposition leaders, he said.
   A solution mentioned in the developing showdown is for Ne Win to
leave Burma, perhaps for West Germany, where he has spent time in
the past, Solarz said.
   ``As for West Germany, the potential role they have to play is
in terms of willingness _ if Ne Win expressed interest in leaving
the country _ to facilitate resolution of the crisis in permitting
him to go there,'' the New York Democrat said.
   If Ne Win decided to leave, West Germany ``is one of the places
he might choose to go to. The other leading contender is Austria,''
Solarz said, recalling his conversations with Burmese.
   Although Ne Win resigned July 23 as head of Burma's ruling
Socialist Program Party, Solarz said his talks in Rangoon gave him
``the impression that Ne Win continues to call the shots ...
   ``Virtually everybody I spoke to said he was not managing day to
day affairs, but there was the sense that no decision may be made
without his consent. There was also some evidence that key people
in government are beating a steady path to his door,'' he said.
   Solarz said the proposal of Ne Win's successors for a party
congress next week followed by a referendum on multi-party
democracy came too late and is ``utterly unacceptable to the
people.'' This is because the government has lost all credibility
and the proposal is regarded as a maneuver to cling to power, he
said.
</TEXT>
