<HEAD>Embezzling UC Chancellor And Wife Get 5-Years Probation, Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chancellor of the
University of California at Santa Barbara and his wife, convicted
of embezzlement and tax evasion, were sentenced Wednesday to five
years probation.
   Former chancellor Robert Huttenback also was ordered to pay
$60,000 in fines for one count of embezzlement and two counts of
tax evasion.
   Huttenback, 60, was also ordered to serve 1,000 hours of
community service.
   His wife, Freda, was fined $10,000 for one count of embezzlement
by Superior Court Judge Zel Canter.
   The Huttenbacks were convicted of siphoning more than $200,000
from university funds to remodel their home.
   Santa Barbara County Assistant District Attorney Patrick
McKinley had sought jail terms for the Huttenbacks. Defense
attorneys moved for a new trial, but the motion was denied.
   Huttenback, who resigned his post under pressure when the
embezzlement became known, declined comment after sentencing.
   Huttenback, a history scholar specializing in British
colonialism, served nine years as chancellor of the scenic coastal
campus about 100 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
