<HEAD>Woman Says Car Seized Because Friend Purchased Pipes In Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Ms. Miller ... with 2 grafs to CORRECT
spelling of woman's name to Cantrell, sted Cantrall, and UPDATE
with decision to return the car; edits grafs 8-10 to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose car was seized at the border
because agents found two 50-cent pipes from Mexico says the agency
carried Zero Tolerance too far.
   A U.S. Customs Service spokesman in Houston confirmed that no
drugs were found but said Teresa Miller's car was seized Sunday
because of ``paraphernalia.''
   Custom officials said Thursday the car would be returned.
   Ms. Miller, who lives in suburban Houston, said Wednesday that
her friend, Valerie Cantrell, bought the pipes in Mexico, where the
two had gone shopping.
   ``It's appalling,'' said Ms. Miller, 27, a clerical worker at a
Pasadena law office. ``I'm an American citizen, and I should have
rights. First off, they (the pipes) were not even mine.''
   Ms. Cantrell, 23, who also does clerical work at the law office,
said the onyx pipes were among several knick-knacks she bought and
were a gift for a friend. Ms. Cantrell said neither she or Ms.
Miller use drugs.
   The seizure, at the U.S. port of entry at Progreso, stems from
the administration's Zero Tolerance policy, designed to curtail the
demand for drugs, Customs spokesman Charles Conroy said.
   Customs officials announced Thursday afternoon that they would
release the car back to Ms. Miller if she or someone else returns
to Progreso and claims it, and Conroy said it had been decided that
no charges would be filed.
   ``That seizure has been canceled by the U.S. Customs Service,''
Conroy said. ``We considered all the facts involved and the
circumstances in the case and came to the conclusion that the
seizure did not fit the spirit and intent of the Zero Tolerance
program.''
   Conroy said he was not aware of any decision to reimburse Ms.
Miller for her additional travel expenses. Houston is about 350
miles from Progreso.
   The women said they had been told that the car, on which Ms.
Miller still owes $5,800, would be put up for auction if the appeal
was rejected.
   Chris Peacock, a spokesman for U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas,
had said the matter was being looked into. He added that five
complaints had been received in the last month about seizures along
the Texas border.
   Conroy said that from March 21, when Zero Tolerance took effect,
through June, 474 vehicles have been seized in the Customs
Service's southwest region _ Texas, Oklahoma, Arizona and New
Mexico.
</TEXT>
