<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DeltaCrash-Transcript 2ndLd-Writethru a0828 09-08 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Crash-Transcript, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0828,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Union Criticizes Leak of Cockpit Recording Transcript</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The transcript ..., to make co-pilot's name
Carey, sted Casey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transcript of cockpit conversation on Delta
Flight 1141 reveals the crew knew their jetliner was in serious
trouble about 21 seconds before it crashed Aug. 31 at Dallas-Fort
Worth International Airport, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   The transcript of a tape shows that about nine seconds after an
apparently normal takeoff, a cockpit alarm showed the Boeing 727
was not able to gather enough speed to stay aloft, the Dallas Times
Herald reported.
   The Salt Lake City-bound plane exploded and exploded and broke
apart on impact, killing 13 of the 108 people on board.
   Eleven secords before impact, Capt. Larry Lon Davis exclaimed,
``We're not gunna make it!'' One of the final entries on the
transcript appears to be a scream.
   The unauthorized release of the transcript drew sharp criticism
from John Mazor, spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association in
Washington, D.C., who warned, ``There will probably be some
repercussions.''
   It will be months before investigators pinpoint the cause of the
crash, but two primary suspects have emerged. They are wing flaps,
designed to give the plane lift, and engine problems during the
flight.
   The transcript reveals that flight engineer Steven Judd and
co-pilot Carey Kirkland went through a standard preparation
checklist.
   In the transcript, Kirkland told Judd that the flaps were
extended in the correct position for normal takeoff during the
checklist less than a minute before the plane received permission
for takeoff.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators said last
week that the cockpit recording indicates there were two compressor
stalls, which are disruptions of air flow, one each in two of the
engines.
   The transcript, however, notes five possible compressor stalls
within six seconds, a set of two followed within seconds by three
more, the newspaper reported.
   Investigators have not been able to determine whether any
compressor stalls actually occurred, safety board officials said.
The engines are to be tested at the Pratt & Whitney manufacturing
plant in East Hartford, Conn.
   Mazor said he believes the transcript, which he said appears to
be a very relevant portion of the cockpit tape, may have been
released ``to point the finger (of blame) away from whoever was
doing the leaking,'' but said he would not speculate on who that
may have been.
   The release of one piece of evidence in an investigation that
make take nearly a year is ``folly'' and may lead people to draw
wrong and unfair conclusions, Mazor said.
   ``This has happened many times in the past, and we've complained
many times in the past,'' Mazor said.
   He said the pilots union may consider filing a complaint with
the National Transportation Safety Board, which is investigating
the crash, about the transcript's early release.
   ``We got it from an investigator,'' said Ray Herndon, an
assistant managing editor of the Times Herald, but the newspaper
would not disclose what agency the investigator worked for.
   A spokesman for the transportation safety board in Washington,
D.C., said the board also is upset that a major portion of the
transcript was leaked to the newspaper.
   ``We're upset because that transcript is an unauthorized,
preliminary and incomplete version,'' said the NTSB spokesman,
Michael Benson. ``By law, that transcript is not to be released for
60 days. We make every effort to ensure the transcript is
confidential.''
   Benson said there is no way to determine who gave the transcript
to the Times Herald. ``A number of parties have access to that
transcript,'' including the pilots union, he said.
   Benson said NTSB officials are reviewing security procedures to
see if they must be changed to prevent such documents from being
leaked to the press in the future.
</TEXT>
