<1ST_LINE>u w AM-RowanHospitalized 1stLd-Writethru a0850 09-08 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowan Hospitalized, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0850,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with nine grafs adding detail, eyewitness account;
picks up 4th graf pvs, Rowan, 52; Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan was rushed
to Georgetown University Hospital when he fainted after giving a
speech Thursday night, hospital officials said.
   Rowan's condition and the cause of his collapse were not
immediately available, but Georgetown University spokesman Jim
Kurtzke said the columnist was ``alert, he's conscious, he's
sitting up.''
   An ambulance dispatcher, who would not give his name, said Rowan
was taken to the hospital about 9:11 p.m. EDT for apparent heat
exhaustion.
   Rowan was leaving a lecture hall at American University after
giving a speech on the presidential campaign when he collapsed, a
student who was nearby said.
   ``He walked up the stairs, paused, and was leaning forward over
a sign,'' said Michelle Karpf, a freshman at American.
   ``He said, `Oh, it's kind of warm in there,' and he wasn't
feeling well,'' she said. ``I looked back over, and he was lying on
the ground.''
   ``He was holding his chest,'' Karpf said. ``Nobody really knew
what was going on. People were running around going, `Does anybody
know CPR?'''
   About a dozen people were around Rowan trying to ask questions
when he collapsed, she said.
   ``He was conscious when they took him away,'' in the ambulance,
Karpf said.
   Rowan, 52, has been the target of national publicity recently
for shooting a teenage intruder who had taken an unauthorized
midnight dip in Rowan's back yard swimming pool.
   The columnist, generally known for his liberal views and an
outspoken opponent of handgun use, is scheduled to stand trial
Sept. 22 on charges that he used an unregistered handgun and
ammunition in the June 14 shooting.
   Rowan has argued that the weapon and bullets were given to him
by his son, Carl Rowan Jr., a former FBI agent, who has said he was
told by District of Columbia officials that he did not have to
register the weapon.
   The district's far-reaching 1976 handgun ordinance requires that
all weapons be registered.
   If convicted on both misdemeanor charges, Rowan faces a maximum
penalty of two years in prison and $2,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
