<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Justice-CivilRights     09-08 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Civil Rights,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Charges LA County With Vote Bias Against
Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department sued Los Angeles
County and its top officials Thursday, alleging that the county's
1981 redistricting plan has denied Hispanics equal voting rights.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, seeks to invalidate
the electoral boundaries set for the county's five elected
supervisors, and to devise a new plan that complies with federal
law.
   County Board of Supervisors Chairman Deane Dana said the lawsuit
was expected, and added it is ``unfortunate that the Justice
Department has elected to take its action so near to the 1990
census.''
   Supervisor Mike Antonovich agreed, saying ``It makes more sense
to wait 16 months for the next census than to use antiquated
statistics from 1980 as the basis for reapportionment.''
   Antonovich also denied that there has been any pattern of racial
discrimination by the Board of Supervisors. However, leaders of
local Hispanic and civil rights groups welcomed the suit as long
overdue.
   ``I think it makes it utterly uncontestable that there can be a
continuation of the white enclave that has governed Los Angeles
County,'' said Mark Rosenbaum, an attorney with the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   The 1981 districts were ``gerrymandered to dilute the power of
latino communities to elect a leader of their own choosing,'' said
Alan Clayton, a California representative for the League of United
Latin American Citizens.
   A discrimination case also was filed against the county last
month by the ACLU and the Mexican American Legal Defense Education
Fund, which called the Board of Supervisors ``the most exclusive,
most powerful whites-only club in the nation.''
   The Justice Department's suit most likely be consolidated with
the suit filed by the ACLU and MALDEF, Rosenbaum said.
   The county, which has an annual operating budget of about $8.9
billion, comprises an estimated 8.5 million residents, with each
supervisor representing between 1.6 million and 1.7 million people,
Clayton said.
   A similar Justice Department discrimination suit was filed
aginst the city of Los Angeles in 1985, leading to a settlement
that radically revised City Council districts in the San Fernando
Valley and in East Los Angeles.
   The federal lawsuit charges that the county's electoral plan
fragments the county's geographically cohesive Hispanic community,
thus denying Hispanics an equal opportunity to participate in the
political process and to elect candidates of their choice to the
county governing body.
   Named as defendants, in addition to the county, were the Board
of Supervisors; Dana; Antonovich; and Supervisors Peter F.
Schabarum, Kenneth Hahn, Edmund D. Edelman, and Registar-Recorder
Charles Weissburd.
   Schabarum did not immediately respond to a telephone call
seeking comment, and Edelman declined to comment.
   Hahn said in a prepared statement, ``I believe this could have
been avoided if this past June 21st, the Board of Supervisors had
approved my motion to place a measure on the November ballot to
expand the board to seven members.''
   The Justice Department suit alleges that in 1970, Hispanics
numbered 1,289,311, or 18.3 percent of the total population. In
1980, the suit says, the county's Hispanic population rose to
2,066,103, or 27.6 percent of the total population of 7,477,503.
   Blacks comprised 12.4 percent, or 926,361, and Asians and
Pacific Islanders 5.8 percent, 434,850, of the 1980 population.
   The suit says the Hispanic population stretched from the City of
Los Angeles on the west to the San Gabriel Valley on the east,
comprising about 73 percent of the more than 1.2 million people
residing in the 230 contiguous census tracts and constituting what
is called a ``community of interest.''
   The 1981 reapportionment plan adopted by the Board of
Supervisors divided the concentration of Hispanic voters into three
districts, with the result that Hispanics did not constitute a
voting-age majority or plurality in any of the five single-member
districts.
   Clayton charged that the county also has systemically
discriminated against Hispanics in its employment policies. He
cited a recent study that found that Hispanics make up about 18.3
percent of the government's work force, while county hiring goals
call for a 27.6 percent representation.
   The Justice Department complaint says that non-partisan
elections in Los Angeles County, including those for the Board of
Supervisors, are characterized by patterns of racial and ethnic
bloc voting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
