<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-BehindtheWheel ADV17-18   09-08 1018</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, ADV 17-18,1046</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 17-18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Voyager Gives Huge Impression</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It doesn't seem quite right to use the word huge
when talking about a minivan, but that's the impression the 1988
Plymouth Voyager LE conveys.
   It also is comfortable, easy to drive and versatile.
   Want to take that antique table (with two leaves and four
chairs) off Aunt Ruth's hands? Pull out the two back seats of the
van and tuck the dining set inside for the trip home. No problem.
   And the furniture won't get wet or dirty, as it would in the
back of a pickup during inclement weather. Have five young
ballplayers to take to the park? Put the rear seats back in and
there's room for equipment and another adult _ and no one is
cramped.
   It's no wonder Chrysler Corp. has sold more than 1 million of
these little-big gems since the automaker pioneered the minivan
concept in the 1984 model year.
   Today, bigger automakers such as Toyota, Ford and General Motors
have joined the market, but Chrysler retains the sales lead.
Toyota's van is sold in smaller quantities and has a higher base
price for the cheapest passenger model (about $13,200 vs. about
$11,000 for a Chrysler).
   The Ford and GM downsized vans are rear-drive and a bit larger
than Chrysler's. One auto analyst has called the minivan the
product success of this decade, and some analysts predict annual
industry sales of 1 million in the next decade.
   Chrysler's idea for the minivan was to provide a fuel-thrifty
way to cart around passengers and cargo comfortably in a roomy
vehicle that would drive like a car and fit in a garage like a car.
   Chrysler has stayed true to that concept, as the test Plymouth
Voyager LE bore out. It was easy to drive and felt like a car, even
during difficult parallel parking maneuvers.
   Driving in some other, especially full-size, vans can give a
distinct bus-like feel as you turn the steering wheel and maneuver.
Getting in and out of the Voyager was uncomplicated compared with
some other vans where you have to climb up to enter and take a
flying leap to exit.
   But like other vans and unlike a car, the Voyager _ 64.4 inches
tall _ offered a good view of the road ahead. I appreciated being
able to spot potential slowdowns in traffic and parking spots in
shopping center aisles.
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Jakobowski noted company research shows
the low step height and low loading height are among the main
reasons for the minivans' popularity.
   Women like that, he said, adding that 37 percent of buyers are
female. Buyers' median age is 39, with median annual income of
$45,000, he said. Fifty-six percent are college graduates and as
many as 45 percent have professional-technical-managerial jobs.
   The Voyager test vehicle had superb fit and finish, inside and
out. The side door slid open easily for passenger exit.
   The rear seats were arranged so two people could sit comfortably
in the middle seat and three adults could fit in the seat behind
them. Both seats could be removed with a bit of effort after
detaching locks that held the seats to hooks in the floor.
   Be sure to check that the locks hold when replacing the seats
or, whoa, you might flip backwards. Bucket seats were in the front,
with space between them so a person could climb into the back
without going outside.
   But the van's roofline is low, so adults do have to hunch over
when moving about inside. There was some room behind the rear seat
for cargo storage, enough to stand up several grocery bags.
   If more room is needed, there's a lever to pull so the the rear
seat advances on a track. The seat back also can be folded down. In
the 1987 model year, Chrysler also introduced a longer minivan, the
Grand Voyager, which is 14 inches longer than the regular Voyager
and offers more cargo space behind the rear seat.
   Both the regular and elongated vans have a lifting rear door so
you don't have to hoist items up and over the vehicle body. I also
appreciated the rear window being all one piece. In some other
vans, such as the Chevrolet Astro, there is a pillar in the center
which reduces rear viewing.
   Also changed from the earliest Chrysler minivan models are the
engine options. The base engine for a Voyager has gone from a
2.2-liter four-cylinder powerplant to a 2.5-liter four-cylinder.
   Also offered is an optional 3-liter V-6, which boosts
performance but decreases fuel economy. The test model had the V-6
paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. The V-6 certainly
is an improvement over the standard four-cylinder, but I had to put
in 15.3 gallons of gasoline after 263 combined city-highway miles.
   That worked out to around 17-18 miles per gallon.
   There were nice touches throughout. Because the engine and
components take up much of the small hood and under-the-dash space,
Chrysler tucked the drawer-ike, locking glovebox under the
passenger-side bucket seat.
   There was a center console on the ceiling that included map
lights for driver and front-seat passenger, sunglasses storage and
a spot for garage door transmitter. In the rear, there were two
compartments for storing small items and spots to rest two cups.
   Outdoor enthusiasts who tow boats, campers, etc. will note that
Chrysler's front-drive configuration does limit towing capacity,
however. With the standard 2.5-liter four-cylinder, the Voyager can
handle up to 2,000 lbs. with the V-6 and Class II frame-mounted
trailer hitch, it can take 2,750 lbs.
   In contrast, many rear-drive vans can handle bigger loads.
   Consumer Reports says 1984-86 Plymouth Voyagers have ranked
average or above average in reports of trouble.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
