<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-08 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0585</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has filed
civil insider trading, fraud and stock manipulation charges against
the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., Michael Milken,
the head of its junk bond trading unit, and others.
   In the 184-page civil complaint, filed Wednesday at U.S.
District Court in New York, the SEC said it would seek to have the
defendants surrender profits made on the affected stock trades and
pay a penalty of three times the profits. The firm and Milken
reiterated previous statements denying any wrongdoing.
   The suit capped months of speculation that the government had
assembled an extensive case against the firm as a result of the
investigation into Wall Street abuses spawned by the Ivan Boesky
insider trading scandal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Morgan Stanley & Co. rookie analyst,
Stephen Sui-Kuan Wang Jr., 24, has pleaded guilty to the first
criminal charges stemming from what the government has called the
second-largest insider trading case in Wall Street history.
   In another insider trading development on Wednesday, a fired
Merrill Lynch & Co. stockbroker, William Dillon, 34, pleaded guilty
to fraud after admitting he traded securities based on advance
knowledge of the contents of a stock-touting column in
undistributed copies of Business Week magazine.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's commercial banks enjoyed their
most profitable six months on record through June this year,
despite continuing losses in Texas, the government reports.
   Commercial banks earned $10.5 billion in the first and second
quarters this year, topping the $9.7 billion in net income for the
second and third quarters of 1985.
   Also on Wednesday, a private panel of bankers, economists and
labor leaders released a report urging that banks and debtor
nations renegotiate existing loans rather than seek new ones to
help ease the $1 trillion Third World debt problem.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has come up with a
paperwork way to reduce the reported U.S. trade deficit by about $3
billion before the election, but officials denied that the
accounting change was politically motivated.
   Commerce Under Secretary Robert Ortner said Wednesday the change
made more sense economically.
   The new procedures will change how merchandise imports get
counted each month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Trans World Airlines Inc.
overwhelmingly have approved Chairman Carl C. Icahn's proposal to
buy their shares and take the nation's seventh-largest airline
private.
   But opposition to the move mounted Wednesday among TWA employees
as the 3,300-member pilots union sued Icahn in New York State
Supreme Court to block the privatization.
   Airline industry analysts estimate the Icahn bid puts a value of
around $40 a share, or $304.8 million, on the TWA shares that Icahn
doesn't already own. TWA stock closed at $36.75 on the New York
Stock Exchange, up 37{ cents a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has issued a restraining
order temporarily blocking the $2.5 billion merger of Lucky
supermarkets into American Stores, saying the combination threatens
serious irreversible harm to Californians.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon said Wednesday he would hold a
hearing Sept. 16 on whether to grant a preliminary injunction
requested by California Attorney General John Van de Kamp.
   Van de Kamp wants a trial to decide whether the merger of the
two supermarket giants is anti-competitive.
</TEXT>
