<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The belief that the United States' economic
standing in the world will be rescued by emerging high-technology
industries is being questioned by a prestigious study group which
said the country is fast losing its dominance in many of these
fields.
   The Council on Competitiveness recommended Wednesday a major
effort on the part of government, industry and schools to reverse
the trend.
   ``We cannot afford any further erosion in our once-commanding
technological lead,'' said the council's report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has agreed to sell all 76 of its
Gold Circle and Richway stores for more than $325 million, the
Toronto-based retailing and real estate company said.
   The buyer, Kimco Development Corp., a privately-held owner and
manager of shopping centers, said Wednesday it had agreed to sell
31 of the stores to Dayton Hudson Corp. and to leas 35 to Hills
Department Stores and two to K mart Corp.
   Buyers or operators are still being sought for the other eight
stores, according to Kimco, which is based in Roslyn, N.Y.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board has granted Bank of
New York Co. up to 90 more days to complete its effort to acquire
Irving Bank Corp.
   The ruling Wednesday was a new blow to Irving's nearly year-long
struggle to avoid an unfriendly takeover by Bank of New York.
   Irving's hopes of thwarting Bank of New York faded last week
when Banca Commerciale Italiana dropped its friendly offer of $840
million, or $84 a share, for 51 percent of Irving's stock. The
Milan-based bank pulled out after an unfavorable Fed ruling on Aug.
19.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether driving a run-of-the-mill station
wagon or an expensive luxury car, the safest vehicles generally are
the largest, accordinbg to an insurance industry report.
   The report released Wednesday on injury claims involving 207
popular cars showed a wide range, as cars with the worst safety
record posted injury losses more than double those with the best
record.
   The annual report released by the Highway Loss Data Institute,
an insurance industry research group, reflects findings similar to
those in previous years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two dozen women's groups have
launched a campaign for legislation requiring large employers to
grant unpaid leave to parents of newborn or seriously ill children.
   ``If politicians truly want to capture women's votes, they must
go beyond pro-family rhetoric and photo opportunities with
children,'' Judith Lichtman, president of the Women's Legal Defense
Fund, said Wednesday.
   The groups, ranging from Church Women United to the National
Abortion Rights Action League, have mobilized in support of the
Family and Medical Leave Act tentatively scheduled for a House vote
Sept. 14.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved slightly higher Wednesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials rose 0.53 points to 2,065.79.
   Bond prices were little changed, moving slightly higher.
   The dollar ended mixed against major currencies. Gold prices
also were mixed.
   Coffee futures prices rose sharply for the second straight day,
cocoa futures were sharply lower, energy futures were mixed, grains
and soybeans were mixed and livestock and meat futures rose.
</TEXT>
