<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BizWeekProbe     09-08 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Merrill Lynch Broker Pleads Guilty to Second Criminal Count</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Insider Trading-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former stockbroker William Dillon has pleaded
guilty to another criminal charge stemming from his admissions that
he traded securities based on advance knowledge of a stock market
column that appears in Business Week magazine.
   ``I know what I did was wrong and I'm very sorry for what I did
and for the people who were affected,'' Dillon, 34, told U.S.
District Judge John M. Walker in Manhattan when he pleaded guilty
Wednesday to a single count of wire fraud.
   Dillon, who had worked in Merrill Lynch & Co.'s New London,
Conn. branch, was the first person to face criminal charges as a
result of a federal probe into insider trading on Business Week's
``Inside Wall Street'' columns.
   Dillon, who was fired by Merrill Lynch, already has pleaded
guilty to a separate wire fraud charge in federal court in
Connecticut, under an agreement with the government.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani stated that Dillon has been
cooperating in a continuing investigation of insider trading based
on advance knowledge of securities to be mentioned in Business Week.
   Last month, federal prosecutors charged that Dillon earned
$94,000 in illicit profits on trades of approximately 129
securities as part of the scheme, in which he would buy
undistributed copies of Business Week for as little as $20 each
from a worker at a plant where the magazine was printed.
   Dillon, who faces a maximum penalty of five years in prison and
a $250,000 fine for each fraud count, will be sentenced March 7. He
was released on his own recognizance.
   Several stockbrokers are under investigation in connection with
the Business Week scandal and others have resigned or been
dismissed. In addition, R.R. Donnelley & Sons Co., Business Week's
printer, has fired or disciplined several workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
