<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SovietPizza     09-08 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Pizza,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NJ Pizza Company Chief To Scout Sites For Restaurants In Soviet
Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If he can't teach them capitalism, at least
he'll give them heartburn.
   The man who brought American pizza to the Soviets via a roving
concession truck in Moscow now says he is working to establish the
Soviet Union's first full-fledged pizza parlor.
   Louis Piancone Sr., president of Roma Food Enterprises Inc. of
Piscataway, said Wednesday he plans to meet next week with Soviet
officials in Moscow and inspect several potential sites for a pizza
restaurant in the capital and two other cities.
   ``We are going to be looking at several locations in Moscow,
Riga and Tula,'' said Piancone.
   Piancone and his partner, Ukranian-born entrepreneur Shelley M.
Zeiger of Moorestown, entered a joint venture with Soviet officials
last year to bring the company's Astro Pizza mobile concession
truck to Moscow. The truck began selling slices of the American
fast food to tourists and Soviet customers in April.
   ``Our sales so far have been extremely lucrative,'' he said.
``This is just the next logical step.''
   To date the truck has been using ingredients purchased in Europe
and the United States because Soviet tomatoes, cheese and other
products were not readily available.
   Piancone said his trip will include a meeting with Soviet
Agriculture Ministry officials to discuss the feasibility of using
products grown locally.
   The mobile pizza parlor made a splash in Moscow when it began
operating on a snowy day in April, selling more than 1,200 slices
of the cheese-and-tomato pie in just three hours.
   Since opening, Piancone said the truck has operated three days a
week for tourists, accepting only Western currency, and three days
a week for local customers, selling slices for 1.25 rubles, roughly
just more than $2 a slice. The truck does not make rounds on the
seventh day.
   Piancone said it was always his intention, and the intention of
his Soviet partners _ who by law own 51 percent of the enterprise _
to open permanent restaurants around the country.
   He said the company is concerned that competitors may take the
initiative away if Astro Pizza Ltd. doesn't move quickly.
   PepsiCo. Inc. and Pizza Hut Restaurants earlier this year
announced their intention to open two restaurants in Moscow.
Piancone said neither has opened yet.
   But he said a Baskin Robbins ice cream parlor opened in the
lobby of a Moscow hotel. The ice cream parlor does not accept
Soviet currency, which is not readily convertible on currency
markets.
   ``I think the people in Moscow kind of resent that approach,''
Piancone said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
