<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Delors     09-08 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Delors,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Chief Says Single Market Doesn't Threaten National Identity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOURNEMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The creation of a single European
market in 1992 won't undermine the national identities of the 12
member countries of the European Economic Community, an EEC chief
said Thursday.
   Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, promised
delegates to the Trades Union Congress' annual conference that
workers' rights will be respected when the community eliminates
national trade barriers in four years.
   ``You, dear friends, will remain British. We will all maintain
our individual ways of life and our valued traditions,'' Delors
told the delegates, who represent 9.1 million workers from 85
unions affiliated with the national labor federation.
   Delors said the post-1992 single market of 320 million Europeans
will create new job opportunities and better living standards for
workers.
   Meanwhile, Delors said, the EEC will spend 40 billion pounds, or
about $70 billion, in economically deprived regions of Europe to
reverse industrial decline, fight long-term unemployment, develop
rural areas and provide jobs.
   The community's member countries are Belgium, Denmark, France,
Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal,
Spain, Britian and West Germany.
</TEXT>
