<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-S&LCrisis 1stLd-Writethru f0021 09-08 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Crisis, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$2 Billion S&L Bailout Under Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 12 grafs new with today's hearing, edits throughout to
tighten; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the House Banking Committee today
criticized regulators' use of promissory notes to rescue insolvent
savings institutions as a ``shell game'' designed to push the
problem into the next administration.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates the nation's
3,000 savings institutions, has pledged more than $12 billion over
the last three weeks to rescue or close 48 savings institutions,
including 21 in Texas and 14 in Oklahoma, states hard hit by the
depression in the oil industry.
   However, much of the assistance has been in the form of
interest-bearing notes, which will obligate the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp. to billions of dollars in payments a year for
the next decade.
   The plan ``seems to be nothing more than a massive shell game in
which insolvent institutions are reshuffled, the names changed, and
little if any real capital injected, resulting in thinly
capitalized weak institutions,'' said Rep. Charles E. Schumer,
D-N.Y.
   ``Many of these institutions will ultimately have to be bailed
out again at even greater cost to the taxpayer,'' he said.
   Schumer said the bank board's strategy would ``postpone the day
on which the bill for this crisis becomes due until long after the
members of the current administration have left Washington and are
sitting on a beach somewhere.''
   However, Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, who is asking
Congress to put the full faith and credit of the U.S. government
behind the notes, said the notes, because they are tax free and
carry a low interest rate, are the most effective way to close down
insolvent thrift institutions that are draining the industry's
health.
   Wall said his agency had $10.1 billion in the notes outstanding
at the end of August and said by the end of this month it will have
spent billions more to resolve the cases of 65 more ailing thrifts.
   Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., chairman of the committee,
was particularly critical of the $2 billion rescue earlier this
week of American Savings and Loan Association in Stockton, Calif.
   The Robert M. Bass Group, the investment arm of a Fort Worth,
Texas, billionaire, is spending $550 million and getting $2 billion
in assistance from FSLIC to acquire American. It is the
largest-ever rescue of a single savings institution.
   Part of the deal allows Bass to use $1.5 billion of American's
funds for merchant banking activities such as acquisitions of
commercial companies.
   ``Frankly, I am concerned when notes ... are utilized to promote
risky ventures such as merchant bank subsidiaries,'' St Germain
said, warning thatr, ``the industry as a whole can be expected to
take this as a green light to again reach for the riskier
operations.''
   The Bass group has been an active player in corporate takeover
battles in recent years. It is currently pushing a $1.75 billion
offer for Macmillan Inc., a publishing company. Previously, it has
participated in buyouts of Taft Broadcasting Co. and Bell & Howell
Inc.
   Wall, in a letter earlier this week to Sen. Donald W. Riegle,
D-Mich., who also had questioned the merchant banking activities,
said they are being permitted to allow the Bass group to ``capture
substantial tax benefits'' of taking over the ailing S&L.
   He noted that 75 percent of the benefits will be funneled back
to the government fund insuring S&L deposits.
   Moreover, Wall said, the agreement with Bass ``will impose
substantial restrictions, more stringent than those imposed by
(California) state law.''
   Some members of Congress fear that the slew of FSLIC notes
issued in recent weeks setting up the insurance fund for a bailout
by taxpayers, with some private analysts pegging the cost of
restoring the industry's health as high as $80 billion.
   However, the bank board says it expects to receive $42 billion
in income over the next decade and to spend only $31 billion.
   The bank board is also being criticized for agreeing to
negotiate exclusively with Bass since April 21. Before that, First
Nationwide Bank, the San Francisco-based S&L subsidiary of Ford
Motor Co., had pursued the acquisition of American for 10 months.
Its executives were upset about being shut out from making another
offer for most of this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
