<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-08 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for grain and soybeans opened
moderately lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting an
increase in farmers' sales of new-crop soybeans at levels near $9 a
bushel, analysts said.
   Soybeans for November delivery advanced to $9.05 a bushel
Wednesday before closing at $8.97. Many farmers who sign forward
contracts to sell their new-crop soybeans to grain elevators found
such levels hard to resist, said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice
president of grain futures trading with Thomson McKinnon Securities
Inc. in New York.
   ``Farmers haven't seen $9 beans for quite a while,'' she said.
   Ms. Leow said soybeans historically have rarely maintained the
$9 level, and she predicted prices would fluctuate within an
$8-to-$9 range until significant new export demand develops.
   The corn and soybean harvests are getting underway, which
typically has a negative impact on prices, she said.
   Some wheat futures rallied Wednesday to match the year's highs
reached earlier this summer but the market could not break through
those levels.
   In early trading today, wheat was 2 cents to 3{ cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.23 a bushel; corn was 3
cents to 3{ cents lower with September at $2.88{ a bushel; December
oats, the only oat contract active in early trading, was 2{ cents
lower at $2.77{ a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 8{ cents lower
with September at $8.77 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .50 cent lower with October at
71.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .55 cent lower
with September at 81.10 cents a pound; hogs were .32 cent lower to
.10 cent higher with October at 38.10 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .27 cent to .75 cent lower with February at 47.35
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
