<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SAfricaSanctions 2ndLd-Writethru f0086 09-08 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica Sanctions, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0086,0767</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf pvs, The committee, to reflect change in
committee plans, moving vote from Tuesday to Wednesday; Also moved
on general newswires</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sanctions Opponents Seeking To Halt Proposed Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee made clear today that it will be difficult, if
not impossible, to build bipartisan support for legislation
imposing new and stern economic sanctions against white-dominated
South Africa.
   And State Department officials suggested that any action on the
measure to institute an almost-total trade embargo on South Africa
and to pull out most U.S. investment might disrupt delicate ongoing
negotiations involving independence for Namibia and the withdrawal
of cuban troops from Angola.
   The committee set a vote for Wednesday on the measure as
statements from individual Republican members indicated the
legislation will not enjoy the wide bipartisan support given the
milder sanctions bill that became law over President Reagan's veto
two years ago.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a key supporter of sanctions
legislation in 1986, called the present bill ``untimely'' and told
the committee, ``There are occasions when legislation is not always
helpful.''
   ``At this moment, to go into a total disruption of our business
in South Africa does not benefit anyone,'' Lugar said, adding that
the measure would remove any leverage the United States has to
bring pressure on South Africa to end its apartheid system of
forced racial separation.
   Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., agreed, saying she does not
believe that comprehensive sanctions will end apartheid.
   ``We simply create havoc,'' she said. ``To strike out alone with
a package that requires complete disinvestment and a total trade
embargo does not behoove us at this time.''
   Speaking for the bill, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said it is
designed to ``increase the costs of maintaining apartheid.''
   ``If we fail to focus on South Africa we will, in essence, allow
the South African regime to declare victory ...,'' Cranston said.
``We have a moral obligation to continue to press for freedom for
all South Africans.''
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., is reportedly ready to submit up to 40
amendments designed to dilute the impact of the legislation during
its examination by the Foreign Relations panel.
   President Reagan is considered highly likely to veto new
sanctions legislation if the Senate follows the lead of the House
and approves a bill blocking most trade with South Africa and
requiring practically a complete withdrawal of U.S. business
investment.
   Cranston and Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., another backer of the
harsh sanctions measure, said on Wednesday they believed the
measure could be brought to the Senate floor for a vote in the
waning days of this year's session, despite a tight legislative
schedule.
   But both said it would be difficult to pass the bill in the
absence of significant Republican support. They said opponents
could make it difficult even to get it past the Foreign Relations
Committee.
   Even if both of those hurdles were cleared, there would not be
enough support to override a veto, they said.
   But any action, even passage by the committee, would ``send a
signal to the government of South Africa that pressure is rising''
against apartheid, Simon said.
   ``I know of no other way to send that signal, other than
sanctions,'' he said.
   Simon said his recent five-day trip to South Africa convinced
him that it is time for the United States to adopt the most
punishing economic sanctions to date as a signal to Pretoria that
its apartheid policies of racial repression must be abandoned.
   ``Blacks are living in despair and hopelessness, and whites are
living in fear,'' Simon told a news conference. ``And the greater
the fear, the more there is repression.''
   ``South Africa is drifting toward massive violence and the
community of nations has to signal to South Africa that peaceful
change has got to come about,'' he said.
   The House bill, passed on Aug. 11 by a vote of 244-132, has
become a focal point of election-year politics. Many Democrats
would like to force the issue in order to portray Republicans who
oppose it as weak on civil and human rights.
   Opponents contend stronger sanctions would impose further
economic hardship on black South Africans and strengthen the
government's resolve to resist pressure for change from outside.
   A more limited sanctions measure was enacted two years ago over
Reagan's veto, an action made possible only with significant GOP
support in both chambers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
