<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower Thursday on the London
Stock Exchange, as the market fretted again over the direction of
domestic interest rates and the overall health of the British
economy.
   By the end of the trading session, the Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100-share index was down 16.3 points, or 0.9 percent, at
1,739.8.
   The index plunged just before midday as much as 27.5 points.
   Volume was 412.5 million shares, up from 310.1 million traded on
Wednesday.
   ``Let's just say it's been a very unsettling day,'' one equity
salesman said.
   Market watchers said additional pressure was placed on share
prices by a cautious survey on the domestic economy from the
Confederation of British Industry and a wobbly start on Wall Street.
   Some dealers said the London market came unhinged when the
British pound turned lower, sparking fears that domestic interest
rates will be pushed higher.
