<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MarriottExpansion     09-08 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marriott Expansion,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marriott To Spend $1 Billion on Residence Inns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marriott Corp. will spend $1 billion over
the next five years to expand its extended-stay lodging centers,
company officials announced Thursday.
   Marriott plans to build 300 Residence Inns nationwide, with most
of the units scheduled for construction in the Northeast, Midwest,
and West.
   Marriott already has 123 Residence Inns, which feature
moderately-priced, all-suite accommodations geared to customers
staying in hotels for five or more nights at a time.
   The new units are scheduled for completion by the early 1990s,
company officials said.
   ``The extended stay traveler who is on the road much of the time
is looking for a place that looks and feels like home,'' said David
H. Rolson, executive vice president and general manager of
Marriott's Residence Inn division.
   Extended-stay travelers now account for more than 50 percent of
the Residence Inn division's business, which Marriott officials
estimate to be more than 7 million customers per year, who average
10 nights or longer per stay.
   Residence Inns are built in a two-story residential style and
include either one or two-bedroom suites. Each comes with complete
kitchens, and many include fireplaces. Swimming pools, health spas
and exercise clubs are also available to lodgers.
</TEXT>
