<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-08 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Close Higher; Wheat Lower; Corn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed strongly higher Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to new drought-damage
estimates while wheat declined and corn was narrowly mixed.
   The crop production estimates of about 30 trading companies
averaged 1.4 billion bushels of soybeans and 4.2 billion bushels of
corn. Those compare with last year's production of 1.9 billion
bushels of soybeans and 7.1 billion bushels of corn.
   The average estimated production declines of 25 percent for
soybeans and 41 percent for corn compare with the Agriculture
Department's August estimates of a 23 percent reduction in the
soybean crop and a 37 percent drop in corn production.
   Strength in the soybean meal market added to the soybean rally,
said Mario Balletto, soybean analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc.
   Wheat declined in reaction to the USDA's rejection of various
offers for export sales, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 6{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.05{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.90{ a bushel;
oats were 2} cents to 3 cents lower with September at $2.66{ a
bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to 15 cents higher with September at
$8.89 a bushel.
</TEXT>
