<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Peachtree-Portman 1stLd-Writethru   09-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peachtree-Portman, 1st Ld-Writethru,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portman Buys Rest Of Peachtree Center</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf ``The towers ...'' to CORRECT that Portman
does not have ownership interest in Hyatt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a $333 million deal believed to be Atlanta's
largest real estate sale, architect and developer John Portman said
Thursday he has bought out the investors in his Peachtree Center
complex, giving him ownership of the project he began piecemeal 27
years ago.
   Portman, who already owned about half of the complex of six
office buildings, two parking decks and a retail mall, said, ``We
have now the potential to go forward much more rapidly'' on other
downtown projects.
   The developer also has projects in New York, Los Angeles,
Detroit, San Francisco, Shanghai and Singapore.
   The Peachtree sale is being financed by Equitable Real Estate
Investment Management Inc., the Atlanta-based subsidiary of
Equitable Life Assurance Society of the United States. Under terms
of the mortgage, Equitable Real Estate Chairman George R. Puskar
said, the company would receive a portion of the revenue from
Peachtree Center as well as an option in 10 years to become half
owner of the project.
   The sale comes at a time when many downtown Atlanta trophy
properties are the objects of investors, mainly foreign, looking to
acquire high-profile real estate.
   In a deal yet to be closed, Sumitomo Life Insurance Co. of Japan
is negotiating to buy the IBM Tower, Atlanta's newest showpiece
skyscraper, for $300 million.
   Other major downtown office properties, including
Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s headquarters tower and Ted Turner's CNN
Center, are known to be for sale.
   Peachtree Center has become the center of downtown Atlanta since
Portman first began putting it together in 1961 with the beginning
of the Atlanta Merchandise Mart, which has been expanded several
times. The Atlanta Market Center now covers 6.2 million square feet.
   The six Peachtree Center office towers account for 2.3 million
square feet of prime office space, 22 percent of the downtown
total. Portman earlier this year also announced the construction of
a seventh tower, a 60-story, $300 million building. A major tenant
for that building has yet to be announced.
   The towers and underground shopping mall are connected via
numerous overhead walkways to the Market Center and three
Portman-designed hotels _ Westin Peachtree Plaza and Marriott
Marquis, in which he maintains an ownership interest, and the Hyatt
Regency.
</TEXT>
