<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hovered in a narrow range
Thursday, showing few shock effects from the latest developments in
Wall Street's insider trading scandal.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 2.67 to 2,063.12.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 8 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
765 up, 677 down and 519 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 149.38 million
shares, up from 139.50 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 174.91 million shares.
   Analysts said no concerted selling appeared in the wake of the
news late Wednesday that the Securities and Exchange Commission had
charged Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and several other parties with
a series of securities violations.
   For one thing, they said, it had long been known and widely
discussed on Wall Street that the investigation leading to the
allegations was under way.
   However, brokers added, it was evident that the market was still
suffering from apathy and caution about the outlook for the economy
and interest rates.
   Some observers have said they were disappointed that the market
has shown little follow-through this week toord of a $10-a-share
bid for the company by a concern controlled by the Pritzker family
of Chicago.
   Browning-Ferris Industries rose { to 27. On Wednesday the
company named William Ruckelshaus, former head of the Environment
Protection Agency, as its chairman and chief executive.
   Among the blue chips, Philip Morris rose ~ to 96} and
International Business Machines added ] to 112[, while Exxon dipped
[ to 45| and General Motors lost [ to 73|.
   Financial Corp. of America plunged | to [, for an 83 percent
drop. The company, whose American Savings & Loan Association is
slated to be taken over in a government-assisted transaction, has
been authorized by its directors to file a petition under Chapter
11 of the federal bankruptcy law.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $3.20 billion, or .12
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .08 to 150.46.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index lost .05 to 304.67, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was up .01 at 265.88.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 1.77 to 379.73. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 297.00, up .64.
