<FILEID>AP-NR-09-08-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ClothingWorkers     09-08 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clothing Workers,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Workers Ratify New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cutters and stitchers of men's clothing ratified
an 18-month contract with major manufacturers that calls for wage
increases and improved health benefits, the Amalgamated Clothing
and Textile Workers Union announced Thursday.
   More than two-thirds of the 15,000 workers covered by the pact
voted in favor of it, according to Jack Sheinkman, ACTWU president.
   The manufacturers, members of the Cotton Garment Allied
Industries Fund, include several big-name makers of men's shirts
and pants including Arrow, Gant and Hathaway and operate factories
throughout the South and Northeast.
   The new contract runs until Feb. 28, 1990, and provides for a
25-cent hourly wage increase in the first year, which is a 4.3
percent increase over the current industry average, and a 15-cent
raise on Sept. 1, 1989.
   Cutters and sewers of men's and boy's shirts and men's sleepwear
currently earn an average of $5.54 an hour, according to the Bureau
of Labor Statistics. The bureau has no wage figures for pants
makers.
   The pact also includes some innovations including a six-week
unpaid parental leave clause, a joint union-employer safety and
health committee to be established at each plant and a special
child care committee to explore establishing child care facilities
wherever feasible.
   The contract is expected to form the basis for other contracts
covering another 27,000 workers whose contracts expire later this
year, Sheinkman said.
</TEXT>
