<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Advances Against Most Major Currencies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar advanced slightly against most major
currencies Thursday after trading in a narrow range while the
market awaited fresh news on the economy.
   Gold prices rose. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
was bid at $428.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $427.50
late Wednesday.
   Currency analysts said there was little news to stir the markets
after last week's higher unemployment figures sent the dollar
tumbling.
   ``Most of the market is on the sidelines waiting for the PPIs
tomorrow and the trades on Wednesday,'' said Ted Wolicki, a trader
with Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. in Chicago. ``I
don't think much will happen until they come out.''
   The Labor Department is scheduled to release statistics Friday
on the Producer Price Index for August, which measures wholesale
prices and is an important indicator of inflation. Next Wednesday,
the Commerce Department will release numbers on the U.S. trade
deficit for July.
   ``The biggest thing the market is looking for are the trade
figures,'' said George Palfi, vice president of foreign exchange
marketing for First Capital Corp. of Chicago. ``As they go, the
dollar will go.''
   Analysts said the dollar tried to move higher Thursday but then
reacted negatively to a Commerce Department statement that a rise
in the U.S. currency would be counterproductive to the U.S. economy.
   The market also reacted negatively to later statements at a
foreign exchange conference in New York that the dollar was headed
downward, analysts said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to a closing 134.20 Japanese yen from
134.30 yen at Wednesday's close. Later, in London, it slipped to
133.75 yen.
   The dollar reversed its slide against the Japanese yen in New
York trading, closing at 133.625 yen, compared with 133.325 late
Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6940 from $1.7060 late
Wednesday. Later, in New Yorkthe pound cost $1.7000, compared with
$1.7080 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Wednesday included: 1.84625 West German marks, up from 1.84125;
1.5571 Swiss francs, up from 1.5530; 1.23975 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.23755; 6.2865 French francs, up from 6.2760; and 1,383.00
Italian lire, up from 1,377.375.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8485 West German marks, up from
1.8435; 1.5600 Swiss francs, up from 1.5545; 6.3025 French francs,
up from 6.2795; 2.0855 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0810; 1,384.50
Italian lire, up from 1,376.50; and 1.2395 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2392.
   Several large buy orders boosted gold bullion, but trading
activity remained limited, dealers said.
   In London, the metal rose to a late bid price of $428, up from
$426.70 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich, it rose to $428.50 from
$427.50 bid late Wednesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at
$430.51, up from $430.19 bid at Wednesday's close.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold also closed up at
$428.80 a troy ounce, compared with $428.10 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $6.58 a troy
ounce, up from $6.52 bid late Wednesday.
   On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery rose to
$6.612 a troy ounce, from Wednesday's $6.546.
</TEXT>
