<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-08 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speculators Push Soybean Futures To 7{-Week High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices registered their highest daily close
since mid-July Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade after new
drought-damage estimates sparked a speculative rally.
   Wheat finished lower and corn futures were mixed.
   On other markets, energy, precious-metals and cocoa futures
gained while livestock, meat and stock-index futures declined.
   The Agriculture Department won't release new crop production
estimates until Monday afternoon. But private predictions issued
Thursday indicate most analysts expect the USDA to again lower its
estimates for the 1988 corn and soybean harvests.
   The estimates of about 30 trading companies averaged 1.4 billion
bushels of soybeans, 25 percent less than last year's production of
1.9 billion bushels, and 4.2 billion bushels of corn, a 41 percent
decline from last year's 7.1 billion bushels.
   The USDA had estimated declines of 23 percent for soybeans and
37 percent for corn in its August crop production report.
   Speculators gave the soybean market its initial push, then
technical traders turned buyers based on the improved chart
signals, analysts said.
   Soybeans for November delivery, the first month for the new-crop
beans, finished at $9.05{ a bushel, the highest close for that
contract since it settled at $9.27 on July 18.
   ``It was a pretty impressive day,'' said Mario Balletto, soybean
analyst in New York with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   Balletto said the strong soybean meal market provided additional
support.
   ``The meal market is very bullish,'' he said. ``Prices are still
too low and that's certainly spilling over.''
   The wheat market ended a 6-day rally, settling lower on
disappointment over slow export sales and reports the Soviet Union
was negotiating a large purchase of European wheat and barley,
analysts said.
   ``We're not the only ones they're buying from and that's kind of
negative,'' said Jerry Gidel, grain analyst in Chicago with the
G.H. Miller division of LIT American Inc.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 5{ cents lower with September at
$4.06{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to } cent higher with
September at $2.90{ a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 3 cents lower
with September at $2.66{ a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 15
cents higher with September at $8.89{ a bushel.
   Oil futures prices rebounded on the New York Mercantile Exchange
after five straight days of declines that had left them at their
lowest point in nearly two years.
   Analysts said the increase was partly technical in nature and
partly caused by a reassessment of the intentions of Saudi Arabia.
   Prices had been knocked down this week by rumors that the Saudis
were offering volume discounts to Japan. But stories Thursday
contradicted those rumors and said any price cuts the Saudis
offered to the Japanese would not be mirrored by price cuts
elsewhere, said Bob Baker, an analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 32 cents
higher with October at $14.48 a barrel; heating oil was .24 cent to
.43 cent higher with October at 41.87 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .25 cent lower to .40 cent higher with October at
42.99 cents a gallon.
   The advance in the oil market helped to boost the
inflation-sensitive precious metals futures, with platinum leading
the way.
   Platinum settled $9.60 to $10.10 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with October at $537.50 a troy ounce.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold was 60 cents to 70 cents
higher with October at $430.80 a troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to
7.2 cents higher with September at $6.612 a troy ounce.
   The battered cocoa market rebounded on reports that discussions
between producer and consumer nation-members of the International
Cocoa Organization were centering on ways to support prices. Some
analysts had expected the two-week meeting in London to accomplish
nothing except to hasten the demise of the price-stabilization
group.
   Cocoa settled $28 to $46 higher with September at $1,219 a
metric ton.
   Cattle futures prices fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in response to denials of Wednesday's rumor that a large
Iowa meatpacker had signed a long-term agreeement to supply beef to
Japan, said Charles Richardson, livestock market analyst in Denver
with Lind Waldock & Co.
   Pork futures retreated in sympathy with cattle, he said.
   Live cattle settled .18 cent to 1.27 cents lower with October at
70.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to 1.37 cents
lower with September at 80.70 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to
.47 cent lower with October at 38.10 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .62 cent to 1.03 cents lower with February at 47.07
cents a pound.
   Stock index futures settled mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. The contract for September delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index was unchanged at 266.10 points.
</TEXT>
