<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Hyatt-Ramada     09-08 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hyatt-Ramada,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hyatt Makes $397 Million Offer for Ramada Inc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyatt Corp. offered Thursday to buy rival
hotelier Ramada Inc. for an estimated $397 million.
   Ramada officials were noncommittal after Hyatt announced its
bid, but investors reacted enthusiastically to the offer, bidding
Ramada stock up $2.12{ a share to $9.75 in New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   Hyatt chief Jay Pritzker made the offer in a letter to Ramada
chairman Richard Snell, Hyatt spokeswoman Karen Rugen said.
   ``We have believed for some time that an affiliation of our
companies would be mutually beneficial,'' Pritzker's letter said.
   Spokesman Joe Cole said the Ramada board would meet to discuss
the offer before the close of business next Friday, the deadline
set by Pritzker in his letter.
   Pritzker's letter said the proposal would expire ``if you have
not indicated a sincere desire on or before'' the deadline set.
   ``Should you choose not to commence a dialogue with us or should
market conditions warrant, we may take unilateral action to
increase our stake in the company or to dispose of any or all or
any part thereof.''
   Neither Cole nor Ms. Rugen could comment beyond company
statements when asked whether the offer was considered hostile.
   Hyatt offered to pay $10 for each of Ramada's 39.7 million
outstanding shares, or a total of $397 million.
   HCC Corp., a Hyatt affiliate, already holds 2.8 million shares,
or 7.2 percent, of Ramada stock, Ms. Rugen said.
   Cole said it has been known for some time that the Pritzker
family, which founded the closely-held Hyatt, has been interested
in Ramada.
   ``The last conversation before this offer (was in) March of this
year,'' he said. At that time, Ramada officials told Hyatt
officials they were not interested, Cole said.
   Pritzker's letter said Hyatt had cash on hand for the
transaction.
   ``Our proposal to acquire all of the equity of the company is
not conditioned upon financing and we have available sufficient
funds to consummate the transactions contemplated hereby,''
Pritzker wrote.
   Ramada companies operate 800 hotels, mostly moderately priced,
in 40 countries. They include Ramada Inns, Rodeway motels and the
upscale Ramada Rennaissance hotels. Ramada also owns 135
restaurants in the Marie Callender's chain, Cole said.
   In 1987, the company had revenue of $226.6 million from hotels,
$406.8 million from gaming operations and $113.1 million from
restaurants, Cole said.
   Hyatt subsidiaries, all owned by the Pritzker family, operate
144 luxury hotels in many major cities worldwide, Ms. Rugen said.
   Hyatt in 1985 announced plans to build 40 hotels by late 1990 in
areas outside the the major cities which had formed the base of its
business.
   Ms. Rugen would not comment Thursday when asked if the proposed
acquisition of Ramada was linked to that plan.
</TEXT>
