<1ST_LINE>u f AM-C&NWStrike 1stLd-Writethru f0153 09-08 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-C&NW Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0153,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union, Railroad Delay Strike Until after Friday Commuter Rush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-6 pvs Simon hoped...for passage with 4 new grafs
to UPDATE with Senate passage. Picks up 7th graf pvs, The
railroad...
^By CLIFF EDWARDS</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Chicago commuters were spared a
morning ``rush-hour nightmare'' when the Chicago & North Western
railway and one of its unions agreed Thurssday to delay a likely
strike.
   ``Both sides agree that this is a step that is in the best
interest of commuters,'' 41,000 of whom use C&NW commuter trains
serving the Chicago area, said David Carle, a spokesman for U.S.
Sen Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   The 2,600 members of the United Transportation Union at the
railroad had planned to walk off their jobs at 12:01 a.m. CDT
Friday, when a 36-day cooling-off period ends and the Chicago &
North Western Transportation Co. had planned to lay off 1,150 of
the 2,300 union brakemen in its 10-state freight operation.
   The Senate late Thursday gave unanimous approval to Simon's bill
implementing recommendations of a presidential emergency board,
which in July called for trimming 689 brakemen.
   President Reagan appointed the panel in April to study the labor
dispute and seek a solution.
   Simon predicted the measure would sail through the House on
Friday and win quick approval from Reagan. He said the bill could
be passed by late morning and signed an hour or so later by the
president.
   Under the Railway Labor act, Congress and the president have
specific authority to settle railroad disputes that threaten
national commerce.
   The railroad and the union have been battling for more than a
year over the size of train crews on C&NW freight trains.
   The company contends the brakemen's jobs are obsolete and that
trains can be run with a two- or three-man crew _ an engineer, a
conductor and, in some cases, a fireman.
   The union contends the brakemen _ two on each train's crew _ are
necessary to maintain railroad safety.
   The two sides have failed to reach a compromise and earlier this
week had implemented strike plans.
   Don Markgraf, UTU general chairman, said he opposes federal
intervention, but that the union would honor the settlement if it
is approved by Congress.
   The railroad expects Congress to push through the legislation,
said C&NW spokesman James Foote, but he noted that management
personnel had been deployed throughout the freight system and about
8,000 replacement workers had been recalled.
   C&NW commuters also were bracing for a walkout _ the third
threatened this year.
   The UTU struck C&NW for about four hours Aug. 4, after an
earlier cooling-off period imposed by President Reagan. During that
period, the special presidential board proposed a compromise to end
the impasse.
   Both sides then rejected the proposal _ the one now going before
Congress _ setting the stage for the August strike.
   Congress, however, ended that strike quickly by imposing a
second cooling-off period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
